rg/10.1186/s12864-015-812-x </ref>\n<ref> Will, I. et al. Genetic underpinnings of host manipulation by Ophiocordyceps as revealed \nby comparative transcriptomics. bioRxiv 2020.01.03.893917 (2020) \ndoi:10.1101/2020.01.03.893917.</ref>\n<ref>Fredericksen, M.A., Zhang, Y., Hazen, M.L., Loreto, R.G., Mangold, C.A., Chen, D.Z. & \nHughes, D.P. 2017: Three-dimensional visualization and a deep-learning model \nreveal complex fungal parasite networks in behaviorally manipulated ants. \u2013 \nProceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America \n114: 12590-12595.</ref>\n<ref>Mongkolsamrit, S., Kobmoo, N., Tasanathai, K., Khonsanit, A., Noisripoom, W., \nSrikitikulchai, P., \u2026 Luangsa-ard, J. J. (2012). Life cycle, host range and \ntemporal variation of Ophiocordyceps unilateralis/Hirsutella formicarum on \nFormicine ants. Journal of Invertebrate Pathology, 111(3), 217\u2013\n224. doi:10.1016/j.jip.2012.08.007 </ref>\n\n<ref>Lin, Yi-Chun, et al. \u201cTwo Distinct Arsenite-Resistant Variants of Leishmania Amazonensis Take Different Routes to Achieve Resistance as Revealed by Comparative Transcriptomics.\u201d Molecular and Biochemical Parasitology, vol. 162, no. 1, Nov. 2008, pp. 16\u201331. DOI.org (Crossref), doi:10.1016/j.molbiopara.2008.06.015.</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://beta.uniprot.org/taxonomy/268505 Ophiocordyceps unilateralis] at [[UniProt]].org. Accessed on 2010-08-22.\n* [http://cordyceps.us/ An Electronic Monograph of Cordyceps and Related Fungi]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q127353}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ophiocordyceps Unilateralis}}\n[[Category:Cordyceps]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1865]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Africa]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fungi of South America]]\n[[Category:Ophiocordycipitaceae]]\n[[Category:Mind-altering parasites]]\n[[Category:Parasitic fungi]]\n[[Category:Suicide-inducing parasitism]]\n", "name_user": "Lenapcrd", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ophiocordyceps_unilateralis"}
{"title_page": "Cosmic Call", "text_new": "[[File:70-\u043c \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u041f-2500 (\u0420\u0422-70).jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[RT-70]] in [[Yevpatoria]]]]'''Cosmic Call''' was the name of two sets of interstellar radio messages that were sent from [[RT-70]] in [[Yevpatoria]], [[Crimea]] in 1999 (Cosmic Call 1) and 2003 (Cosmic Call 2) to various nearby stars. The messages were designed with noise-resistant format and characters.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Oberhaus|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-CWzDwAAQBAJ|title=Extraterrestrial Languages|date=2019-09-27|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-35527-8|location=|pages=99\u2013104|language=en|oclc=1142708941}}</ref>\n\nThe project was funded by Team Encounter, Charlie Chafer (CEO)<ref name=smthsonian>{{cite journal| url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/how-couple-guys-built-most-ambitious-alien-outreach-project-ever-180960473/?no-ist | title= How a Couple of Guys Built the Most Ambitious Alien Outreach Project Ever, History of Cosmic Calls |author= Michael Chorost | journal= Smithsonian | date=September 26, 2016}}</ref> a [[Texas]]-based startup, which went out of business in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cs.astronomy.com/asycs/forums/p/17428/295175.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515102750/http://cs.astronomy.com/asycs/forums/p/17428/295175.aspx |archivedate=2009-05-15 }}</ref>\n\nBoth transmissions were at ~150&nbsp;kW, 5.01&nbsp;GHz ([[Frequency-shift_keying | FSK]] +/-24&nbsp;kHz).<ref name=CC2>{{ cite web | url=http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/CosmicCall-2003/index.html | title = Synthesis and Transmission of Cosmic Call 2003 Interstellar Radio Message | author=Richard Braastad, Team Encounter, USA, Alexander Zaitsev, IRE RAS, Russia}}}</ref>\n\n==Message structure==\n\nEach '''Cosmic Call 1''' session had the following structure. The Scientific Part (DDM, BM, AM, and ESM) was sent three times (at 100 bit/s),<ref name=RC1>[http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/report-1999.html  \"Broadcast for Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence from Evpatoria Deep Space Center\" Report on Cosmic Call 1999]</ref> and the Public Part (PP) was sent once (at 2000 bit/s),<ref name=RC1/> according to the following arrangement:\n\n:DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; PP,\n\nwhere DDM is the [http://www.plover.com/misc/Dumas-Dutil/messages.pdf Dutil-Dumas Message], created by Canadian scientists [[Yvan Dutil]] and [[St\u00e9phane Dumas (astrophysicist)|St\u00e9phane Dumas]], BM is the Braastad Message, AM is the [[Arecibo Message]], and ESM is the Encounter 2001 Staff Message.<ref name=RC1/>\n\nEach '''Cosmic Call 2''' session in 2003 had the following structure:\n\n:DDM2 &rarr; DDM2 &rarr; DDM2 &rarr; AM &rarr; AM &rarr; AM &rarr; BIG &rarr; BIG &rarr; BIG &rarr; BM &rarr; ESM &rarr; PP,\n\nwhere DDM2 is modernized DDM (aka [[Interstellar Rosetta Stone]], ISR), BIG is [[Bilingual Image Glossary]].<ref name=CC2/>  All but the PP were transmitted at 400 bit/s<ref name=CC2/>\n\nThe ISR was 263,906 bits; BM, 88,687 bits, AM, 1,679 bits; BIG was 12 binary images 121,301 bits; ESM 24,899 bits.  Total = 500,472 bits for 53 minutes.  PP was 220 megabytes and sent at a rate of 100,000 bit/s for 11 hours total.<ref name=CC2/>\n\n==Stars targeted==\nThe messages were sent to the following stars:<ref name=\"cplire.ru\">[http://www.cplire.ru/rus/ra&sr/VAK-2004.html \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0443\u043c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u043e \u0412\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Name\n! Designation [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]\n! Constellation\n! Date sent\n! Arrival date\n! Message\n|- align=center\n| [[16 Cygni|16 Cyg A]]|| [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 186408 || [[Cygnus (constellation)|Cygnus]] || May 24, 1999|| November 2069||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| [[15 Sagittae|15 Sge]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 190406 || [[Sagitta]] || June 30, 1999|| February 2057||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 178428 || [[Sagitta]] || June 30, 1999|| October 2067||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| [[Gliese 777|Gl 777]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 190360 || [[Cygnus (constellation)|Cygnus]] || July 1, 1999|| April 2051||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| || [[Hipparcos Catalogue|Hip]] 4872 || [[Cassiopeia (constellation)|Cassiopeia]] || July 6, 2003|| April 2036||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 245409 || [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]] || July 6, 2003|| August 2040||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| [[55 Cancri|55 Cnc]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 75732 || [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]] || July 6, 2003|| May 2044||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| || [[HD 10307]] || [[Andromeda (constellation)|Andromeda]] || July 6, 2003|| September 2044||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| [[47 Ursae Majoris|47 UMa]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 95128 || [[Ursa Major]] || July 6, 2003|| May 2049||Cosmic Call 2\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arecibo message]]\n* [[Active SETI]]\n* [[Communication with extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n* [[Interstellar messages]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [https://www.fourmilab.ch/goldberg/setimsg.html Self-Decoding Messages]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223524/http://www.activeseti.org/evpatoria.html Discussion of the Call's \"Rosetta Stone\" and how it was developed\n* [http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/report-1999.html Report on Cosmic Call]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20121001045355/http://www3.sympatico.ca/stephane_dumas/CETI/evpatoria.html Evpatoria 2003 discussion with bitmap and image\n\n\n{{Interstellar messages}}\n\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Interstellar messages]]\n[[Category:Time capsules]]\n[[Category:1999 in science]]\n[[Category:2003 in science]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:1999 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:2003 in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:70-\u043c \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u041f-2500 (\u0420\u0422-70).jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[RT-70]] in [[Yevpatoria]]]]'''Cosmic Call''' was the name of two sets of interstellar radio messages that were sent from [[RT-70]] in [[Yevpatoria]], [[Crimea]] in 1999 (Cosmic Call 1) and 2003 (Cosmic Call 2) to various nearby stars. The messages were designed with noise-resistant format and characters.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Oberhaus|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-CWzDwAAQBAJ|title=Extraterrestrial Languages|date=2019-09-27|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-35527-8|location=|pages=99\u2013104|language=en|oclc=1142708941}}</ref>\n\nThe project was funded by Team Encounter, Charlie Chafer (CEO) <ref name=smthsonian>{{cite journal| url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/how-couple-guys-built-most-ambitious-alien-outreach-project-ever-180960473/?no-ist | title= How a Couple of Guys Built the Most Ambitious Alien Outreach Project Ever, History of Cosmic Calls |author= Michael Chorost | journal= Smithsonian | date=September 26, 2016}}</ref> a [[Texas]]-based startup, which went out of business in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cs.astronomy.com/asycs/forums/p/17428/295175.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515102750/http://cs.astronomy.com/asycs/forums/p/17428/295175.aspx |archivedate=2009-05-15 }}</ref>\n\nBoth transmissions were at ~150&nbsp;kW, 5.01&nbsp;GHz ([[Frequency-shift_keying | FSK]] +/-24&nbsp;kHz).<ref name=CC2>{{ cite web | url=http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/CosmicCall-2003/index.html | title = Synthesis and Transmission of Cosmic Call 2003 Interstellar Radio Message | author=Richard Braastad, Team Encounter, USA, Alexander Zaitsev, IRE RAS, Russia}}}</ref>\n\n==Message structure==\n\nEach '''Cosmic Call 1''' session had the following structure. The Scientific Part (DDM, BM, AM, and ESM) was sent three times (at 100 bit/s),<ref name=RC1>[http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/report-1999.html  \"Broadcast for Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence from Evpatoria Deep Space Center\" Report on Cosmic Call 1999]</ref> and the Public Part (PP) was sent once (at 2000 bit/s),<ref name=RC1/> according to the following arrangement:\n\n:DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; DDM &rarr; BM &rarr; AM &rarr; ESM &rarr; PP,\n\nwhere DDM is the [http://www.plover.com/misc/Dumas-Dutil/messages.pdf Dutil-Dumas Message], created by Canadian scientists [[Yvan Dutil]] and [[St\u00e9phane Dumas (astrophysicist)|St\u00e9phane Dumas]], BM is the Braastad Message, AM is the [[Arecibo Message]], and ESM is the Encounter 2001 Staff Message.<ref name=RC1/>\n\nEach '''Cosmic Call 2''' session in 2003 had the following structure:\n\n:DDM2 &rarr; DDM2 &rarr; DDM2 &rarr; AM &rarr; AM &rarr; AM &rarr; BIG &rarr; BIG &rarr; BIG &rarr; BM &rarr; ESM &rarr; PP,\n\nwhere DDM2 is modernized DDM (aka [[Interstellar Rosetta Stone]], ISR), BIG is [[Bilingual Image Glossary]].<ref name=CC2/>  All but the PP were transmitted at 400 bit/s<ref name=CC2/>\n\nThe ISR was 263,906 bits; BM, 88,687 bits, AM, 1,679 bits; BIG was 12 binary images 121,301 bits; ESM 24,899 bits.  Total = 500,472 bits for 53 minutes.  PP was 220 megabytes and sent at a rate of 100,000 bit/s for 11 hours total.<ref name=CC2/>\n\n==Stars targeted==\nThe messages were sent to the following stars:<ref name=\"cplire.ru\">[http://www.cplire.ru/rus/ra&sr/VAK-2004.html \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0443\u043c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432\u043e \u0412\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Name\n! Designation [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]\n! Constellation\n! Date sent\n! Arrival date\n! Message\n|- align=center\n| [[16 Cygni|16 Cyg A]]|| [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 186408 || [[Cygnus (constellation)|Cygnus]] || May 24, 1999|| November 2069||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| [[15 Sagittae|15 Sge]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 190406 || [[Sagitta]] || June 30, 1999|| February 2057||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 178428 || [[Sagitta]] || June 30, 1999|| October 2067||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| [[Gliese 777|Gl 777]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 190360 || [[Cygnus (constellation)|Cygnus]] || July 1, 1999|| April 2051||Cosmic Call 1\n|- align=center\n| || [[Hipparcos Catalogue|Hip]] 4872 || [[Cassiopeia (constellation)|Cassiopeia]] || July 6, 2003|| April 2036||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 245409 || [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]] || July 6, 2003|| August 2040||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| [[55 Cancri|55 Cnc]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 75732 || [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]] || July 6, 2003|| May 2044||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| || [[HD 10307]] || [[Andromeda (constellation)|Andromeda]] || July 6, 2003|| September 2044||Cosmic Call 2\n|- align=center\n| [[47 Ursae Majoris|47 UMa]] || [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]] 95128 || [[Ursa Major]] || July 6, 2003|| May 2049||Cosmic Call 2\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arecibo message]]\n* [[Active SETI]]\n* [[Communication with extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n* [[Interstellar messages]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [https://www.fourmilab.ch/goldberg/setimsg.html Self-Decoding Messages]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223524/http://www.activeseti.org/evpatoria.html Discussion of the Call's \"Rosetta Stone\" and how it was developed\n* [http://www.cplire.ru/html/ra&sr/irm/report-1999.html Report on Cosmic Call]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20121001045355/http://www3.sympatico.ca/stephane_dumas/CETI/evpatoria.html Evpatoria 2003 discussion with bitmap and image\n\n\n{{Interstellar messages}}\n\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Interstellar messages]]\n[[Category:Time capsules]]\n[[Category:1999 in science]]\n[[Category:2003 in science]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:1999 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:2003 in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "Wingman4l7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:-- rm space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmic_Call"}
{"title_page": "List of war deities", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect2|God of war|War gods|other uses|God of War (disambiguation)|and|War Gods (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{cleanup rewrite|date=August 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2013}}\n}}\n[[File:0 Statue de Mars (Pyrrhus) - Musei Capitolini - MC0058 (2).JPG|thumb|[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], the Roman god of war]]\n[[File:Sarutahiko \u014ckami.crop.4.wp.working.print.png|thumb|Sarutahiko.]]\n\nA '''war god''' in [[mythology]] associated with war, [[combat]], or bloodshed. They occur commonly in both [[monotheism|monotheistic]] and [[polytheism|polytheistic]] religions.\n\nUnlike most gods and goddesses in polytheistic religions, monotheistic deities have traditionally been portrayed in their mythologies as commanding war in order to spread their religion. (The intimate connection between \"[[Religious war|holy war]]\" and the \"one true god\" belief of monotheism has been noted by many scholars, including [[Jonathan Kirsch]] in his book ''God Against The Gods: The History of the War Between Monotheism and Polytheism'' and Joseph Campbell in ''The Masks of God, Vol. 3: Occidental Mythology''.) <ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=God Against the Gods: The History of the War Between Monotheism and Polytheism|author=Kirsch, J.|date=2004|publisher=Viking Compass|isbn=9780670032860|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780965916776|url-access=registration|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref><ref name=\"amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/014019441X|title=Occidental Mythology (Masks of God): Joseph Campbell: 9780140194418: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of war deities:\n\n== Africa and the Middle East ==\n=== Sub-Sahara Africa === \n==== Nilo-Saharan ==== \n'''Nubian'''\n*[[Apedemak]], [[Nubia]]n lion-headed warrior god.\n\n==== Kenya ====\n'''Kalenjin'''\n*[[Boryet]], [[Kipsigis people|Kipsigis]] Death-wielding god of war. Boryet (also luket) is the act of war. Death (Me'et) is observed as a consequence of war. War is thus personified as such.\n\n==== Western Niger-Congo ==== \n'''Yoruba'''\n*[[Kokou)|Kokou]]\n*[[Ogoun]] \n*[[Oya]]\n\n=== Afroasiatic Middle East ===\n\n==== Berber ====\n*[[Gurzil]], bull-headed warrior god.<ref> Morris, Arnold Hugh Martin Jones, John Robert: The Prosopography of the Later Roman Empire p. 612</ref>\n*Ifri, war goddess\n\n==== Canaanite ==== \n*[[Anat]], goddess of war\n*[[Astarte]], goddess of sex and war, western Semitic version of the Mesopotamian [[Ishtar]] and [[Inanna]]\n*[[Resheph]], god of plague and war\n*[[Tanit]], main Carthaginian goddess whose functions included war and the moon, a composite of Anat and Astarte/Ishtar/Inanna\n\n==== Egyptian ==== \n*[[Anhur]], god of war, not a native god\n*[[Bastet (mythology)|Bast]], cat-headed goddess associated with war, protection of [[Lower Egypt]] and the [[pharaoh]], the sun, perfumes, ointments, and embalming\n*[[Horus]], god of the king, the sky, war, and protection\n*[[Maahes]], lion-headed god of war\n*[[Menhit]], goddess of war, \"she who massacres\"\n*[[Montu]], [[falcon]]-headed god of war, valor, and the Sun\n*[[Neith]], goddess of war, hunting, and wisdom\n*[[Pakhet]], goddess of war\n*[[Satet|Satis]], deification of the floods of the [[Nile River]] and an early war, hunting, and fertility goddess\n*[[Sekhmet]], goddess of warfare, pestilence, and the desert\n*[[Set (mythology)|Set]], god of the desert and storms, associated with war\n*[[Sobek]], god of the Nile, the army, military, fertility, and crocodiles\n*[[Sopdu]], god of the scorching heat of the summer sun, associated with war\n*[[Wepwawet]], wolf-god of war and death who later became associated with [[Anubis]] and the afterlife\n\n==== Ethiopian ==== \n*[[Maher (god)|Maher]], god of war.\n\n==== Mesopotamian ==== \n*[[Agasaya]], \"the Shrieker\", goddess of war\n*[[Belus (Babylonian)|Belus]], [[Babylonian mythology|Babylonian]] god of war\n*[[Inanna]], [[Sumerian religion|Sumerian]] goddess of  fertility, sex and war\n*[[Ishtar]], [[Assyria]]n, Akkadian, and Babylonian counterpart to Inanna\n*[[Nergal]], [[Babylonian mythology|Babylonian]] god of war, fire, the underworld, and pestilence\n*[[Pap-nigin-gara]], [[Akkadian Empire|Akkad]]ian and Babylonian god of war\n*[[Sebitti]], group of minor Akkadian and Babylonian war gods\n*[[Shala]], Akkadian and Babylonian goddess of war and grain\n*[[Shara (god)|Shara]], minor Sumerian god of war\n*[[Shulmanu]], god of the underworld, fertility, and war\n\n== Western Eurasia ==\n\n=== Balto-Slavic ===\n\n==== Baltic ==== \n* Kara M\u0101te, Latvian goddess of war\n* Kauriraris, Lithuanian god of war and war steeds\n* Junda, Lithuanian goddess of war\n\n==== Slavic ==== \n*[[Jarovit]], god of vegetation, fertility, and spring, also associated with war and harvest\n*[[Perun]], god of thunder and lightning, associated with war\n*[[Svetovid]], god of war, fertility, and abundance\n*[[Zorya|Zorya Utrennyaya]], goddess of the morning star, sometimes depicted as a warrior goddess who protected men in battle\n\n\n=== Celtic ===\n*[[Agrona]], reconstructed [[Proto-Celtic]] name for the [[river Aeron]] in [[Wales]], and possibly the name of an associated war goddess\n*[[Alaisiagae]], a pair of goddesses worshiped in [[Roman Britain]], with parallel Celtic and Germanic titles\n*[[Andarta]], Brittonic goddess theorized to be associated with victory, overcoming enemies, war\n*[[Andraste]], [[Gaulish]] warrior goddess\n*[[Anann]], [[Irish mythology|Irish]] goddess of war, death, predicting death in battle, cattle, prosperity, and fertility\n*[[Badb]], Irish goddess of war who took the form of a crow; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[Bandua]], Gallaecian God of War\n*[[Belatucadros]], war god worshipped by soldiers and equated with the Roman war god [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]]\n*[[Camulus]], god of war of the Belgic [[Remi]] and British [[Trinovantes]]\n*[[Catubodua]], Gaulish goddess assumed to be associated with victory\n*[[Cicolluis]], Gaulish and Irish god associated with war\n*[[Cocidius]], [[Romano-British]] god associated with war, hunting and forests\n*[[Macha]], Irish goddess associated with war, horses, and [[sovereignty goddess|sovereignty]]; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[The Morr\u00edgan]], Irish [[triple deity|triple goddess]] associated with [[sovereignty goddess|sovereignty]], prophecy, war, and death on the battlefield\n*[[Neit]], Irish god of war, husband of Nemain of Badb\n*[[Nemain]], Irish goddess of the frenzied havoc of war; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[Rudianos]], Gaulish god of war\n*[[Segomo]], Gaulish god of war\n*[[Teutates]], British and Gaulish god of war and the tribe\n==== Lusitanian ====\n*[[Neto (deity)|Neto]], god believed to be associated with war, death, and weaponry\n\n=== Norse-Germanic ===\n[[File:Idise by Emil Doepler.jpg|thumb|Idise by Emil Doepler.]]\n==== Continental Germanic ====\n*[[Baduhenna]], a western Frisii goddess of warfare\n*[[Idis (Germanic)]]/itis/ides, the West Germanic cognates of North Germanic ''d\u00eds'', they are connected with battle magic and fettering enemy armies\n*[[Sandraudiga]], goddess whose name may mean \"she who dyes the sand red\", suggesting she is a war deity or at least has a warrior aspect\n*[[T\u00fdr]], god of war, single combat, law, justice, and the [[thing (assembly)|thing]], who later lost much of his religious importance and mythical role to the god W\u014dden\n*[[W\u014dden]], god associated with wisdom, poetry, war, victory, and death\n\n==== Norse ====\n*[[D\u00eds]], a group of lesser goddesses who are sometimes connected with battle magic; valkyrie may be a [[kenning]] for them\n*[[Freyja]], goddess associated with love, beauty, fertility, gold, [[sei\u00f0r]], war, and death\n*[[Odin]], god associated with wisdom, war, battle, and death\n*[[T\u00fdr]], god associated with law, justice, victory, and heroic glory\n*[[Ullr]], god associated with archery, skiing, bows, hunting, single combat, and glory\n*[[Valkyrie]]s, choosers of the slain and connected to Odin, ruler of Valhalla; they may be the same as the d\u00eds above\n\n=== Graeco-Roman ===\n==== Greek / Hellenic ====\n*[[Alala]], spirit of the war cry\n*[[Alke]], spirit of courage and battle-strength\n*[[Amphillogiai]], goddesses of disputes\n*[[Androktasiai]], spirits of battlefield slaughter\n*[[Ares]], the main Greek god of war, despised by all the city-states except Sparta\n*[[Athena]], goddess of wisdom, war strategy, and weaving, more beloved by ancient Greeks than Ares and tutelary deity of Athens, Sparta's rival\n*[[Bia (mythology)|Bia]], spirit of force and compulsion\n*[[Deimos (mythology)|Deimos]], personification of terror\n*[[Enyalius]], god of war; in early periods apparently an epithet of Ares, they were differentiated later\n*[[Enyo]], goddess of war, sometimes appears to be identical to Eris\n*[[Eris (mythology)|Eris]], goddess of discord and strife\n*[[Hera]], in the ''[[Illiad]]'' she has a martial character and fights (and wins) against Artemis; however, this warlike aspect of her appears nowhere else in the surviving corpus, suggesting it was dropped early on\n*[[Homados]], spirit of the din of battle\n*[[Hysminai]], female spirits of fighting and combat\n*[[Ioke (mythology)|Ioke]], spirit of onslaught, battle-tumult, and pursuit\n*[[Keres (Greek mythology)|Keres]], female spirits of violent or cruel death, including death in battle, by accident, murder, or ravaging disease\n*[[Kratos (mythology)|Kratos]], personification of strength and power\n*[[Kydoimos]], spirit of the din of battle\n*[[Makhai]], male spirits of fighting and combat\n*[[Nike (mythology)|Nike]], spirit of victory\n*[[Palioxis]], spirit of backrush, flight, and retreat from battle\n*[[Pallas (Titan)|Pallas]], Titan god of war-craft and of the springtime campaign season\n*[[Perses (Titan)|Perses]], the Titan of destruction\n*[[Phobos (mythology)|Phobos]], spirit of panic, fear, flight, and battlefield rout\n*[[Phonoi]], spirits of murder, killing, and slaughter\n*[[Polemos]], spirit of war\n*[[Proioxis]], spirit of onrush and battlefield pursuit\n\n==== Roman ====\n[[File:Juno Sospita Statue.jpg|thumb|Juno Sospita Statue holding a spear and shield.]]\n*[[Bellona (goddess)|Bellona]], goddess of war\n*[[Honos]], god of chivalry, honor, and military justice\n*[[Juno (mythology)|Juno]], has a consistent martial character and the patron goddess of Rome, the mother of Mars and Bellona\n*[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], god of war and agriculture, equivalent to Ares as far as being war gods; aside from this they have very little in common\n*[[Minerva]], goddess of wisdom, medicine, music, crafts, and war, while somewhat equivalent to the Greek Athena, the Romans did not emphasize her war aspect like the Greeks did\n*[[Nerio]], warrior goddess and personification of valor\n*[[Victoria (mythology)|Victoria]], personification of victory, equivalent to the Greek goddess Nike\n*[[Virtus (deity)|Virtus]], god of bravery and military strength\n'''Etruscan'''\n*[[Laran]], god of war.\n*[[Menrva]], goddess of war, art, wisdom, and health\n\n=== Balkan ===\n*Danubian Rider\n*[[Sabazios]]\n*[[Thracian Rider]]\n\n=== Western Asia === \n==== Armenian ====\n*[[Anahit]], goddess of healing, fertility, wisdom, and water; in early periods associated with war\n==== Hittite ====\n*[[Shaushka]], goddess of fertility, war, and healing\n*[[Wurrukatte]], god of war\n\n==== Hindu-Vedic ====\n[[File:Kartikeya War of God by Surendra Nath Ganguly 1913.jpg|thumb|Kartikeya, god of war by Surendra Nath Ganguly, 1913.]]\n*[[Kartikeya]], god of war and battle\n*[[Mangala]], god of war\n*[[Nirrti]], goddess of strife\n*[[Parvati]], her forms [[Durga]] and [[Kali]] are known for fighting demons\n*[[Shiva]], several of his avatars are gods of avenging and destroying \n*[[Vishnu]], god of protection. Several of his avatars are associated with fighting and vanquishing evil.\n*[[Indra]], god of power, kingship, thunder, rains, electricity and the senses.\n==== Nuristani ====\n*[[Great Gish]], god of war\n\n=== Uralic === \n==== Hungarian ====\n*[[Had\u00far]], god of war and the metalsmith of the gods\n\n== Asia-Pacific / Oceania ==\n=== Turkic === \n*[[Kyzaghan]], Turkic deity of war\n=== Mongolian === \n*[[Dayisun Tngri]]\n\n=== Far East Asia === \n==== Chinese ====\n[[File:FS KwanKung 60116.jpg|thumb|[[Guan Yu]], Chinese god of loyalty, righteousness, and valor.]]\n* Ba Yikao, Pole Star of Purple Subtlety Emperor. God of Military Outcomes\n* [[Chiyou]], god of war\n* [[Di Qing]], Star of Military Fortune, God of Valor\n* [[Erlang Shen]], a three-eyed warrior\n* [[Guan Yu]], Han dynasty general. God of loyalty, righteousness, and valor. \n* [[Jinzha]], marshal of the center altar\n* [[Jiutian Xuann\u00fc]], goddess of war, sex, and longevity <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cahill|first1=Suzanne E.|title=Sublimation in Medieval China: The Case of the Mysterious Woman of the Nine Heavens|journal=Journal of Chinese Religions|date=18 July 2013|volume=20|issue=1|pages=91\u2013102|doi=10.1179/073776992805307692}}</ref>\n* [[Li Jing (deity)|Li Jing]], Guardian of Celestial Palace\n* [[Muzha (deity)|Muzha]], marshal of the center altar\n* [[Nezha]]\n* Wang Shan, Song dynasty general. Primordial Lord-General of Heaven. Guardian of Celestial Palace\n* Wen Qiong <ref>http://etheses.lib.cuhk.edu.hk/pdf/004777762.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Yue Fei]]\n* Zhao Lang ([[Zhao Gongming]]), God of Military Fortune, Guardian of Celestial Palace, Protector of Households\n\n==== Japanese ====\n*[[Futsunushi]], god of swords, martial arts, and conquest; god of the Mononobe clan\n*[[Hachiman]] Daimy\u014djin, [[Shinto]] god of war (on land) and agriculture, divine protector of the Minamoto clan; mostly worshiped by samurai\n*[[Sarutahiko]], god of war and misogi; the deity who stands at the junction of Heaven and Earth; one of the main Kunitsukami; actively worshipped by Ueshiba Morihei\n*[[Takemikazuchi]], god of war, conquest, martial arts, [[sumo]], and lightning; general of the Amatsukami; god of Kashima and [[Ujigami]] of Nakatomi clan\n*[[Takeminakata|Suwa My\u014djin (Takeminakata-no-kami)]], god of valor and duty, protector of the Japanese religion\n*[[Vai\u015brava\u1e47a|Bishamonten]], Buddhist god of war\n\n=== Southeast Asia === \n==== Vietnamese ====\n*[[Cao L\u1ed7]], god of military innovations\n*\u0110\u1ed9c C\u01b0\u1edbc, the protector of coastal settlements. Legend has it that he split himself in two with his axe, each half guards coastal villages against sea ogres.\n*Th\u1ea7n \u0110\u1ed3ng C\u1ed5, the armored protector of the [[L\u00fd dynasty]]\n*[[Th\u00e1nh Gi\u00f3ng]], god of triumph over foreign invaders\n\n=== Polynesian === \n*[['Oro]], god of war\n*[[Rongo]], [[Mangaia|Mangaian]] god of war and taro\n==== Hawaiian ====\n*[[K\u016b]], god of war and birds\n*[[Pele (deity)|Pele]], goddess of fire, lightning, dance, volcanoes, and violence\n==== M\u0101ori ====\n*[[Maru (mythology)|Maru]], god of war and fresh water\n*[[T\u016bmatauenga]], god of war and human activities\n\n== Native Americas ==\n=== North America === \n==== Great Plains ====\n*Morning Star, O-pi-ri-kus by one spelling; the god of war in [[Pawnee mythology]]\n==== Pacific Northwest ====\n*[[Qamaits]], [[Nuxalk Nation|Nux\u00e1lk]] warrior goddess\n*[[Winalagalis]], [[Kwakwaka'wakw]] god of war\n\n=== Central American and the Caribbean === \n==== Aztec ====\n*Patterns of War\n* [[Huitzilopochtli]], god of will, patron of war, fire, and sun; lord of the south\n** [[Mixcoatl]], god of war and hunting\n** [[Tlaloc]], god of thunder, rain, and earthquakes\n** [[Xipe-Totec]], god of force, patron of war, agriculture, vegetation, diseases, seasons, rebirth, hunting, trades, and spring; lord of the east\n** [[Xiuhtecuhtli]], god of fire\n==== Mayan ====\n*[[Tohil]], god associated with fire, the sun, rain, mountains, and war\n==== [[Haitian Vodou|Voodoo]] ====\n*[[Ogoun]], loa who presides over fire, iron, hunting, politics, and war\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{List of mythological figures by region}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of War Deities}}\n[[Category:Lists of deities|War]]\n[[Category:War deities| ]]\n[[Category:War in mythology| Deities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect2|God of war|War gods|other uses|God of War (disambiguation)|and|War Gods (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{cleanup rewrite|date=August 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2013}}\n}}\n[[File:0 Statue de Mars (Pyrrhus) - Musei Capitolini - MC0058 (2).JPG|thumb|[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], the Roman god of war]]\n[[File:Sarutahiko \u014ckami.crop.4.wp.working.print.png|thumb|Sarutahiko.]]\n\nA '''war god''' in [[mythology]] associated with war, [[combat]], or bloodshed. They occur commonly in both [[monotheism|monotheistic]] and [[polytheism|polytheistic]] religions.\n\nUnlike most gods and goddesses in polytheistic religions, monotheistic deities have traditionally been portrayed in their mythologies as commanding war in order to spread their religion. (The intimate connection between \"[[Religious war|holy war]]\" and the \"one true god\" belief of monotheism has been noted by many scholars, including [[Jonathan Kirsch]] in his book ''God Against The Gods: The History of the War Between Monotheism and Polytheism'' and Joseph Campbell in ''The Masks of God, Vol. 3: Occidental Mythology''.) <ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=God Against the Gods: The History of the War Between Monotheism and Polytheism|author=Kirsch, J.|date=2004|publisher=Viking Compass|isbn=9780670032860|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780965916776|url-access=registration|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref><ref name=\"amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/014019441X|title=Occidental Mythology (Masks of God): Joseph Campbell: 9780140194418: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of war deities:\n\n== Africa and the Middle East ==\n=== Sub-Sahara Africa === \n==== Nilo-Saharan ==== \n'''Nubian'''\n*[[Apedemak]], [[Nubia]]n lion-headed warrior god.\n\n==== Kenya ====\n'''Kalenjin'''\n*[[Boryet]], [[Kipsigis]] Death-wielding god of war. Boryet (also luket) is the act of war. Death (Me'et) is observed as a consequence of war. War is thus personified as such.\n\n==== Western Niger-Congo ==== \n'''Yoruba'''\n*[[Kokou)|Kokou]]\n*[[Ogoun]] \n*[[Oya]]\n\n=== Afroasiatic Middle East ===\n\n==== Berber ====\n*[[Gurzil]], bull-headed warrior god.<ref> Morris, Arnold Hugh Martin Jones, John Robert: The Prosopography of the Later Roman Empire p. 612</ref>\n*Ifri, war goddess\n\n==== Canaanite ==== \n*[[Anat]], goddess of war\n*[[Astarte]], goddess of sex and war, western Semitic version of the Mesopotamian [[Ishtar]] and [[Inanna]]\n*[[Resheph]], god of plague and war\n*[[Tanit]], main Carthaginian goddess whose functions included war and the moon, a composite of Anat and Astarte/Ishtar/Inanna\n\n==== Egyptian ==== \n*[[Anhur]], god of war, not a native god\n*[[Bastet (mythology)|Bast]], cat-headed goddess associated with war, protection of [[Lower Egypt]] and the [[pharaoh]], the sun, perfumes, ointments, and embalming\n*[[Horus]], god of the king, the sky, war, and protection\n*[[Maahes]], lion-headed god of war\n*[[Menhit]], goddess of war, \"she who massacres\"\n*[[Montu]], [[falcon]]-headed god of war, valor, and the Sun\n*[[Neith]], goddess of war, hunting, and wisdom\n*[[Pakhet]], goddess of war\n*[[Satet|Satis]], deification of the floods of the [[Nile River]] and an early war, hunting, and fertility goddess\n*[[Sekhmet]], goddess of warfare, pestilence, and the desert\n*[[Set (mythology)|Set]], god of the desert and storms, associated with war\n*[[Sobek]], god of the Nile, the army, military, fertility, and crocodiles\n*[[Sopdu]], god of the scorching heat of the summer sun, associated with war\n*[[Wepwawet]], wolf-god of war and death who later became associated with [[Anubis]] and the afterlife\n\n==== Ethiopian ==== \n*[[Maher (god)|Maher]], god of war.\n\n==== Mesopotamian ==== \n*[[Agasaya]], \"the Shrieker\", goddess of war\n*[[Belus (Babylonian)|Belus]], [[Babylonian mythology|Babylonian]] god of war\n*[[Inanna]], [[Sumerian religion|Sumerian]] goddess of  fertility, sex and war\n*[[Ishtar]], [[Assyria]]n, Akkadian, and Babylonian counterpart to Inanna\n*[[Nergal]], [[Babylonian mythology|Babylonian]] god of war, fire, the underworld, and pestilence\n*[[Pap-nigin-gara]], [[Akkadian Empire|Akkad]]ian and Babylonian god of war\n*[[Sebitti]], group of minor Akkadian and Babylonian war gods\n*[[Shala]], Akkadian and Babylonian goddess of war and grain\n*[[Shara (god)|Shara]], minor Sumerian god of war\n*[[Shulmanu]], god of the underworld, fertility, and war\n\n== Western Eurasia ==\n\n=== Balto-Slavic ===\n\n==== Baltic ==== \n* Kara M\u0101te, Latvian goddess of war\n* Kauriraris, Lithuanian god of war and war steeds\n* Junda, Lithuanian goddess of war\n\n==== Slavic ==== \n*[[Jarovit]], god of vegetation, fertility, and spring, also associated with war and harvest\n*[[Perun]], god of thunder and lightning, associated with war\n*[[Svetovid]], god of war, fertility, and abundance\n*[[Zorya|Zorya Utrennyaya]], goddess of the morning star, sometimes depicted as a warrior goddess who protected men in battle\n\n\n=== Celtic ===\n*[[Agrona]], reconstructed [[Proto-Celtic]] name for the [[river Aeron]] in [[Wales]], and possibly the name of an associated war goddess\n*[[Alaisiagae]], a pair of goddesses worshiped in [[Roman Britain]], with parallel Celtic and Germanic titles\n*[[Andarta]], Brittonic goddess theorized to be associated with victory, overcoming enemies, war\n*[[Andraste]], [[Gaulish]] warrior goddess\n*[[Anann]], [[Irish mythology|Irish]] goddess of war, death, predicting death in battle, cattle, prosperity, and fertility\n*[[Badb]], Irish goddess of war who took the form of a crow; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[Bandua]], Gallaecian God of War\n*[[Belatucadros]], war god worshipped by soldiers and equated with the Roman war god [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]]\n*[[Camulus]], god of war of the Belgic [[Remi]] and British [[Trinovantes]]\n*[[Catubodua]], Gaulish goddess assumed to be associated with victory\n*[[Cicolluis]], Gaulish and Irish god associated with war\n*[[Cocidius]], [[Romano-British]] god associated with war, hunting and forests\n*[[Macha]], Irish goddess associated with war, horses, and [[sovereignty goddess|sovereignty]]; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[The Morr\u00edgan]], Irish [[triple deity|triple goddess]] associated with [[sovereignty goddess|sovereignty]], prophecy, war, and death on the battlefield\n*[[Neit]], Irish god of war, husband of Nemain of Badb\n*[[Nemain]], Irish goddess of the frenzied havoc of war; member of the Morr\u00edgan\n*[[Rudianos]], Gaulish god of war\n*[[Segomo]], Gaulish god of war\n*[[Teutates]], British and Gaulish god of war and the tribe\n==== Lusitanian ====\n*[[Neto (deity)|Neto]], god believed to be associated with war, death, and weaponry\n\n=== Norse-Germanic ===\n[[File:Idise by Emil Doepler.jpg|thumb|Idise by Emil Doepler.]]\n==== Continental Germanic ====\n*[[Baduhenna]], a western Frisii goddess of warfare\n*[[Idis (Germanic)]]/itis/ides, the West Germanic cognates of North Germanic ''d\u00eds'', they are connected with battle magic and fettering enemy armies\n*[[Sandraudiga]], goddess whose name may mean \"she who dyes the sand red\", suggesting she is a war deity or at least has a warrior aspect\n*[[T\u00fdr]], god of war, single combat, law, justice, and the [[thing (assembly)|thing]], who later lost much of his religious importance and mythical role to the god W\u014dden\n*[[W\u014dden]], god associated with wisdom, poetry, war, victory, and death\n\n==== Norse ====\n*[[D\u00eds]], a group of lesser goddesses who are sometimes connected with battle magic; valkyrie may be a [[kenning]] for them\n*[[Freyja]], goddess associated with love, beauty, fertility, gold, [[sei\u00f0r]], war, and death\n*[[Odin]], god associated with wisdom, war, battle, and death\n*[[T\u00fdr]], god associated with law, justice, victory, and heroic glory\n*[[Ullr]], god associated with archery, skiing, bows, hunting, single combat, and glory\n*[[Valkyrie]]s, choosers of the slain and connected to Odin, ruler of Valhalla; they may be the same as the d\u00eds above\n\n=== Graeco-Roman ===\n==== Greek / Hellenic ====\n*[[Alala]], spirit of the war cry\n*[[Alke]], spirit of courage and battle-strength\n*[[Amphillogiai]], goddesses of disputes\n*[[Androktasiai]], spirits of battlefield slaughter\n*[[Ares]], the main Greek god of war, despised by all the city-states except Sparta\n*[[Athena]], goddess of wisdom, war strategy, and weaving, more beloved by ancient Greeks than Ares and tutelary deity of Athens, Sparta's rival\n*[[Bia (mythology)|Bia]], spirit of force and compulsion\n*[[Deimos (mythology)|Deimos]], personification of terror\n*[[Enyalius]], god of war; in early periods apparently an epithet of Ares, they were differentiated later\n*[[Enyo]], goddess of war, sometimes appears to be identical to Eris\n*[[Eris (mythology)|Eris]], goddess of discord and strife\n*[[Hera]], in the ''[[Illiad]]'' she has a martial character and fights (and wins) against Artemis; however, this warlike aspect of her appears nowhere else in the surviving corpus, suggesting it was dropped early on\n*[[Homados]], spirit of the din of battle\n*[[Hysminai]], female spirits of fighting and combat\n*[[Ioke (mythology)|Ioke]], spirit of onslaught, battle-tumult, and pursuit\n*[[Keres (Greek mythology)|Keres]], female spirits of violent or cruel death, including death in battle, by accident, murder, or ravaging disease\n*[[Kratos (mythology)|Kratos]], personification of strength and power\n*[[Kydoimos]], spirit of the din of battle\n*[[Makhai]], male spirits of fighting and combat\n*[[Nike (mythology)|Nike]], spirit of victory\n*[[Palioxis]], spirit of backrush, flight, and retreat from battle\n*[[Pallas (Titan)|Pallas]], Titan god of war-craft and of the springtime campaign season\n*[[Perses (Titan)|Perses]], the Titan of destruction\n*[[Phobos (mythology)|Phobos]], spirit of panic, fear, flight, and battlefield rout\n*[[Phonoi]], spirits of murder, killing, and slaughter\n*[[Polemos]], spirit of war\n*[[Proioxis]], spirit of onrush and battlefield pursuit\n\n==== Roman ====\n[[File:Juno Sospita Statue.jpg|thumb|Juno Sospita Statue holding a spear and shield.]]\n*[[Bellona (goddess)|Bellona]], goddess of war\n*[[Honos]], god of chivalry, honor, and military justice\n*[[Juno (mythology)|Juno]], has a consistent martial character and the patron goddess of Rome, the mother of Mars and Bellona\n*[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], god of war and agriculture, equivalent to Ares as far as being war gods; aside from this they have very little in common\n*[[Minerva]], goddess of wisdom, medicine, music, crafts, and war, while somewhat equivalent to the Greek Athena, the Romans did not emphasize her war aspect like the Greeks did\n*[[Nerio]], warrior goddess and personification of valor\n*[[Victoria (mythology)|Victoria]], personification of victory, equivalent to the Greek goddess Nike\n*[[Virtus (deity)|Virtus]], god of bravery and military strength\n'''Etruscan'''\n*[[Laran]], god of war.\n*[[Menrva]], goddess of war, art, wisdom, and health\n\n=== Balkan ===\n*Danubian Rider\n*[[Sabazios]]\n*[[Thracian Rider]]\n\n=== Western Asia === \n==== Armenian ====\n*[[Anahit]], goddess of healing, fertility, wisdom, and water; in early periods associated with war\n==== Hittite ====\n*[[Shaushka]], goddess of fertility, war, and healing\n*[[Wurrukatte]], god of war\n\n==== Hindu-Vedic ====\n[[File:Kartikeya War of God by Surendra Nath Ganguly 1913.jpg|thumb|Kartikeya, god of war by Surendra Nath Ganguly, 1913.]]\n*[[Kartikeya]], god of war and battle\n*[[Mangala]], god of war\n*[[Nirrti]], goddess of strife\n*[[Parvati]], her forms [[Durga]] and [[Kali]] are known for fighting demons\n*[[Shiva]], several of his avatars are gods of avenging and destroying \n*[[Vishnu]], god of protection. Several of his avatars are associated with fighting and vanquishing evil.\n*[[Indra]], god of power, kingship, thunder, rains, electricity and the senses.\n==== Nuristani ====\n*[[Great Gish]], god of war\n\n=== Uralic === \n==== Hungarian ====\n*[[Had\u00far]], god of war and the metalsmith of the gods\n\n== Asia-Pacific / Oceania ==\n=== Turkic === \n*[[Kyzaghan]], Turkic deity of war\n=== Mongolian === \n*[[Dayisun Tngri]]\n\n=== Far East Asia === \n==== Chinese ====\n[[File:FS KwanKung 60116.jpg|thumb|[[Guan Yu]], Chinese god of loyalty, righteousness, and valor.]]\n* Ba Yikao, Pole Star of Purple Subtlety Emperor. God of Military Outcomes\n* [[Chiyou]], god of war\n* [[Di Qing]], Star of Military Fortune, God of Valor\n* [[Erlang Shen]], a three-eyed warrior\n* [[Guan Yu]], Han dynasty general. God of loyalty, righteousness, and valor. \n* [[Jinzha]], marshal of the center altar\n* [[Jiutian Xuann\u00fc]], goddess of war, sex, and longevity <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cahill|first1=Suzanne E.|title=Sublimation in Medieval China: The Case of the Mysterious Woman of the Nine Heavens|journal=Journal of Chinese Religions|date=18 July 2013|volume=20|issue=1|pages=91\u2013102|doi=10.1179/073776992805307692}}</ref>\n* [[Li Jing (deity)|Li Jing]], Guardian of Celestial Palace\n* [[Muzha (deity)|Muzha]], marshal of the center altar\n* [[Nezha]]\n* Wang Shan, Song dynasty general. Primordial Lord-General of Heaven. Guardian of Celestial Palace\n* Wen Qiong <ref>http://etheses.lib.cuhk.edu.hk/pdf/004777762.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Yue Fei]]\n* Zhao Lang ([[Zhao Gongming]]), God of Military Fortune, Guardian of Celestial Palace, Protector of Households\n\n==== Japanese ====\n*[[Futsunushi]], god of swords, martial arts, and conquest; god of the Mononobe clan\n*[[Hachiman]] Daimy\u014djin, [[Shinto]] god of war (on land) and agriculture, divine protector of the Minamoto clan; mostly worshiped by samurai\n*[[Sarutahiko]], god of war and misogi; the deity who stands at the junction of Heaven and Earth; one of the main Kunitsukami; actively worshipped by Ueshiba Morihei\n*[[Takemikazuchi]], god of war, conquest, martial arts, [[sumo]], and lightning; general of the Amatsukami; god of Kashima and [[Ujigami]] of Nakatomi clan\n*[[Takeminakata|Suwa My\u014djin (Takeminakata-no-kami)]], god of valor and duty, protector of the Japanese religion\n*[[Vai\u015brava\u1e47a|Bishamonten]], Buddhist god of war\n\n=== Southeast Asia === \n==== Vietnamese ====\n*[[Cao L\u1ed7]], god of military innovations\n*\u0110\u1ed9c C\u01b0\u1edbc, the protector of coastal settlements. Legend has it that he split himself in two with his axe, each half guards coastal villages against sea ogres.\n*Th\u1ea7n \u0110\u1ed3ng C\u1ed5, the armored protector of the [[L\u00fd dynasty]]\n*[[Th\u00e1nh Gi\u00f3ng]], god of triumph over foreign invaders\n\n=== Polynesian === \n*[['Oro]], god of war\n*[[Rongo]], [[Mangaia|Mangaian]] god of war and taro\n==== Hawaiian ====\n*[[K\u016b]], god of war and birds\n*[[Pele (deity)|Pele]], goddess of fire, lightning, dance, volcanoes, and violence\n==== M\u0101ori ====\n*[[Maru (mythology)|Maru]], god of war and fresh water\n*[[T\u016bmatauenga]], god of war and human activities\n\n== Native Americas ==\n=== North America === \n==== Great Plains ====\n*Morning Star, O-pi-ri-kus by one spelling; the god of war in [[Pawnee mythology]]\n==== Pacific Northwest ====\n*[[Qamaits]], [[Nuxalk Nation|Nux\u00e1lk]] warrior goddess\n*[[Winalagalis]], [[Kwakwaka'wakw]] god of war\n\n=== Central American and the Caribbean === \n==== Aztec ====\n*Patterns of War\n* [[Huitzilopochtli]], god of will, patron of war, fire, and sun; lord of the south\n** [[Mixcoatl]], god of war and hunting\n** [[Tlaloc]], god of thunder, rain, and earthquakes\n** [[Xipe-Totec]], god of force, patron of war, agriculture, vegetation, diseases, seasons, rebirth, hunting, trades, and spring; lord of the east\n** [[Xiuhtecuhtli]], god of fire\n==== Mayan ====\n*[[Tohil]], god associated with fire, the sun, rain, mountains, and war\n==== [[Haitian Vodou|Voodoo]] ====\n*[[Ogoun]], loa who presides over fire, iron, hunting, politics, and war\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{List of mythological figures by region}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of War Deities}}\n[[Category:Lists of deities|War]]\n[[Category:War deities| ]]\n[[Category:War in mythology| Deities]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKipsigis(link changed toKipsigis people) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_war_deities"}
{"title_page": "Special Delivery (1922 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Special Delivery\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Roscoe Arbuckle]]<br>''(uncredited)''\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Alfred St. John|Al St. John]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{film date|1922|4|30}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Special Delivery''''' is a 1922 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Roscoe Arbuckle]]. It was Arbuckle's first film as a director, albeit uncredited, following his acquittal of the manslaughter of [[Virginia Rappe]]. A print of the film survives in the film archive of the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SpecialDelivery1922.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Special Delivery'' |accessdate=March 15, 2010|work=silentera.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAs described in a [[film magazine]],<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite journal |title=Reviews: ''Special Delivery'' |journal=Exhibitors Herald |volume=14 |issue=22 |page=50 |publisher=Exhibitors Herald Company |location=New York City |date=May 27, 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/exhibitorsherald14exhi}}</ref> Al is told to deliver a radiophone message to a certain businessman. A gang of wicked looking plotters endeavor to capture him and steal the message. After a long chase involving Al's trick bicycle, the Sunshine lions of Fox studios, and scenes at the top of a tall building, Al safely delivers the message and the thugs are arrested.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Al St. John]]\n* [[Vernon Dent]]\n* [[Billy Engle]]\n* Tiny Ward\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fatty Arbuckle filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0248473|title=Special Delivery}}\n\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roscoe Arbuckle]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1922 comedy films]]\n[[Category:1922 short films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n{{1920s-comedy-film-stub}}\n{{short-silent-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Special Delivery\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Roscoe Arbuckle]]<br>''(uncredited)''\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Alfred St. John|Al St. John]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{film date|1922|4|30}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Special Delivery''''' is a 1922 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Roscoe Arbuckle]]. It was Arbuckle's first film as a director, albeit uncredited, following his acquittal of the manslaughter of [[Virginia Rappe]]. A print of the film survives in the film archive of the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SpecialDelivery1922.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Special Delivery'' |accessdate=2010-03-15|work=silentera.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAs described in a [[film magazine]],<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite journal |title=Reviews: ''Special Delivery'' |journal=Exhibitors Herald |volume=14 |issue=22 |page=50 |publisher=Exhibitors Herald Company |location=New York City |date=May 27, 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/exhibitorsherald14exhi}}</ref> Al is told to deliver a radiophone message to a certain businessman. A gang of wicked looking plotters endeavor to capture him and steal the message. After a long chase involving Al's trick bicycle, the Sunshine lions of Fox studios, and scenes at the top of a tall building, Al safely delivers the message and the thugs are arrested.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Al St. John]]\n* [[Vernon Dent]]\n* [[Billy Engle]]\n* Tiny Ward\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fatty Arbuckle filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0248473|title=Special Delivery}}\n\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roscoe Arbuckle]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1922 comedy films]]\n[[Category:1922 short films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n{{1920s-comedy-film-stub}}\n{{short-silent-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_Delivery_(1922_film)"}
{"title_page": "Laurette Tuckerman", "text_new": "{{short description|American mathematical physicist}}\n'''Laurette Stephanie Tuckerman''' (born 1956) is a mathematical physicist working in the areas of hydrodynamic instability, bifurcation theory, and computational fluid dynamics. She is currently a director of research for the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]], at the Physics and Mechanics of Heterogeneous Media Laboratory of [[ESPCI Paris]].<ref name=\"espci\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espci.fr/en/directory?recherche=tuckerman&r_en_cours=on&type=recherche&unique_id=CglMGTcGFSs%3D&lang=en|title=ESPCI Paris : Directory}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nTuckerman was born in [[New York City]] in 1956. Her mother was a journalist for the [[Agence France Presse]] covering the [[United Nations]] who had left France during World War II, and her father was a New York City union negotiator and devoted amateur pianist. She attended [[Hunter College High School]].\n\n== Education ==\nTuckerman attended [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Princeton University]] and obtained a Ph.D in applied mathematics from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1984. \n\n== Career ==\nTuckerman first worked at the [[Saclay Nuclear Research Centre]] in France and then at [[University of Texas at Austin]], where she was a postdoc at the Center for Nonlinear Dynamics and then a faculty member in the department of mathematics. In 1994, she became a researcher at [[Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique]] in France. She has also taught at [[Ecole Polytechnique]] and at [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)]].\n\n==Awards==\n\nIn 2002, she was elected as fellow of the [[American Physical Society]]<ref name=\"apsfellow\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=2002&unit_id=DFD&institution=|title=APS Fellow Archive}}</ref> and in 2018 she became a fellow of Euromech.<ref name=\"euromechfellow\">{{cite web|url=https://euromech.org/fellows/euromech-fellows-fluids|title=Fluid Mechanics Fellows}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://blog.espci.fr/laurette/ Home page]\n*{{Google Scholar id|qnxPT9UAAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority control|ORCID=0000-0001-5893-9238}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuckerman, Laurette}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:Mathematical physicists]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Physical Society]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamicists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mathematical physicist}}\n'''Laurette Stephanie Tuckerman''' (born 1956) is a mathematical physicist working in the areas of hydrodynamic instability, bifurcation theory, and computational fluid dynamics. She is currently a director of research for the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]], at the Physics and Mechanics of Heterogeneous Media Laboratory of [[ESPCI Paris]].<ref name=\"espci\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espci.fr/en/directory?recherche=tuckerman&r_en_cours=on&type=recherche&unique_id=CglMGTcGFSs%3D&lang=en|title=ESPCI Paris : Directory}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nTuckerman was born in [[New York City]] in 1956. Her mother was a journalist for the [[Agence_France-Presse]] covering the [[United Nations]] who had left France during World War II, and her father was a New York City union negotiator and devoted amateur pianist. She attended [[Hunter College High School]].\n\n== Education ==\nTuckerman attended [[Wesleyan University]] and [[Princeton University]] and obtained a Ph.D in applied mathematics from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1984. \n\n== Career ==\nTuckerman first worked at the [[Saclay Nuclear Research Centre]] in France and then at [[University of Texas at Austin]], where she was a postdoc at the Center for Nonlinear Dynamics and then a faculty member in the department of mathematics. In 1994, she became a researcher at [[Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique]] in France. She has also taught at [[Ecole Polytechnique]] and at [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)]].\n\n==Awards==\n\nIn 2002, she was elected as fellow of the [[American Physical Society]]<ref name=\"apsfellow\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=2002&unit_id=DFD&institution=|title=APS Fellow Archive}}</ref> and in 2018 she became a fellow of [[Euromech]].<ref name=\"euromechfellow\">{{cite web|url=https://euromech.org/fellows/euromech-fellows-fluids|title=Fluid Mechanics Fellows}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://blog.espci.fr/laurette/ Home page]\n*{{Google Scholar id|qnxPT9UAAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority control|ORCID=0000-0001-5893-9238}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuckerman, Laurette}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:Mathematical physicists]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Physical Society]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamicists]]\n", "name_user": "Topdown bottomup", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurette_Tuckerman"}
{"title_page": "Special Delivery (1927 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1927 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Special Delivery\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = William Goodrich<br>([[Roscoe Arbuckle]])\n| producer       = [[Jesse L. Lasky]]<br>[[B. P. Schulberg]]<br>[[Adolph Zukor]]<br>'''Uncredited:'''<br>[[Larry Semon]]\n| writer         = [[George Marion Jr.]]<br>John F. Goodrich<br>'''Uncredited:'''<br>Larry Semon\n| story          = [[Eddie Cantor]]\n| starring       = Eddie Cantor<br>[[Jobyna Ralston]]<br>[[William Powell]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Harry Hallenberger]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1927|5|6}}\n| runtime        = 60 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]<br>English intertitles\n}}\n\n'''''Special Delivery''''' is a 1927 American [[silent film|silent]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Roscoe Arbuckle]] (as ''\"William Goodrich\"''), starring [[Eddie Cantor]], written by Cantor, John F. Goodrich and [[George Marion Jr.]] (with [[Larry Semon]], uncredited). It was released by [[Paramount Pictures]].<ref>''The American Film Institute Catalog Feature Films: 1921-30'' by The American Film Institute, c.1971</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SpecialDelivery1927.html ''Special Delivery'' at silentera.com ]</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eddie Cantor]] - Eddie, The Mail Carrier\n* [[Jobyna Ralston]] - Madge, The Girl\n* [[William Powell]] - Harold Jones\n* [[Donald Keith (actor)|Donald Keith]] - Harrigan, The Fireman\n* Jack Dougherty - Flannigan, a cop\n* [[Victor Potel]] - Nip, a detective\n* [[Paul Kelly (actor)|Paul Kelly]] - Tuck, another detective\n* [[Mary Carr]] - The Mother\n* Marilyn Cantor Baker - Extra (uncredited) (as Marilyn Cantor)\n* Marjorie Cantor - Extra (uncredited)\n* [[The Doll Family|Tiny Doll]] - Baby on Eddie's Route (uncredited)\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]] - Extra at Postal Ball (uncredited)\n* Natalie Cantor Metzger - Extra (uncredited) (as Natalie Cantor)\n* [[Spec O'Donnell]] - Office Boy (uncredited)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fatty Arbuckle filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0018433|title=Special Delivery}}\n\n[[Category:1927 films]]\n[[Category:1927 comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by B. P. Schulberg]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roscoe Arbuckle]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n{{1920s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1927 film}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Special Delivery\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = William Goodrich<br>([[Roscoe Arbuckle]])\n| producer       = [[Jesse L. Lasky]]<br>[[B. P. Schulberg]]<br>[[Adolph Zukor]]<br>'''Uncredited:'''<br>[[Larry Semon]]\n| writer         = [[George Marion Jr.]]<br>John F. Goodrich<br>'''Uncredited:'''<br>Larry Semon\n| story          = [[Eddie Cantor]]\n| starring       = Eddie Cantor<br>[[Jobyna Ralston]]<br>[[William Powell]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Harry Hallenberger]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1927|5|6}}\n| runtime        = 60 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]<br>English intertitles\n}}\n\n'''''Special Delivery''''' is a 1927 American [[silent film|silent]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Roscoe Arbuckle]] (as ''\"William Goodrich\"''), starring [[Eddie Cantor]], written by Cantor, John F. Goodrich and [[George Marion Jr.]] (with [[Larry Semon]], uncredited). It was released by [[Paramount Pictures]].<ref>''The American Film Institute Catalog Feature Films: 1921-30'' by The American Film Institute, c.1971</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SpecialDelivery1927.html ''Special Delivery'' at silentera.com ]</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eddie Cantor]] - Eddie, The Mail Carrier\n* [[Jobyna Ralston]] - Madge, The Girl\n* [[William Powell]] - Harold Jones\n* [[Donald Keith (actor)|Donald Keith]] - Harrigan, The Fireman\n* Jack Dougherty - Flannigan, a cop\n* [[Victor Potel]] - Nip, a detective\n* [[Paul Kelly (actor)|Paul Kelly]] - Tuck, another detective\n* [[Mary Carr]] - The Mother\n* Marilyn Cantor Baker - Extra (uncredited) (as Marilyn Cantor)\n* Marjorie Cantor - Extra (uncredited)\n* [[The Doll Family|Tiny Doll]] - Baby on Eddie's Route (uncredited)\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]] - Extra at Postal Ball (uncredited)\n* Natalie Cantor Metzger - Extra (uncredited) (as Natalie Cantor)\n* [[Spec O'Donnell]] - Office Boy (uncredited)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fatty Arbuckle filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0018433|title=Special Delivery}}\n\n[[Category:1927 films]]\n[[Category:1927 comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by B. P. Schulberg]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roscoe Arbuckle]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n{{1920s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_Delivery_(1927_film)"}
{"title_page": "The Weeknd", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Weekend (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|Canadian singer, songwriter, actor and record producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = The Weeknd\n| image              = FEQ July 2018 The Weeknd (44778856382) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = The Weeknd during a show in 2018\n| birth_name         = Abel Makkonen Tesfaye\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1990|2|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* actor \n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| partner            = \n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd|Full list]]\n| website            = {{URL|theweeknd.com}}\n| signature          = Logo de The Weeknd.png\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed        = yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|<!-- Only add acts whose collaborations have been significant to his career.-->\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]]\n* [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]]\n* [[Doc McKinney]]\n* [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n* [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Abel Makkonen Tesfaye''' (born February 16, 1990), known professionally as '''The Weeknd''', is a Canadian singer, songwriter, actor and record producer.<ref name=\"sex-drugs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/sex-drugs-and-rb-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-176091/ |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |last=Eells |first=Josh |date=October 21, 2015 |website=Rolling Stone |access-date=July 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2010, he anonymously uploaded several songs to [[YouTube]] under the name \"The Weeknd\" and released the [[mixtape]]s ''[[House of Balloons]]'', ''[[Thursday (album)|Thursday]]'', and ''[[Echoes of Silence]]'' in 2011 which quickly gained him a following and recognition from several mainstream publications due to his dark style of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and the mystique surrounding his identity[[Contemporary R&B|.]]<ref name=\"happy\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/house-of-balloons/critic-reviews |title=House of Balloons \u2013 The Weeknd |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> \n\n''House of Balloons'', ''Thursday'', and ''Echoes of Silence''  were later remastered and re-released on the compilation album ''[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]]'' (2012). In 2013, The Weeknd released his debut album ''[[Kiss Land]]'' and followed it up with ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' (2015), the latter of which became his first [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] number-one album, and featured the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one singles \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\" and \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\". At the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th Grammy Awards]], ''Beauty Behind the Madness'' won [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]] and was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]. A year after the release of the album, The Weeknd released his third album ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]'' (2016), which spawned the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one hit [[Starboy (song)|of the same name]]. His first EP ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' (2018) debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, and preceded his fourth album ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' (2020). It was critically acclaimed, and featured the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" and \"[[Blinding Lights]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11323/The-Weeknd-After-Hours.aspx|title=After Hours by The Weeknd reviews {{!}} Any Decent Music|website=www.anydecentmusic.com|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Weeknd has won three [[Grammy Award]]s, two [[American Music Award]]s, nine [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], nine [[Juno Award]]s, and has been nominated for an [[Academy Award]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/the-weeknd |title=The Weeknd |publisher=The Recording Academy |access-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> He holds several chart records, being the first artist to simultaneously hold the top three positions on the [[R&B Songs|''Billboard'' Hot R&B Songs]] chart with \"Can't Feel My Face\", \"[[Earned It]]\", and \"The Hills\", while \"The Hills\" was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/ |title=Gold & Platinum |website=RIAA |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> One of the most successful Canadian recording artists, The Weeknd was awarded the [[Allan Slaight Award]] by [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] for \"making a positive impact in the fields of music, film, literature, visual or performing arts, sports, innovation or philanthropy\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/story/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame |title=THE WEEKND HONOURED WITH ALLAN SLAIGHT AWARD FROM CANADA'S WALK OF FAME |date=February 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214052542/http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/story/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame |archive-date=February 14, 2015 |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAbel Makkonen Tesfaye was born on February 16, 1990 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], and was raised in the district of [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], in the city's east end.<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"allmusic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162/biography |title=The Weeknd Biography |last=Kellman |first=Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFl8uYyO?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162/biography |archive-date=October 13, 2015 |access-date=October 13, 2015}}</ref> He is the only child of Makkonen and Samra Tesfaye, who were [[Ethiopian Canadians|Ethiopian immigrants to Canada]] in the late 1980s.<ref name=\"jcaramanica\">{{Cite news |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/magazine/can-the-weeknd-turn-himself-into-the-biggest-pop-star-in-the-world.html |title=Can The Weeknd Turn Himself into the Biggest Pop Star in the World? |date=July 27, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFlDxFgo?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/magazine/can-the-weeknd-turn-himself-into-the-biggest-pop-star-in-the-world.html?_r=0 |archive-date=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RStone\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sex-drugs-and-r-b-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-20151021 |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |date=October 21, 2015 |access-date=October 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mistry\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontostandard.com/culture/daily-disc-the-weeknds-echoes-of-silence |title=Daily Disc: The Weeknd's 'Echoes Of Silence' |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |website=[[Toronto Standard]] |publisher=MeshSquared Ventures |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"RSinterview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/sex-drugs-and-rb-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-176091/ |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |last=Eeels |first=Josh |date=October 21, 2015 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Wenner Media LLC]] |access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye was raised by his grandmother and mother after his parents split up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/the-weeknd-trivia_us_56bb63cfe4b08ffac1236c5e |title=9 things You Need To Know About The Weeknd |last=Ledbetter |first=Carly |date=February 11, 2016 |publisher=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> While living with his grandmother Tesfaye learned [[Amharic]], which he also spoke with his mother,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/the-weeknd-reddit-ama-interview.html |title=The Weeknd Reveals The Origin Of His Name + More |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> and attended [[Ethiopian Orthodox]] church services.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /><ref name=\"where the e went\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama.jhtml |title=The Weeknd Reveals How He Got His Name... And Where The 'E' Went |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |date=September 13, 2013 |publisher=[[MTV News]] |access-date=September 15, 2013}}</ref> When asked about his father in an interview, Tesfaye stated: \"I saw him vaguely when I was six, and then again when I was 11 or 12, and he had a new family and kids. I don't even know where he lived \u2014 I'd see him for, like, a night. I'm sure he's a great guy. I never judged him. He wasn't abusive, he wasn't an alcoholic, he wasn't an asshole. He just wasn't there.\"<ref name=\"RSinterview\" />\n\nTesfaye describes his teenage years as the film \"''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'' without the [[AIDS]]\". Tesfaye states he began smoking [[marijuana]] at age 11, and later moved on to [[hard drugs|harder drugs]]. Tesfaye claims he often shoplifted to supplement his use of [[MDMA|ecstasy]], [[oxycodone]], [[xanax]], [[cocaine]], [[Psilocybin mushroom|psilocybin]], and [[ketamine]].<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/5-things-you-should-know-about-the-weeknd |title=10 Things You Should Know About the Weeknd |last=Wagstaff |first=Keith |last2=Swanson |first2=David |website=GQ |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye attended [[West Hill Collegiate Institute]] and [[Birchmount Park Collegiate Institute]] in Scarborough, from which he did not graduate, leaving altogether in 2007,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/6163335-scarborough-native-the-weeknd-scores-seven-grammy-nominations/ |title=Scarborough native The Weeknd scores seven Grammy nominations |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe and Mail: Mistry\">{{Cite news |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/why-the-weeknd-is-truly-torontos-very-own/article27053702/ |title=Why The Weeknd is truly Toronto's very own |date=October 30, 2015 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=December 26, 2016}}</ref> after which he also left home. Tesfaye moved to the [[Parkdale, Toronto|Parkdale]] neighborhood of Toronto. Tesfaye has credited his stage name as being inspired by his high school dropout status, claiming \"after [he] left one weekend and never came home\", though producer Jeremy Rose claims the name was his idea.<ref name=\"McGuire\">{{Cite journal |last=McGuire |first=Patrick |date=April 2012 |title=How the Producer of The Weeknd's Breakout Tracks Got Majorly Screwed |url=https://www.vice.com/read/how-the-producer-of-the-weeknds-breakout-tracks-got-majorly-screwed |journal=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |location=New York |access-date=March 3, 2013}}</ref> The spelling was modified in order to avoid trademark issues with the Canadian band [[The Weekend (Canadian band)|The Weekend]].<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"where the e went\" />\n\n==Career==\n===2010\u20132011: Career beginnings===\n{{main|House of Balloons|Thursday (album)|Echoes of Silence}}\nTesfaye met Jeremy Rose in 2010, a producer who had an idea for a dark [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] musical project<!-- not a typo; cited in the source -->. After initially trying to pitch the idea to musician [[Curtis Santiago]], Rose played one of his instrumentals for Tesfaye, who [[freestyle rap]]ped over it. This led to the two collaborating on an album. Rose produced three songs \u2013 \"What You Need\", \"Loft Music\", and \"The Morning\" \u2013 and others that Tesfaye had rapped on, which were ultimately scrapped. Rose let Tesfaye keep the tracks he had produced under the condition that he would ultimately be credited for them.<ref name=\"McGuire\" /> In December 2010, Tesfaye uploaded \"What You Need\", \"Loft Music\" and \"The Morning\" to [[YouTube]] under his stage name,<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite news |last=Caramanica A-Train |first=Jon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/02/arts/music/02playlist.html?_r=4&ref=music |title=Screams That Charmed, and Other Overlooked Highlights |date=December 26, 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref> although his identity was initially unknown.<ref name=\"pforkwynreview\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/12131-what-you-need/ |title=The Playlist \u2013 The Weeknd \u2013 ''What You Need'' |last=Fitzmaurice |first=Larry |date=March 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326174005/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/12131-what-you-need |archive-date=March 26, 2011 |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"washpost\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/03/14/AR2011031403984.html |title=Singles File: Da Phuture, The Weeknd, Fever Ray |last=Stewart |first=Allison |date=March 14, 2011 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref> The songs drew some attention online, and were later included in a blog post from [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]].<ref name=\"McGuire\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thirteen.org/riffcity/music/love-and-other-drugs-the-weeknds-altered-state-rb/ |title=Love and Other Drugs: The Weeknd's Altered-State R&B |last=Shepherd |first=Julianne Escobedo |date=March 23, 2011 |publisher=[[WNET]] |access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The songs subsequently received coverage from various media outlets, including [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] and ''[[The New York Times]]''. Before adopting the stage name \"The Weeknd\", he worked under the aliases of \"The Noise\" and \"Kin Kane\".<ref name=\"RStone\" />\n\nTesfaye took to his Twitter to mention that his extended play, ''Noise,'' were \"a bunch of songs leaked by salty producers and found AFTER HOB dropped.\" He says that they were demos that he had written as a teenager to try and get recognition. The EP consists of 10 tracks, some of which influenced his debut mixtape, [[House of Balloons|''House of Balloon''s]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/263753618484760577?lang=en |title=@theweeknd Twitter |last=Tesfaye |first=Abel |date=October 31, 2012 |website=Twitter |access-date=May 7, 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2011, Tesfaye [[self-released]] his debut mixtape ''[[House of Balloons]]''.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{Cite web |url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/03/21/say-hello-to-the-weeknd-drake-co-signs/ |title=Say Hello to The Weeknd, Drake Co-Signs |last=Ramirez |first=Erika |date=March 21, 2011 |publisher=MTV |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbcmusic.ca/posts/17548/cohen-gould-buffy-25-best-canadian-debut-albums \"25 best Canadian debut albums ever\"]. ''CBC Music'', June 16, 2017.</ref> The mixtape included production from Canadian producers [[Illangelo]] and [[Doc McKinney]], and included the tracks produced by Rose, although, he did not receive production credits.<ref name=\"McGuire\" /> ''House of Balloons'' was met with critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/house-of-balloons/the-weeknd |title=House of Balloons Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 3, 2013}}</ref> It was named as one of ten shortlisted nominees for the [[2011 Polaris Music Prize]].<ref name=\"shortlist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.polarismusicprize.ca/2011/ |title=Polaris Music Prize |website=Polaris Music Prize |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409053023/http://www.polarismusicprize.ca/2011/ |archive-date=April 9, 2014 |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye began a tour of [[Toronto]], with his first live performance at the city's [[Mod Club]] venue. Drake was in attendance to view the performance, which ran for a total of ninety minutes.<ref>Ritchie, Kevin (July 25, 2011). [http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/music/story.cfm?content=181922 The Weeknd's perfect premiere].''[[NOW Toronto]]''. Retrieved March 28, 2012</ref> Drake approached Tesfaye and described a potential musical collaboration between the pair. Tesfaye accompanied Drake at his various shows, often performing as the opening act for shows scheduled at the [[Molson Canadian Amphitheatre]], as well as appearing at the second annual [[OVO Fest]] in July.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/42716-the-weeknd-to-play-drakes-ovo-festival/ |title=The Weeknd to Play Drake's OVO Festival |last=Fitzmaurice |first=Larry |date=July 3, 2011 |access-date=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Over the summer of 2011, Tesfaye contributed to four songs on Drake's ''[[Take Care (album)|Take Care]]'', both as a writer and a featured artist.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Berry |first=Peter A. |url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/drake-the-weeknd-wrote-take-care/ |title=Drake Sets The Record Straight On How Much The Weeknd Wroteon Take Care Album |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=April 15, 2019 |publisher=XXL Mag}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye refrained from participating in interviews, choosing to communicate via [[Twitter]], after the album was released.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lau |first=Melody |date=July 25, 2011 |title=Mysterious R&B singer sells out first show |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/drake-protege-the-weeknd-proves-hes-no-fluke-in-live-debut-20110725 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> This was credited{{By whom|date=June 2019}} as an advertising tactic for Tesfayes second mixtape ''[[Thursday (album)|Thursday]]'', which was released on August 18, 2011.<ref name=\"npost\">Dunlevy, T'Cha (March 23, 2012). [http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/20/365-days-of-weeknd-we-chart-abel-tesfayes-rise-to-fame-a-year-after-house-of-balloons/ \"365 days of Weeknd: We chart Abel Tesfaye's rise to fame a year after House of Balloons\"] {{webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120321220120/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/20/365%2Ddays%2Dof%2Dweeknd%2Dwe%2Dchart%2Dabel%2Dtesfayes%2Drise%2Dto%2Dfame%2Da%2Dyear%2Dafter%2Dhouse%2Dof%2Dballoons/ |date=March 21, 2012 }} .''[[National Post]]''. Retrieved March 27, 2012</ref> Tesfaye's third mixtape ''[[Echoes of Silence]]'' was released on December 21, 2011, a year after his debut singles.<ref name=npost/><ref>The Weeknd's Official site [http://the-weeknd.com/ Official Site]. Retrieved March 28, 2012</ref>\n\nFollowing this release, the three mixtapes were collectively known as the ''Balloons Trilogy'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/echoes-of-silence-the-weeknd-reveals-final-part-of-the-balloons-trilogy-77249 |title=Echoes Of Silence The Weeknd reveals final part of the Balloons Trilogy The Line Of Best Fit |date=December 22, 2011 |publisher=theLineofBestFit.com |access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref> and saw Tesfaye receiving offers from various record labels.{{Which|date=June 2019}}<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\n===2012\u20132014: ''Trilogy'' and ''Kiss Land''===\n{{main|Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Kiss Land}}\n[[File:The Weeknd by David Hwang.jpg|thumb|Tesfaye performing at Coachella in 2012.]]\nIn April 2012, Tesfaye began his first tour of the United States, with a performance at the [[Coachella Festival]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/46157-watch-the-weeknds-entire-coachella-set/ |title=Abel Tesfaye makes his U.S. debut |last=Snapes |first=Laura |date=April 16, 2012 |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> The tour culminated in New York with back-to-back sold-out shows, which were positively reviewed by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref name=\"tour\" /><ref name=\"Stones\">{{Cite journal |last=Krishnamurthy |first=Sowmya |date=April 29, 2012 |title=The Weeknd Mesmerizes at Bowery Ballroom |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-weeknd-mesmerizes-at-bowery-ballroom-20120429 |journal=Rolling Stone |location=New York |access-date=May 27, 2012}}</ref> Tesfaye expanded his tour to accompany Europe, performing at various European festivals, including the [[Primavera Sound Festival]]s in Spain and Portugal,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://prettymuchamazing.com/news/the-weeknd-announces-first-ever-tour |title=The Weeknd announces first ever tour |last=Tovar |first=Luis |publisher=prettymuchamazing.com |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> and the [[Wireless Festival]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wirelessfestival.co.uk/line-up/ |title=Wireless line up 2012 |publisher=wirelessfestival.co.uk |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316180853/http://www.wirelessfestival.co.uk/line-up/ |archive-date=March 16, 2012 |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> Covering \"[[Dirty Diana]]\" at his performance in London, he received positive responses from both [[Katy Perry]] and [[Florence Welch]], who noted the singer's ability to successfully undertake a complex song.<ref name=\"June\">{{Cite journal |title=The Weeknd covers Michael Jackson as he plays his debut UK show |url=http://www.nme.com/news/weekend--3/64204 |journal=[[NME]] |location=London |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref> In June, the ''Balloons Trilogy'' was revealed to have been downloaded over 8 million times, which allowed Tesfaye to initiate formal commercial release of the projects later that year.<ref name=\"June\" />\n\nIn September 2012, Tesfaye signed with [[Republic Records]] in a joint venture with his own [[Imprint label|imprint]] [[XO (record label)|XO]].<ref name=\"Hampp\">{{Cite journal |last=Hampp |first=Andrew |date=November 12, 2012 |title=The Weeknd & Reps Talk Clearing Samples, Touring For 'Trilogy' Release |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474219/the-weeknd-reps-talk-clearing-samples-touring-for-trilogy-release |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |location=New York |access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref> The compilation album for the mixtapes entitled ''[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]]'', was released two months later, and consisted of several remastered versions of songs, as well as three additional ones.<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/48066-the-weeknd-shares-rolling-stone-video-trilogy-artwork |title=The Weeknd Shares 'Rolling Stone' Video, Trilogy Artwork |last=Battan |first=Carrie |date=October 2, 2012 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref> It also officially credited Rose as a producer and writer on the three songs from ''House of Balloons'' for which he did not initially receive credit.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]] |others=The Weeknd |year=2012 |type=CD liner notes |publisher=[[Republic Records]] |id=3719793}}</ref> ''Trilogy'' charted at number four on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with first-week sales of 86,000 copies. It also debuted at number five on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], with similar sales.<ref name=\"bb\">{{Cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=The weeknd|chart=all}} |title=Trilogy&nbsp;\u2013 The Weeknd |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=November 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Caulfield\">{{Cite journal |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |date=October 10, 2012 |title=One Direction Tops Billboard 200 Chart, 'Twilight' Debuts at No. 3 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474052/one-direction-tops-billboard-200-chart-twilight-debuts-at-no-3 |journal=Billboard |location=Los Angeles |access-date=November 21, 2012}}</ref> ''Trilogy'' was later certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and double-platinum by [[Music Canada]] in May 2013.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22THE%20WEEKND%22 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |access-date=December 19, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Trilogy&sa=The+Weeknd&smt=0 |title=Gold and Platinum Search |publisher=[[Music Canada]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927064324/http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Trilogy&sa=The+Weeknd&smt=0 |archive-date=September 27, 2013 |access-date=December 21, 2012}}</ref> He had also gained a nomination for the [[Sound of...|Sound of 2013]] poll award by the [[BBC]] a week later.<ref name=\"so13\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p010q6bc/profiles/theweeknd |title=Sound of 2013 Profiles: The Weeknd |date=December 9, 2012 |publisher=BBC |access-date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Weeknd at Massey Hall October 17, 2013 amber lighting.jpg|thumb|Tesfaye performing at [[Massey Hall]] in October 2013.]]\nOn May 16, 2013, Tesfaye premiered the [[Kiss Land (song)|title track]] to his debut studio album ''[[Kiss Land]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/05/listen-the-weeknd-kiss-land |title=Listen: The Weeknd \"Kiss Land\" |last=Nostro |first=Lauren |date=May 16, 2013 |access-date=May 17, 2013}}</ref> and announced the album's release date as September 10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://idolator.com/7472491/the-weeknd-kiss-land-release-date-cover-artwork |title=The Weeknd Unveils 'Kiss Land' Release Date & Cover Artwork |last=Williott |first=Carl |date=July 22, 2013 |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |access-date=July 22, 2013}}</ref> The album was later promoted by the singles \"[[Belong to the World]]\" and \"[[Live For]]\" featuring [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], as well as with Tesfaye embarking on The Fall tour a week prior to the album's release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisgoesin.com/2013/07/the-weeknds-kiss-land-arrives-on-august-27th-belong-to-the-world-snippet-news/ |title=The Weeknd's 'Kiss Land' Arrives on August 27th, \"Belong to the World\" Snippet |date=July 13, 2013 |publisher=ThisGoesIn |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723110346/http://www.thisgoesin.com/2013/07/the-weeknds-kiss-land-arrives-on-august-27th-belong-to-the-world-snippet-news/ |archive-date=July 23, 2013 |access-date=July 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Live-For-feat-Drake/dp/B00EP54R5U |title=Amazon.com: Live For [feat. Drake] [Clean]: The Weeknd: MP3 Downloads |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Upon release, ''Kiss Land'' debuted at number two on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 96,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695587/keith-urban-edges-the-weeknd-for-no-1-debut-on-billboard-200 |title=Keith Urban Edges The Weeknd for No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 |date=December 1, 2012 |website=Billboard |access-date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> It was later confirmed to have sold over 273,000 copies in the United States, as well as receiving generally positive reviews from music critics.<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/kiss-land/the-weeknd |title=Kiss Land Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |access-date=September 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye appeared on [[the 20/20 Experience World Tour]], joining headline act [[Justin Timberlake]] for six shows.<ref name=\"jttour\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5778176/the-weeknd-to-open-for-justin-timberlake-on-2020-experience-tour |title=The Weeknd To Open For Justin Timberlake On '20/20 Experience' Tour |last=Payne |first=Chris |date=November 4, 2013 |website=Billboard |access-date=November 27, 2015}}</ref> This was three weeks prior to his contributions to the [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013), contributing \"Devil May Cry\", as well as featuring on [[Sia (singer)|Sia]]'s \"[[Elastic Heart]]\". The latter proved to be the second lead single from the soundtrack.<ref name=\"hunger-cos\">{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/11/album-review-various-artists-the-hunger-games-catching-fire-soundtrack/ |title=Album Review: Various Artists \u2013 The Hunger Games: Catching Fire Soundtrack |last=Hakimian |first=Rob |date=November 19, 2013 |website=Consequence of Sound |access-date=December 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"amazon sia\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Elastic-Heart-From-Hunger-Games/dp/B00FHU3G6I/ |title=Elastic Heart (From \"The Hunger Games: Catching Fire\" Soundtrack) [feat. The Weeknd, Diplo]: Sia |access-date=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Tesfaye remixed \"[[Drunk in Love]]\", a single by [[Beyonc\u00e9]] from her [[Beyonc\u00e9 (album)|eponymous studio album]]. Retaining the theme and concept of the song, he detailed the synopsis through the perspective of a male.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/audio-beyonces-drunk-love-kanye-681039 |title=[Audio] Beyonce's 'Drunk in Love': Kanye West, The Weeknd Release Remixes |last=Lee |first=Ashley |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> The remix was well-received, and came days prior to the announcement of Tesfaye's first headlining tour, entitled the King of the Fall tour. The tour was held across the United States in September and October, and saw [[Schoolboy Q]] and [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] as supporting acts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/archives/2014/06/the_weeknd_tour_1.html |title=The Weeknd touring w/ Schoolboy Q & Jhene Aiko, playing Barclays Center (dates); SBQ played Central Park |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> This oversaw his release of the single \"[[Often]]\", leading to speculation it was the first single from his second studio album.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/entry/view/id/44925 |title=Ida Maria Gets Exclamatory |website=Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on Idolator.com}}</ref> He later collaborated with [[Ariana Grande]] on a duet titled \"[[Love Me Harder]]\", which peaked at number seven on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/10/03/first-look-ariana-grande-the-weeknd-love-me-harder-video/ |title=Ariana Grande and The Weeknd Team Up In 'Love Me Harder' Video |website=Rap-Up |access-date=October 4, 2014}}</ref> Days later, he released \"[[Earned It]]\", a single from ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]'' (2015). This marked his second contribution to a movie, and peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n===2015: ''Beauty Behind the Madness''===\n{{main|Beauty Behind the Madness}}\nAfter Tesfaye won the Centric Award at the [[BET Awards 2015|2015 BET Awards]], he performed \"Earned It\" with [[Alicia Keys]], as well as debuting the song \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60165-janelle-monae-performs-yoga-the-weeknd-performs-earned-it-with-alicia-keys-at-the-bet-awards/ |title=Janelle Mon\u00e1e Performs \"Yoga\", The Weeknd Performs \"Earned It\" with Alicia Keys at the BET Awards |last=Beauchemin |first=Molly |website=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] |access-date=June 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/05/weeknd-debuts-new-song-the-hills.html |title=The Weeknd Returns With 'The Hills,' Which Probably Isn't About Lauren Conrad |last=Lockett |first=Dee |website=Vulture |access-date=May 27, 2015 |ref=vulture-hills}}</ref> \"The Hills\" was later released for digital download, and debuted at number twenty on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The single later went on to top the chart, marking Tesfaye's first number-one single.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.billboard.com/entry/view/id/139265 |title=The Weeknd |website=Billboard |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> The single was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\nOn June 8, \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\", a previously leaked track, was released as the album's third single, following its performance at the [[Apple Inc.|Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]].<ref name=\"RS1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-the-weeknds-funky-new-song-cant-feel-my-face-20150608 |title=Hear The Weeknd's Funky New Song 'Can't Feel My Face' |last=Kreps |first=Daniel |date=June 8, 2015 |website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |access-date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> The song debuted at number twenty-four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and reached number-one on the Hot 100, making it his third top 10 hit, and his second number-one hit in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6613247/wiz-khalifa-no-1-hot-100-selena-gomez-debuts |title=Wiz Khalifa No. 1 on Hot 100 'Again,' Selena Gomez Debuts at No. 9 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 1, 2015 |website=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6656820/the-weeknd-no-1-hot-100-cant-feel-my-face-one-direction-drag-me-down |title=The Weeknd Tops Hot 100 With 'Can't Feel My Face,' One Direction Debuts at No. 3 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> He occupied all three slots on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]]'' [[Hot R&B Songs]] chart simultaneously with the aforementioned singles, becoming the first artist in history to accomplish this.<ref name=\"alone\">[http://music.cbc.ca/#!/blogs/2015/7/Alone-on-the-podium-The-Weeknd-becomes-first-artist-to-take-over-Billboard-RB-chart \"Alone on the podium: The Weeknd becomes first artist to take over Billboard R&B chart\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301002442/http://music.cbc.ca/#!/blogs/2013/6/Rear-view-Mirror-Who-was-Suzanne-and-why-did-Leonard-Cohen-make-her-famous |date= March 1, 2016 }}. [[CBC Music]], July 17, 2015.</ref> He headlined FVDED in the Park, a festival in [[Surrey, British Columbia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thisisblueprint.com/news/tickets/fvded-in-the-park-2015-announced |title=FVDED in the Park 2015 Announced |publisher=thisisblueprint.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926222507/http://thisisblueprint.com/news/tickets/fvded-in-the-park-2015-announced# |archive-date=September 26, 2015 |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> Tesfaye was unveiled as one of the musical faces of the streaming service [[Apple Music]], a position he harbored with frequent collaborator Drake.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-apples-new-musical-faces---drake-and-the-weeknd-2015-6 |title=Apple's new musical faces - Drake and The Weeknd |access-date=June 8, 2015}}</ref> During the [[2015 MTV Video Music Awards]], Apple debuted a two-part promotional commercial featuring Tesfaye, which had a guest appearance from [[John Travolta]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/15/08/31/latest-apple-music-ads-debut-during-mtv-vmas-feature-the-weeknd-playlists |title=Latest Apple Music ads debut during MTV VMAs, feature The Weeknd & playlists |access-date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> It was revealed that his second studio album would be titled ''Beauty Behind the Madness''.\n\n''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' was released on August 28, 2015, and debuted atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], earning 412,000 album equivalent units in its first week.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6685947/the-weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-debuts-at-no-1-billboard-200-charts |title=The Weeknd's 'Beauty Behind the Madness' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart |website=Billboard |access-date=September 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6700714/the-weeknd-billboard-200-third-week-no-1 |title=The Weeknd spends third week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 |website=Billboard |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> It reached the top 10 in over ten countries, as well as reaching number one in Canada, Australia, Norway, and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-the-weeknd-takes-top-spot-on-australian-chart-20150905 |title=ARIA Albums : The Weeknd Takes Top Spot On Australian Chart |publisher=Noise11 |access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musiccanada.com/charts/#albums |title=Top 20 Albums |website=USA Today |access-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The album was promoted by Tesfaye headlining various summer music festivals, including [[Lollapalooza]], the Hard Summer Music Festival, and the [[Bumbershoot]] Festival.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/07/10/weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-august-28-release/29961285/ |title=The Weeknd's new album is coming Aug. 28 |website=USA Today |access-date=July 15, 2015}}</ref> He announced [[The Madness Fall Tour|his first large-scale tour]] across the United States, which began in November, and concluded in December.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60875-the-weeknd-announces-the-madness-fall-tour/ |title=The Weeknd announces The Madness Fall Tour |website=Pitchfork |access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6671102/the-weeknd-the-madness-fall-tour-dates |title=The Weeknd Announces The Madness Fall Tour With Travi$ Scott, Halsey & Banks |website=Billboard |access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref> The album went double platinum in the US, and sold 1.5&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"IFPI2016\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2016.pdf |title=Global Music Report |date=April 12, 2016 |publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] |access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> It was reported to be the most-streamed album throughout 2015, with over 60 million,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6778065/spotify-year-music-lists-2015-drake-rihanna-major-lazer-ed-sheeran |title=Spotify's Year in Music: Drake Most Streamed Artist, Major Lazer & DJ Snake Had Top Song |website=Billboard}}</ref> as well as being ranked on multiple lists concerned with detailing albums of the year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2015-20151201/the-weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-20151130 |title=The Weeknd, 'Beauty Behind the Madness' |website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8, Tesfaye became the first male artist to have simultaneously held the top three spots on the Billboard Hot R&B Songs chart, with the three singles that preceded the release of his album. They all went platinum in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6685989/the-weeknd-hot-100-top-three |title=The Weeknd Doubles Up in Hot 100's Top Three |website=Billboard |access-date=August 8, 2015}}</ref> After engaging in multiple musical collaborations with [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/Music/article/belly-might_not_ft_weeknd |title=Belly 'Might Not' (ft. The Weeknd) |website=Exclaim! |access-date=May 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Meek Mill]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.34353/title.meek-mill-reveals-dreams-worth-more-than-money-features |title=Meek Mill Reveals 'Dreams Worth More Than Money' Features |publisher=hiphopdx |access-date=June 22, 2015}}</ref> and [[Travis Scott (musician)|Travis Scott]],<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7606572/demi-lovato-the-weeknd-perform-saturday-night-live-season-41 |title=Demi Lovato & The Weeknd To Perform On 'Saturday Night Live' This Season |publisher=Idolator |access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2352303/justin-bieber-kanye-west-the-weeknd-more-featuring-on-travis-scott-s-rodeo-album/ |title=Justin Bieber, Kanye West, The Weeknd, & more featuring on Travi$ Scott's 'Rodeo\" album |publisher=Inquisitr |access-date=August 20, 2015}}</ref> Tesfaye was featured on \"[[Low Life (song)|Low Life]]\", the triple platinum single from [[Future (rapper)|Future's]] [[EVOL (Future album)|fourth studio album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kiss925.com/2015/12/27/listen-the-weeknd-surprises-fans-by-dropping-two-new-songs/ |title=Listen: The Weeknd Surprises Fans By Dropping Two New Songs! |date=December 27, 2015 |website=Kiss 92.5 |access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye appeared on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' alongside actress [[Amy Schumer]], performing as the show's musical guest on October 10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6685066/weeknd-demi-lovato-snl-musical-guests |title=The Weeknd & Demi Lovato Announced as 'SNL' Musical Guests |website=Billboard |access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref> This was his first performance on the show as a solo artist, after appearing with [[Ariana Grande]] to perform \"Love Me Harder\".<ref name=\"Idolator\" />\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Starboy'' and ''My Dear Melancholy''===\n{{main|Starboy (album)|My Dear Melancholy}}\n\nTesfaye was featured on \"FML\", a track on [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[The Life of Pablo]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kanyewest.com/credits/ |title=Archived copy |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fMFARK1V?url=http://www.kanyewest.com/credits/ |archive-date=February 17, 2016 |access-date=February 17, 2016}}</ref> It marked the second collaboration between the pair, with West providing production and writing on \"[[Tell Your Friends (song)|Tell Your Friends]]\" from ''Beauty Behind the Madness''. Tesfaye appeared on \"[[6 Inch]]\", the fifth song on [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''. He was announced by [[Spotify]] as being among the top five most streamed artists in their first year partnering with [[Sony]] to provide the streaming service on the [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.spotify.com/us/2016/04/15/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstationmusic/ |title=Spotify and PlayStation Celebrate One Year Together and Hit More Than Five Billion Streams on PlayStation Music |website=Spotify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423181523/https://news.spotify.com/us/2016/04/15/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstationmusic/ |archive-date=April 23, 2016 |access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.scoop.it/topic/music-news-for-orange/p/4062765549/2016/04/19/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstation-music |title=Spotify and PlayStation\u00ae Celebrate One Year Together and Hit More Than Five Billion Streams on PlayStation\u2122Music &#124; Music News |website=Scoop.it}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, in preparation for his third studio album, [[Republic Records]] executive vice-president Wendy Goldstein confirmed Tesfaye began collaborations with French electronic music duo [[Daft Punk]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/the-weeknd-working-with-daft-punk |title=The Weeknd Is Reportedly Working with Daft Punk |date=August 23, 2016 |access-date=August 23, 2016}}</ref> On the same day, Tesfaye also announced a collaboration with Norwegian record producer [[Cashmere Cat]], titled \"[[Wild Love (Cashmere Cat song)|Wild Love]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Morris |first=Jesse |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/the-weeknd-previews-cashmere-cat-collaboration |title=It Sounds Like a Weeknd and Cashmere Cat Collab Is on the Way |date=August 24, 2016 |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> A month later, the previously mentioned album's title was announced as ''Starboy'', and had a release date of November 25.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/67755-the-weeknd-announces-new-album-starboy/ |title=The Weeknd Announces New Album Starboy |last=Pearce |first=Sheldon |date=September 21, 2016 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> He released the album's [[Starboy (song)|title track]], which features Daft Punk on September 21. The song received platinum certification and went to number one in the United States, as well as in various other countries.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/sep/22/hear-the-weeknds-new-track-with-daft-punk-starboy |title=Hear the Weeknd's new track with Daft Punk, Starboy |date=September 22, 2016 |work=The Guardian |access-date=September 22, 2016 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> A second collaboration with Daft Punk, entitled \"[[I Feel It Coming]]\", was released a week proceeding the album's release, alongside the solo efforts \"[[Party Monster (song)|Party Monster]]\" and \"[[False Alarm (The Weeknd song)|False Alarm]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dancingastronaut.com/2016/09/daft-punk-the-weeknd-collaboration-listen/ |title=Listen to Daft Punk's new collaboration with The Weeknd, 'Starboy' |last=Zwilling |first=Eric |date=September 21, 2016 |website=Dancing Astronaut |access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye returned to ''Saturday Night Live'' on October 10, performing \"Starboy\" and \"False Alarm\". He released a 12-minute short film, titled ''M A N I A'', on November 23.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBsycvSU6r8 |title=Watch The Weeknd \u2013 Mania on YouTube |date=November 23, 2016 |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=March 2, 2017}}</ref> Directed by Grant Singer, it featured excerpts from the album, including snippets from \"[[All I Know (The Weeknd song)|All I Know]]\" featuring [[Future (rapper)|Future]], \"[[Sidewalks (song)|Sidewalks]]\" featuring [[Kendrick Lamar]], \"[[Secrets (The Weeknd song)|Secrets]]\" and \"[[Die for You (The Weeknd song)|Die for You]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/69997-watch-the-weeknds-new-short-film-mania/ |title=Watch The Weeknd's New Short Film Mania |date=November 23, 2016 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:The Weeknd with hand in the air performing live in Hong Kong in November 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Tesfaye performing live in Hong Kong in November 2018.]]\nIn 2017, Tesfaye appeared on [[Hndrxx|Future's sixth studio album]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7701959/future-album-hndrxx-the-weeknd-rihanna |title=Future Releases New Album 'HNDRXX' Featuring The Weeknd and Rihanna: Listen |last=Brandle |first=Lars |website=Billboard |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> as well as on the [[Some Way|debut single]] from [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]], who was signed by [[XO (record label)|XO]] in January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-the-weeknds-sultry-some-way-collaboration-with-nav-w467422 |title=Hear the Weeknd's Sultry 'Some Way' Collaboration With Nav |last=Blistein |first=John |website=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> He became the first feature utilized by [[Lana Del Rey]], appearing on \"[[Lust for Life (Lana Del Rey song)|Lust for Life]]\", the title track and second single from [[Lust for Life (Lana Del Rey album)|her fifth studio album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.much.com/lana-del-rey-lust-for-life-the-weeknd/ |title=Lana Del Rey Releases 'Lust For Life' Single with the Weeknd |last=Bowsher |first=Allison |website=Much.com |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> He was featured on [[French Montana]]'s \"[[A Lie]]\", the third single from his second album ''[[Jungle Rules]]'' and on [[Cashmere Cat]]'s debut single \"Wild Love\" from his album ''[[9 (Cashmere Cat album)|9]]''. He appeared on the [[Virgil Abloh]]-directed music video for [[Lil Uzi Vert]]'s \"[[XO Tour Llif3]]\" alongside XO signee [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]]. He was later featured on [[Luv Is Rage 2|Lil Uzi Vert's debut album]] and [[Gucci Mane]]'s eleventh studio album ''[[Mr. Davis]].'' He gained a Grammy nomination for [[Best Urban Contemporary Album]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards]] for ''Starboy'' and ended up winning the award.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/entertainment-pmn/newsalert-starboy-wins-best-urban-contemporary-album-for-the-weeknd |title=NewsAlert: Starboy winds best urban contemporary album for the Weeknd |date=January 28, 2018 |work=National Post |access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2018, [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] revealed the full tracklist of the [[Kendrick Lamar]]-curated [[Black Panther (soundtrack)|''Black Panther'' soundtrack album]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/1/tde-black-panther-soundtrack-cover-tracklist |title=TDE Reveals Loaded Tracklist for 'Black Panther' Soundtrack |last=Boykins |first=Austin |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> with Tesfaye featured on one of the tracks, [[Pray for Me (The Weeknd and Kendrick Lamar song)|\"Pray for Me\"]]. On February 2, 2018, it was released as the soundtrack's third single. This marks the second collaboration between Tesfaye and Lamar, after the song [[Sidewalks (song)|\"Sidewalks\"]] on the [[Starboy (album)|''Starboy'']] album.\n\nOn March 27, 2018, Tesfaye began publicity for a new official release in an Instagram post.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8263214/the-weeknd-new-album-instagram |title=Is The Weeknd Dropping a New Album on Friday? |work=Billboard |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vibe.com/2018/03/the-weeknd-dropping-album-rumor-report/ |title=Is The Weeknd Dropping A New Album This Week? |date=March 27, 2018 |work=Vibe |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/music/international/the-weeknd-teases-new-song-release-14133016 |title=The Weeknd teases new song release {{!}} IOL Entertainment |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> On March 29, 2018, a billboard appeared in [[London|London, England]] promoting a possible album titled ''My Dear Melancholy,''<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://clashmusic.com/news/has-someone-accidentally-leaked-news-of-the-weeknds-new-album |title=Has Someone Accidentally Leaked News of the Weeknd's New Album? |work=Clash Magazine |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> and on the same day the project was officially announced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2018/03/the-weeknd-new-album-my-dear-melancholy-announcement/ |title=The Weekend Announces New Album 'My Dear Melancholy,' |last=Sargent |first=Jordan |date=March 29, 2018 |website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2018, the extended play ''[[My Dear Melancholy,]]'' was released.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/stream-the-weeknds-my-dear-melancholy-ep-news.46817.html |title=Stream The Weeknd's \"My Dear Melancholy\" EP |work=HotNewHipHop |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> On June 6, 2018, The Weeknd announced his new [[Beats 1]] radio show ''Memento Mori'', which's first episode was released two days later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459680/the-weeknd-memento-mori-beats-one-radio-show |title=The Weeknd Announces New Beats 1 Radio Show Memento Mori |website=Billboard |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Later in the year, on November 21, 2018, the compilation album ''[[The Weeknd in Japan]]'' was released and served as his first [[greatest hits album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.universal-music.co.jp/the-weeknd/products/uicu-1305/ |title=The Weeknd in Japan (Singles Collection) |publisher=[[Universal Music Group]] |language=Japanese |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8491268/the-weeknd-first-japan-concert-kenshi-yonezu |title=The Weeknd Performs First Japan Show With Special Guest Kenshi Yonezu |website=Billboard |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''After Hours''===\n{{Main|After Hours (The Weeknd album)}}\nIn January 2019, [[Gesaffelstein]] (who previously worked with Tesfaye on ''My Dear Melancholy,'') began teasing a new collaboration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=malQ597Kgq8 |title=Gesaffelstein on Youtube |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> On January 11, 2019, Tesfaye and Gesaffelstein released \"[[Lost in the Fire]]\", the second single off the latter's second studio album, ''[[Hyperion (Gesaffelstein album)|Hyperion]].''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-gesaffelstein-and-the-weeknds-new-song-lost-in-fire/ |title=Listen to Gesaffelstein and the Weeknd's New Song \"Lost in the Fire\" |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> On April 18, 2019, Tesfaye released \"[[Power Is Power]]\" alongside [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] and [[Travis Scott]], a song part of [[For the Throne: Music Inspired by the HBO Series Game of Thrones|a series of music]] inspired by the television show ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', of which Tesfaye himself is a fan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/sza-the-weeknd-travis-scott-power-is-power/ |title=SZAThe WeekndTravis Scott 'Power Is Power' |access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> On May 5, Tesfaye, [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] and [[Travis Scott]] released the music video for their ''[[Game of Thrones (season 8)|Game of Thrones]]''-inspired track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bbnews050619sza-8510131 |title=SZA, The Weeknd and Travis Scott Share Video For 'Game of Thrones' Inspired Track |date=May 5, 2019 |website=Billboard |access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref> On August 30, 2019, during the [[Telluride Film Festival]], Tesfaye made his debut cinematic appearance on the world premiere of the film ''[[Uncut Gems]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/film/weeknd-recorded-music-oneohtrix-point-never-intended-uncut-gems-2546398 |title=The Weeknd recorded music with Oneohtrix Point Never intended for 'Uncut Gems' |date=September 10, 2019 |access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 24, 2019, \"[[Blinding Lights]]\", the expected lead single of his fourth album, was announced via a [[Mercedes-Benz]] commercial on German television.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/24/the-weeknd-new-single-blinding-lights/ |title=The Weeknd to Release New Single 'Blinding Lights' on Black Friday |website=Rap-Up |access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref> The next day, footage of its music video being shot in [[Fremont Street]], [[Las Vegas]] surfaced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/11/25/the-weeknd-shooting-new-music-video-las-vegas/ |title=The Weeknd Shooting New Music Video in Las Vegas |website=TMZ |access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref> News outlets then began reporting that Tesfaye would follow up \"Blinding Lights\" with another single titled \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\".<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1199113637912350720 |user=TheAffinityMag |title=\ud83d\udea8 NEW MUSIC FROM @theweeknd \ud83d\udea8 Abel is dropping 'Blinding Lights' TOMORROW and 'Heartless' on Wednesday. Who's excited?! \ud83e\udd29 |date=November 25, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> After having covered the aforementioned singles on November 25, 2019, the following day, news outlets reported that Tesfaye had registered a song titled \"Like Selena\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a29988087/the-weeknd-selena-gomez-like-selena-song-rumor/ |title=Looks Like The Weeknd Is Releasing a Song About Selena Gomez |last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |date=November 26, 2019 |website=ELLE}}</ref> which was reported to have been possibly named after the singer's ex-girlfriend [[Selena Gomez]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2019/11/the-weeknd-releasing-new-single-titled-like-selena-about-gomez/ |title=The Weeknd Releasing New Single Titled 'Like Selena' About Gomez |date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> In promotion of the upcoming album, episode seven of The Weeknd's ''Memento Mori'' Beats 1 radio show was released on November 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://i.redd.it/fcwg6cv283141.jpg |title=Screenshots of Instagram Story on November 26, 2019 |publisher=YouTube Music |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126214534/https://i.redd.it/fcwg6cv283141.jpg |archive-date=November 26, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The single \"Heartless\" went on to debut at number 32 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and later became his fourth number one single on the chart, the following week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545288/the-weeknd-heartless-five-burning-questions |title=Five Burning Questions: Billboard Staffers Discuss The Weeknd's Top 40 Debut For 'Heartless' |website=Billboard |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> With \"Blinding Lights\" debuting at number 11 on the chart when the aforementioned single topped the chart, and then reaching the top ten on the issue dated February 29, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8551757/the-box-tops-hot-100-7th-week |title=Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Tops Hot 100 For Seventh Week; Dua Lipa Hits Top 5; Justin Bieber, The Weeknd Go Top 10 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=February 24, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545778/the-weeknd-heartless-no-1-hot-100 |title=The Weeknd's 'Heartless' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100, Mariah Carey's 'All I Want for Christmas Is You' Returns to No. 3 High |website=Billboard |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Tesfaye revealed the album's title, ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'', and release date, March 20, 2020, on February 19, 2020, and released the album's [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] as a promotional single simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8551359/the-weeknd-after-hours-release-date-title-track-release |title=The Weeknd Sets 'After Hours' Release Date, Shares Dark Title Track: Listen |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=February 19, 2020 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the album was released on March 20, 2020, containing the singles \"Heartless\", \"Blinding Lights\" and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=Listen to the Weeknd\u2019s New Album After Hours|last=Strauss|first=Matthew|date=March 20, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the album release, on March 29, 2020, Tesfaye announced the release of three more previously unreleased songs: \"Nothing Compares\", \"Missed You\" and \"Final Lullaby\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/1244332030508199936|title=nothing compares, missed you, final lullaby...|via=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesfayes album ''After Hours'' had a second consecutive week at No. 1 on the Hot 100 Songwriters chart (April 2020), due to five entries on the latest ''Billboard'' Hot 100 (singles), all of which he co-wrote and co-produced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9353926/the-weeknd-songwriters-chart-30roc-producers |title=The Weeknd also repeats at No. 1 on the Billboard 200, Hot 100 & Artist 100 |date=April 8, 2020 |website=billboard.com |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\n\nTesfaye cites [[Michael Jackson]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and [[R. Kelly]] as his main musical inspirations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ca.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |title=The Weeknd: Kiss And Tell (2013 Cover Story) |last=Scott |first=Damien |date=July 15, 2013 |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |access-date=June 9, 2015}}</ref> He has attributed Jackson's music as key in spurring him to be a singer, referencing the lyrics to \"[[Dirty Diana]]\" as an example.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He also said his high-flying vocal style was influenced by [[habesha]] singers like [[Aster Aweke]].<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He grew up listening to a variety of music genres, including [[Soul music|soul]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[funk]], [[indie rock]], and [[post-punk]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberts |first=Randall |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/17/entertainment/la-et-ms-weeknd-review-20121217 |title=Review: Abel Tesfaye, a.k.a. The Weeknd, has hall smoldering |date=December 17, 2012 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Tesfaye has said: \"I've always had an admiration for the era before I was born. You can hear it as far back as my first mixtape that the '80s -- [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Cocteau Twins]] -- play such a huge role in my sound.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Weeknd Worried Album Release was Insensitive|publisher=[[Sioux City Journal]] |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402133801/https://siouxcityjournal.com/people/the-weeknd-worried-album-release-was-insensitive/article_2d374595-cb75-5d45-8fc5-bef91ab613ef.html|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye's songs are \"built around a fogged, [[crepuscular]] production\",<ref name=\"Hoby\">{{Cite news |last=Hoby |first=Hermione |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |title=The Weeknd: Sounds and sensibility |date=November 8, 2012 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=January 6, 2013 |location=London |at=section G2, p. 12}}</ref> and feature slow [[tempo]]s,<ref name=\"Cohen\" /> rumbling bass, and forlorn echoes.<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Tesfaye often sings in a [[falsetto]] register,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/12/rookie-of-the-year-2011/ |title=Rookie of the Year: The Weeknd |last=Robbins |first=Winston |date=December 7, 2011 |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> exhibiting an enticing tone. [[J. D. Considine]] finds his singing's \"[[Tremolo|tremulous]] quality\" similar to Michael Jackson, but writes that he eschews Jackson's \"strong basis in the [[blues]]\" for a more [[Arabic music|Arabic]]-influenced [[melisma]].<ref name=\"Considine\" /> Tesfaye possesses a wide light-lyric [[tenor]] vocal range, which spans over three octaves. His vocal range reaches its extreme low at the bass F (F2), and its peak high at the tenor G\u266f (G\u266f5), with a natural [[tessitura]] within the upper fourth octave.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://therangeplace.boards.net/thread/2513/weeknd |title=The Weeknd {{!}} The Range Place |website=therangeplace.boards.net |access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> Tesfaye often makes use of his [[head voice]] in order to build resonance to belt out strong high notes within the fifth octave.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/singing/comments/4a5h7t/how_is_the_weeknd_abel_testaye_singing/ |title=r/singing - How is The Weeknd (Abel Testaye) singing? |website=reddit |access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> His music incorporates [[Sampling (music)|samples]] that are unconventional in R&B production, including [[Punk rock|punk]] and [[alternative rock]].<ref name=\"Considine\">{{Cite news |last=Considine |first=J. D. |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/how-the-weeknd-became-rbs-next-big-thing/article5370329/ |title=How The Weeknd became R&B's next big thing |date=November 17, 2012 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=January 19, 2013 |location=Toronto |author-link=J. D. Considine}}</ref> Marc Hogan of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' says that Tesfaye's samples tend \"to draw from [[rockism|rock critic-approved]] sources, though generally ones that already share elements of his sexual menace\", with samples of artists such as [[Beach House]], Siouxsie and the Banshees and [[Aaliyah]].<ref name=\"Hogan\">{{Cite journal |last=Hogan |first=Marc |date=October 26, 2012 |title=The Weeknd Imbues 'Enemy' With the Smiths' Seductive Power |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/10/the-weeknd-enemy-the-smiths/ |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |location=New York |access-date=January 19, 2013}}</ref> Tesfaye worked mostly with producers [[Illangelo]] and [[Doc McKinney]], whom ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''{{'}}s Ian Cohen credits with developing \"a state-of-the-art [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] template\" with the artist.<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17280-the-trilogy/ |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy |last=Cohen |first=Ian |date=November 13, 2012 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> In concert, Tesfaye reappropriates his digitized productions with a [[Suite (music)|suite]]-like [[arena rock]] aesthetic.<ref name=\"Mistry\" />\n\nHis emotional, plaintive lyrics often express feelings of hurt and deal with subject matter such as sex,<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> drugs, and partying.<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Hermione Hoby of ''[[The Guardian]]'' characterizes Tesfaye's songs as \"narcotised-[[slow jam]]s\" and delineates their message as \"partying is an existential experience, sex is fraught with alienation, and everything registers as unreal and unsettling\".<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Paul MacInnes has stated that he views Tesfaye's three [[mixtapes]] as \"a rough trajectory of party, after-party and [[hangover]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/15/the-weeknd-trilogy-review |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy \u2013 review |date=November 15, 2012 |work=The Guardian |access-date=January 6, 2013 |location=London |at=section G2, p. 23}}</ref> Anupa Mistry of the ''[[Toronto Standard]]'' observes throughout his mixtapes a \"cast of supine, stoned zombie-women ... whose legs willingly part after being plied with substances and who morph into threats only when [he is] [[Comedown (drugs)|coming down]] and feeling vulnerable\".<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Tesfaye has viewed that, by singing vulgar, ignorant lyrics in an elegant, sexy way, he is paying homage to R. Kelly and Prince.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/07/15/the-weeknds-kiss-land-album-captures-first-experiences-outside-of-toronto/ |title=The Weeknd's Kiss Land Album Captures First Experiences Outside Of Toronto |last=Morgan |first=Nakiya |date=July 15, 2013 |publisher=MTV News |access-date=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye has helped broaden R&B's musical palette to incorporate [[Indie music|indie]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] styles; his work has been categorized with the [[alternative R&B]] tag.<ref name=\":2\">Billboard Staff. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6813596/grammys-2016-preview-best-r-and-b-song-best-urban-contemporary-album-nominees-the-weeknd-dangelo-more \"Grammys 2016 Preview: The Weeknd, D'Angelo and More Soulful Singers Nominated for Best R&B Song and Best Urban Contemporary Album\"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard ]]''. February 13, 2016.</ref> Mistry writes that he \"will be obsequiously praised as the future of R&B music\u2014because [he] is a black singer, not because he's making quantifiable, canonical R&B\".<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Andy Kellman categorizes him as an \"alternative R&B act\".<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162 |title=The Weeknd \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |last=Kellman |first=Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> While promoting his third album ''Starboy'', Tesfaye also revealed [[Lana Del Rey]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interview/9711-the-dark-knight-returns-a-conversation-with-the-weeknd/1 |title=The Dark Knight Returns: A Conversation With the Weeknd |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |date=August 31, 2015 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> [[David Bowie]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-weeknd-talks-david-bowie-prince-influences-on-new-album-w448191 |title=The Weeknd Talks David Bowie, Prince Influences on New Album |last=Reed |first=Ryan |date=November 2, 2016 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> [[The Smiths]], [[Bad Brains]], [[Talking Heads]], [[DeBarge]],<ref name=\"bruce\">{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknds_new_album_is_inspired_by_bad_brains_talking_heads_and_the_smiths |title=The Weeknd's New Album Is Inspired by Bad Brains, Talking Heads and the Smiths |last=Slingerland |first=Calum |date=February 6, 2016 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |access-date=September 6, 2016}}</ref> [[50 Cent]], the [[Wu-Tang Clan]],<ref>Sources:\n\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/50-cent-wu-tang-influenced-the-weeknds-starboy-album/ |title=50 Cent and Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album Read More: 50 Cent, Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album |last=Schwadron |first=Eli |website=Xxl |access-date=May 9, 2017}}\n*{{cite web|title=12 Great Songs That Wouldn't Exist Without the Weeknd|authors=Suzy Exposito, Keith Harris, Anupa Mistry, Nick Murray, Brittany Spanos|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 21, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/12-great-songs-that-wouldnt-exist-without-the-weeknd-20151021/drake-hold-on-were-going-home-2013-20151021|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> and [[Eminem]] as influences.<ref>Sources:\n\n*{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W0b6RGdLqTM |title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Crashed Jay Z on 'Renegade,' Talks \"The Hills\" Remix (Nov 24, 2016)}}\n*{{cite web|title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Destroyed 'The Hills' Remix and Jay Z on 'Renegade'|url=http://www.southpawer.com/2016/11/25/the-weeknd-eminem-jay-z-renegade-the-hills-interview/|website=Southpawer|accessdate=November 26, 2016|date=November 25, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|title=The Weeknd on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/653673994240004100?lang=en|website=Twitter|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Business ventures==\nDuring the American leg of his Fall tour promoting ''[[Kiss Land]]'', Tesfaye collaborated with condom-producing company ONE to give away limited-edition condoms at his shows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/52443-the-weeknd-giving-away-kiss-land-condoms/ |title=The Weeknd Giving Away Kiss Land Condoms |last=Battan |first=Carrie |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> They featured the visual identity of the new album with Oxcy \u2013 the album's mascot \u2013 printed on one side.\n\nIn November 2015, to further promote ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'', Tesfaye collaborated with [[Pax Labs]] to release a limited edition version of the PAX 2 vaporizer, an [[electronic cigarette]] that could be used in shows during [[The Madness Fall Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/103135/20151104/weeknd-launches-vape-plays-hit-single-hills-smoke.htm |title=The Weeknd Launches A Vape That Plays His Hit Single 'The Hills' As You Smoke |last=Keating |first=Lauren |date=November 4, 2015 |website=Tech Times |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> The e-cigarette featured the \"xo\" branding on the front, as well as having the ability to play \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\" when turned on.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://porhomme.com/2015/11/the-weeknd-gets-limited-version-of-pax-2-vaporizer/ |title=The Weeknd Gets Limited Version of Pax 2 Vaporizer |date=November 13, 2015 |website=Por Homme |publisher=Pausr Media LLC |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> With the original PAX 2 priced at $279.99, the limited edition e-cigarette cost $324.99.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.joesdaily.com/gear/pax-2-is-a-refined-and-durable-vaporizer-unlike-any-other/ |title=PAX 2 is a Refined and Durable Vaporizer Unlike Any Other |last=Miragliotta |first=Joe |date=February 4, 2016 |website=GQ |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> PAX also acted as an official sponsor for the tour, presenting special backstage VIP activations for fans who bought packages that included the e-cigarette.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sidewalkhustle.com/pax-labs-x-the-weeknd-presents-the-madness-tour-limited-edition-pax-2/ |title=Pax Labs X The Weeknd Presents The Madness Tour Limited Edition Pax 2 |last=Banning |first=Tristan |website=Sidewalk Hustle |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"theverge.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/4/9663712/the-weekend-pax-labs-vaporizer-limited-edition |title=The Weeknd is teaming up with Pax Labs to create the ultimate fashion vape |last=Cox |first=Jamieson |date=November 4, 2015 |website=The Verge |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> PAX Labs chief marketing officer Richard Mumby stated \"Music and fashion have always been a natural fit for Pax...This was the perfect opportunity to bring together The Weeknd's style with our technology.\"<ref name=\"theverge.com\" />\n\nIn 2016, Tesfaye announced a partnership with [[Puma SE|Puma]], as a Global Brand ambassador, for the company's \"Run the Streets\" campaign. It was launched in early November, with the final collection made available to coincide with the release of his album ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/style/2016/09/the-weeknd-partners-puma-creative-collaborator-ambassador |title=The Weeknd Partners With Puma as New Creative Collaborator and Ambassador |last=Mench |first=Chris |website=Complex |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> He also hosted several [[pop-up retail]] stores for the \"Starboy: Limited Capsule\" collection,<ref name=\"bustle.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-are-the-weeknds-pop-up-shops-if-you-live-in-one-of-these-eight-cities-youre-in-luck-55779 |title=Where Are The Weeknd's Pop-Up Shops? If You Live in One Of These Eight Cities, You're in Luck |last=Tucker |first=Alexa |website=Bustle |access-date=May 6, 2017}}</ref> which were available across [[North America]], including [[New York City]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/style/2017/05/the-weeknd-starboy-2-5-united-states-canada-pop-up-shops-lookbook |title=Here's Your First Look at the Weeknd's Starboy 2017 Pop-Up Shop Collection |last=Espinoza |first=Joshua |website=Complex |access-date=May 6, 2017}}</ref> With this partnership, Tesfaye also released three capsule collections named PUMA X XO including T-shirts, caps, sweatpants, bomber jackets and a pair of shoes called the Parallels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/8/the-weeknd-puma-parallel-sneaker-collection |title=The Weeknd and PUMA Officially Unveil Their \"Parallel\" Sneaker |website=Hypebeast |publisher=Hypebeast}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/11/he-weeknd-x-puma-xo-collection-nyc |title=A Closer Look at The Weeknd x PUMA XO Collection Launch in NYC |website=Hypebeast |publisher=Hypebeast}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye has also begun his own XO branded merchandise, which was furthered by a collaboration with [[H&M]] to present its Spring 2017 campaign. The campaign would feature new collaborative pieces developed with the singer's brand, and was released on March 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.hm.com/en_cn/life/culture/inside-h-m/the-weeknd-teams-with-h-m-on-curated-mens-collection.html |title=The Weeknd Teams With H&M on Curated Men's Collection |website=H&M |publisher=Hennes & Mauritz}}</ref> Tesfaye collaborated with H&M again for a fall collection, however, after an incident which he described as \"deeply offensive\" in 2018, he cut ties with the company.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-cuts-ties-with-hm-over-deeply-offensive-photo/ |title=The Weeknd Cuts Ties With H&M Over \"Deeply Offensive\" Photo |last=Yoo |first=Noah |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Tesfaye had a limited edition [[Pop-up retail|pop up]] sale for the \"Starboy 2017 Limited Capsule Collection\".<ref name=\"bustle.com\" /> The collections were available in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Miami Beach, Houston, Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nTesfaye has collaborated with artists and designers such as Kidult, [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/11/wangxo-apparel |title=HYPEBEAST Exclusive: WANGXO Apparel Collection |last=Hasse |first=Lemola |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> and [[Futura (graffiti artist)|Futura]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/4/the-weeknd-futura-xo-capsule-better-look |title=A Better Look at The Weeknd and Futura's Limited-Edition XO Capsule Collection |last=Sajonas |first=Felson |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> for small-lived and sometimes exclusive capsule collections.\n\nIn October 2017, Tesfaye began marketing and promotion on a partnership with [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] on [[Instagram]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/10/the-weeknd-cryptic-image-marvel-collaboration |title=The Weeknd Teases a Cryptic Image Hinting Towards a Collaborative Project With Marvel |last=Patos |first=Robert |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> A week later, he attended [[New York Comic-Con]] and it was revealed that a [[Starboy (song)|Starboy]] comic book would be released on June 13, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/10/the-weeknd-marvel-to-release-starboy-comic-book/ |title=THE WEEKND TEAMS UP WITH MARVEL TO RELEASE 'STARBOY' COMIC BOOK |last=Coleman II |first=C. Vernon |website=XXL |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> with the title character being a superhero modelled after himself.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8257745/marvel-the-weeknd-starboy-comic-book-release-date |title=Marvel Unveils 'The Weeknd Presents: Starboy' Comic Book Release Date |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[XO (record label)|XO]] released a collection of apparel in collaboration with [[A Bathing Ape]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/bape-x-xo |title=BAPE\u00ae x XO |website=us.bape.com |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/the-weeknd-bape-summer-2018-capsule/ |title=The Weeknd x BAPE Summer Capsule Collection Dropping August 4 |date=July 30, 2018 |website=Highsnobiety  |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> They released another collection in January 2020. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-xo-bape-collection/ |title=The Weeknd Reveals Latest XO And BAPE Capsule Collection {{!}} uDiscover |last=Stavropoulos |first=Laura |date=January 8, 2020 |website=uDiscover Music |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Tesfaye bought ownership in [[esports]] company OverActive Media Group, the owners of [[Splyce]] and [[Overwatch League]] team [[Toronto Defiant]], and will serve as the company's [[Brand ambassador|global ambassador]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/weeknd-overactive-overwatch-1.5091861 |title=The Weeknd signs on as part owner, global ambassador of esports firm |date=April 10, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTesfaye began dating model [[Bella Hadid]] at the beginning of 2015; the couple were first seen together in May at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style-blog/wp/2015/09/11/kylie-jenner-and-bella-hadid-are-18-their-boyfriends-are-25-why-do-their-relationships-elicit-such-different-reactions/ |title=Kylie Jenner and Bella Hadid are 18. Their boyfriends are 25. Why do their relationships elicit such different reactions |last=McDonald |first=Soraya Nadia |date=September 11, 2015 |website=The Washington Post |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a31091/bella-hadid-19th-birthday/ |title=Bella Hadid Spends Her Birthday Weekend with the Weeknd |last=Lindig |first=Sarah |date=October 10, 2015 |website=Elle |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref> Hadid later starred in his music video \"[[In the Night (The Weeknd song)|In the Night]]\" in December. They also made a [[red carpet]] appearance as a couple at the [[2016 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.popsugar.com/celebrity/Weeknd-Bella-Hadid-Grammys-2016-40199219#photo-40199219 |title=The Weeknd and Bella Hadid Made Their Red Carpet Debut at the Grammys |last=Sisavat |first=Monica |website=Popsugar Celebrity |access-date=June 6, 2016}}</ref> On November 11, 2016, it was reported that the couple had split; citing their conflicting schedules as the rationale for the relationship's termination.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.com/music/the-weeknd-bella-hadid-split/ |title=The Weeknd and Bella Hadid Have Split: 'They Still Have a Great Deal of Love for One Another' |last=Tracy |first=Brianne |website=People |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye reportedly started dating [[Selena Gomez]] in January 2017 and they moved in together temporarily in September 2017 in [[Greenwich Village, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.com/music/everything-we-know-selena-gomez-weeknd/ |title=Everything We Know About Selena Gomez and The Weeknd's Whirlwind Romance |last=Yagoda |first=Maria |date=May 25, 2017 |website=People |access-date=September 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/exclusive-selena-gomez-and-weeknd-temporarily-move-apartment-together-new-york-city-86975 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Selena Gomez and The Weeknd Temporarily Move Into an Apartment Together in New York City |last=Murphy |first=Desiree |date=September 11, 2017 |website=Entertainment Tonight |access-date=September 12, 2017}}</ref> They broke up in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chiu |first=Melody |url=http://people.com/music/selena-gomez-the-weeknd-breakup/ |title=Selena Gomez and The Weeknd Split After 10 Months Together |date=October 30, 2017 |work=People |access-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref> By May 2018, Tesfaye and Hadid began dating again,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/music/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-second-outing-cannes-film-festival/ |title=Bella Hadid and The Weeknd Let Loose at Cannes Film Festival 1 Day After Kissing |last=Paasquini |first=Maria |date=May 12, 2018 |website=People |access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> before splitting again in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a28625896/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-breakup-2019-reason/ |title=Why Bella Hadid and The Weeknd Reportedly Broke Up for the Second Time |date=August 6, 2019 |website=Elle}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye often used drugs to help get over [[writer's block]] on earlier albums and also abused illegal substances such as \"... Ketamine, cocaine, MDMA, mushrooms and cough syrup\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/weeknd-opens-dark-past/story?id=43987671 |title=The Weeknd Opens Up About His 'Dark' Past |last=Fisher |first=Luchina |date=December 5, 2016 |publisher=ABC News |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Speaking in December 2013, Tesfaye said that drugs were a \"crutch\" for him when it came to writing music.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/weeknd-opens-drug-use-1888046 |title=The Weeknd opens up about 'heavy' drug use - NME |date=December 3, 2016 |work=NME |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> On [[social media]] he typically suffixed his first name with \"xo\".<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> According to writer Hermione Hoby, it is meant as an [[emoticon]] for \"[[hugs and kisses|a kiss and a hug]]\",<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> while [[VH1]]'s Zara Golden's stated that it is a reference to his recreational use of [[ecstasy (drug)|ecstasy]] and [[oxycodone]].<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-11-16/who-is-the-weeknd-5-things-you-should-know |title=Who Is The Weeknd? 5 Things You Should Know |last=Golden |first=Zara |date=November 16, 2012 |publisher=[[VH1]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127024250/http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-11-16/who-is-the-weeknd-5-things-you-should-know |archive-date=January 27, 2013 |access-date=August 16, 2013}}</ref> He later altered the handles on his social media to reflect his stage name in preparation for the release of ''Starboy''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torchonline.com/entertainment/arts-culture/2012/02/21/the-weeknd-is-ready-for-take-off/ |title=The Weeknd is ready for take-off |last=Dow |first=Gabriele |website=the Torch |publisher=St. John's University |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye's hairstyle has been claimed to be partly inspired by [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]] and has been described as his most recognizable trait.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> In an interview, he detailed that he began growing it out in 2011, and remarked at the easiness in maintaining it, with \"a hard shampoo every once in a while\".<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He eventually cut his hair in 2016 prior to the release of [[Starboy (album)|''Starboy'']].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7518696/80s-90s-artists-inspired-the-weeknd-new-haircut |title=5 '80s & '90s Artists Who May Have Inspired The Weeknd's New Haircut |website=Billboard |access-date=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his leisure time, he enjoys watching television<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama/ |title=The Weeknd Reveals How He Got His Name... And Where the 'E' Went |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |publisher=MTV |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> and is an avid video game fan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/15/madness-tour-the-weeknd-travis-scott-visonelie-photos |title=What It's Really Like To Be On Tour with the Weeknd And Travis Scott |last=Sowunmi |first=Jordan |website=Fader |access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitalxtra.com/features/pictures/best-instagram/27th-january/the-weeknd-playing-mario-kart/ |title=The Weeknd spent some time off playing Mario Kart. |website=CapitalXtra |access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref> In the context of media outlets reporting cases of police brutality, in 2016, he expressed disdain, tweeting \"blue lives murder\".<ref name=\"The Weeknd on Twitter\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/751143768833732608?lang=en |title=The Weeknd on Twitter |website=Twitter |access-date=May 5, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/751143486590623744?lang=en |title=The Weeknd on Twitter |website=Twitter |access-date=May 5, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-6-1194305 |title=The Weeknd has donated $250,000 to Black Lives Matter |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=August 14, 2016 |website=Time |access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref> In May 2016, Tesfaye and [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] cancelled an appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' due to [[Donald Trump]] being present.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/culture/2016/05/27/3782672/weeknd-400-prominent-writers-protest-donald-trump/ |title=Trump Inspires The Weeknd To Cancel Jimmy Kimmel Performance |last=Goldstein |first=Jessica |website=Thinkprogress |publisher=CENTER FOR AMERICAN PROGRESS ACTION FUND |access-date=May 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legal issues===\nIn January 2015, Tesfaye was arrested for punching a [[Las Vegas Police Department|Las Vegas]] police officer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6436581/the-weeknd-arrested-for-punching-las-vegas-police-officer |title=The Weeknd Arrested For Punching Las Vegas Police Officer |last=Stutz |first=Colin |website=Billboard |access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye pleaded [[no contest]], and was sentenced to 50 hours of [[community service]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/10/22/the-weeknd-no-contest-punching-cop/ |title=The Weeknd Pleads No Contest To Punching a Cop |website=TMZ |access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2015, Tesfaye was sued by Cutting Edge Music, who alleged that the [[bass line]] for \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\" had been taken from a composition featured in the score for ''[[The Machine (film)|The Machine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/12/09/the-weeknd-the-hills-lawsuit/ |title=THE WEEKND SUED OVER 'THE HILLS' |website=Tmz |access-date=May 12, 2017}}</ref> In September 2018, Tesfaye and [[Daft Punk]] were sued for allegedly stealing the rhythm from a self-described poet, singer and songwriter named Yasminah.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/09/18/the-weeknd-daft-punk-lawsuit-starboy-stolen/ |title=The Weeknd and Daft Punk Sued for Stealing 'Starboy' |website=TMZ}}</ref> Tesfaye has denied these allegations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-denies-stealing-starboy-beat-from-somali-american-singer-news.80542.html |title=The Weeknd Denies Stealing \"Starboy\" Beat From Somali-American Singer |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nPrior to being presented a Bikila Award for Professional Excellence in 2014, Tesfaye donated $50,000 towards a class at the [[University of Toronto]] on [[Ge'ez]], the classic language of Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carissimo |first=Justin |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-the-university-of-toronto-to-help-start-an-ethiopic-studies-program-a7177606.html |title=The Weeknd donates $50,000 to language class at the University of Toronto |date=August 7, 2016 |access-date=August 7, 2016 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In August 2016 he continued donations to the University of Toronto, in the creation of a new [[Ethiopian Studies|Ethiopic Studies]] program.<ref name=\"Time\" />\n\nIn May 2016 Tesfaye has also donated $50,000 for the St. Mary Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church in Toronto, Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ethiosports.com/2016/05/02/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-st-mary-ethiopian-orthodox-church-in-toronto/ |title=The Weeknd Donates $50,000 To St. Mary Ethiopian Orthodox Church in Toronto |last=Lockett |first=Dee |date=May 2, 2016 |website=Ethiosports |publisher=Samuel Yeshiwas}}</ref> In August 2016, Tesfaye also donated $250,000 to [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/11/the-weeknd-black-lives-matter-beyonce-jay-z-drake |title=The Weeknd gives $250,000 to Black Lives Matter |date=August 11, 2016 |website=The Guardian |access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Time\" /> In December 2015, he worked with [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s foundation to visit [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta|Children's Hospital in Atlanta]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theybf.com/2015/12/17/the-weeknd-does-charity-work-amidst-cheating-rumors-do-gooder-2-chainz-donates-minivan-to |title=The Weeknd Does Charity Work Amidst Cheating Rumors + Do-Gooder 2 Chainz Donates Minivan To Family With Brain Damaged Son |last=Natasha |website=Young, Black & Fabulous |access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Tesfaye donated $100,000 to the Suubi Health Center, a maternity and children's medical facility in Budondo, Uganda. Tesfaye was inspired to support the center after learning of his friend [[French Montana]]'s work with Global Citizen and Mama Hope to help raise awareness for Suubi and the people of Uganda.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/858296/the-weeknd-donates-100-000-to-health-center-in-uganda |title=The Weeknd Donates $100,000 to Health Center in Uganda |access-date=January 9, 2018 |publisher=E!}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd}}\nTesfaye has won three [[Grammy Award]]s, eight [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], two [[American Music Award]]s, nine [[Juno Award]]s,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |last=Bell |first=David |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/junos-sunday-night-1.3517082 |title=The Weeknd really cleaned up this Juno Awards weekend |date=April 3, 2016 |access-date=March 2, 2017 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> and has been nominated for one [[Academy Award]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|The Weeknd discography}}\n<!-- Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works\". Studio albums only. -->\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Kiss Land]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' (2020)\n<!-- STUDIO ALBUMS ONLY! Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works\". -->\n\n== Tours ==\n* King of the Fall Tour (2014)\n* [[The Madness Fall Tour]] (2015)\n* [[Starboy: Legend of the Fall Tour]] (2017)\n* [[The Weeknd Asia Tour]] (2018)\n* [[The After Hours Tour]] (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikimedia|collapsible=true|c=Category:The Weeknd|d=Q2121062|voy=no|v=no|species=no|wikt=no|b=no|s=no|n=no}}\n* {{official website|http://www.theweeknd.com}}\n\n{{The Weeknd}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd|Awards for The Weeknd]]\n|list =\n{{Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporany Album}}\n{{Juno Award for Artist of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Canada|Music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weeknd}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Amharic-language singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ethiopian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian record producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Canadian tenors]]\n[[Category:Singers with a three-octave vocal range]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Single of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Republic Records artists]]\n[[Category:XO (record label)]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Artist of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Songwriter of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:People involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:The Weeknd| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Weekend (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|Canadian singer, songwriter, actor and record producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = The Weeknd\n| image              = FEQ July 2018 The Weeknd (44778856382) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = The Weeknd during a show in 2018\n| birth_name         = Abel Makkonen Tesfaye\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1990|2|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* actor \n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| partner            = \n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd|Full list]]\n| website            = {{URL|theweeknd.com}}\n| signature          = Logo de The Weeknd.png\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed        = yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[alternative R&B]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|<!-- Only add acts whose collaborations have been significant to his career.-->\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]]\n* [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]]\n* [[Doc McKinney]]\n* [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n* [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Abel Makkonen Tesfaye''' (born February 16, 1990), known professionally as '''The Weeknd''', is a Canadian singer, songwriter, actor and record producer.<ref name=\"sex-drugs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/sex-drugs-and-rb-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-176091/ |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |last=Eells |first=Josh |date=October 21, 2015 |website=Rolling Stone |access-date=July 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2010, he anonymously uploaded several songs to [[YouTube]] under the name \"The Weeknd\" and released the [[mixtape]]s ''[[House of Balloons]]'', ''[[Thursday (album)|Thursday]]'', and ''[[Echoes of Silence]]'' in 2011 which quickly gained him a following and recognition from several mainstream publications due to his dark style of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and the mystique surrounding his identity[[Contemporary R&B|.]]<ref name=\"happy\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/house-of-balloons/critic-reviews |title=House of Balloons \u2013 The Weeknd |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> \n\n''House of Balloons'', ''Thursday'', and ''Echoes of Silence''  were later remastered and re-released on the compilation album ''[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]]'' (2012). In 2013, The Weeknd released his debut album ''[[Kiss Land]]'' and followed it up with ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' (2015), the latter of which became his first [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] number-one album, and featured the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one singles \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\" and \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\". At the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th Grammy Awards]], ''Beauty Behind the Madness'' won [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]] and was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]. A year after the release of the album, The Weeknd released his third album ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]'' (2016), which spawned the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one hit [[Starboy (song)|of the same name]]. His first EP ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' (2018) debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, and preceded his fourth album ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' (2020). It was critically acclaimed, and featured the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" and \"[[Blinding Lights]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11323/The-Weeknd-After-Hours.aspx|title=After Hours by The Weeknd reviews {{!}} Any Decent Music|website=www.anydecentmusic.com|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Weeknd has won three [[Grammy Award]]s, two [[American Music Award]]s, nine [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], nine [[Juno Award]]s, and has been nominated for an [[Academy Award]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/the-weeknd |title=The Weeknd |publisher=The Recording Academy |access-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> He holds several chart records, being the first artist to simultaneously hold the top three positions on the [[R&B Songs|''Billboard'' Hot R&B Songs]] chart with \"Can't Feel My Face\", \"[[Earned It]]\", and \"The Hills\", while \"The Hills\" was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/ |title=Gold & Platinum |website=RIAA |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> One of the most successful Canadian recording artists, The Weeknd was awarded the [[Allan Slaight Award]] by [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] for \"making a positive impact in the fields of music, film, literature, visual or performing arts, sports, innovation or philanthropy\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/story/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame |title=THE WEEKND HONOURED WITH ALLAN SLAIGHT AWARD FROM CANADA'S WALK OF FAME |date=February 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214052542/http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/story/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame |archive-date=February 14, 2015 |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAbel Makkonen Tesfaye was born on February 16, 1990 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], and was raised in the district of [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], in the city's east end.<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"allmusic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162/biography |title=The Weeknd Biography |last=Kellman |first=Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFl8uYyO?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162/biography |archive-date=October 13, 2015 |access-date=October 13, 2015}}</ref> He is the only child of Makkonen and Samra Tesfaye, who were [[Ethiopian Canadians|Ethiopian immigrants to Canada]] in the late 1980s.<ref name=\"jcaramanica\">{{Cite news |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/magazine/can-the-weeknd-turn-himself-into-the-biggest-pop-star-in-the-world.html |title=Can The Weeknd Turn Himself into the Biggest Pop Star in the World? |date=July 27, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFlDxFgo?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/magazine/can-the-weeknd-turn-himself-into-the-biggest-pop-star-in-the-world.html?_r=0 |archive-date=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RStone\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sex-drugs-and-r-b-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-20151021 |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |date=October 21, 2015 |access-date=October 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mistry\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.torontostandard.com/culture/daily-disc-the-weeknds-echoes-of-silence |title=Daily Disc: The Weeknd's 'Echoes Of Silence' |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |website=[[Toronto Standard]] |publisher=MeshSquared Ventures |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"RSinterview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/sex-drugs-and-rb-inside-the-weeknds-dark-twisted-fantasy-176091/ |title=Sex, Drugs and R&B: Inside The Weeknd's Dark Twisted Fantasy |last=Eeels |first=Josh |date=October 21, 2015 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Wenner Media LLC]] |access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye was raised by his grandmother and mother after his parents split up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/the-weeknd-trivia_us_56bb63cfe4b08ffac1236c5e |title=9 things You Need To Know About The Weeknd |last=Ledbetter |first=Carly |date=February 11, 2016 |publisher=[[Huffpost News]] |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> While living with his grandmother Tesfaye learned [[Amharic]], which he also spoke with his mother,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/the-weeknd-reddit-ama-interview.html |title=The Weeknd Reveals The Origin Of His Name + More |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> and attended [[Ethiopian Orthodox]] church services.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /><ref name=\"where the e went\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama.jhtml |title=The Weeknd Reveals How He Got His Name... And Where The 'E' Went |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |date=September 13, 2013 |publisher=[[MTV News]] |access-date=September 15, 2013}}</ref> When asked about his father in an interview, Tesfaye stated: \"I saw him vaguely when I was six, and then again when I was 11 or 12, and he had a new family and kids. I don't even know where he lived \u2014 I'd see him for, like, a night. I'm sure he's a great guy. I never judged him. He wasn't abusive, he wasn't an alcoholic, he wasn't an asshole. He just wasn't there.\"<ref name=\"RSinterview\" />\n\nTesfaye describes his teenage years as the film \"''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'' without the [[AIDS]]\". Tesfaye states he began smoking [[marijuana]] at age 11, and later moved on to [[hard drugs|harder drugs]]. Tesfaye claims he often shoplifted to supplement his use of [[MDMA|ecstasy]], [[oxycodone]], [[xanax]], [[cocaine]], [[Psilocybin mushroom|psilocybin]], and [[ketamine]].<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/5-things-you-should-know-about-the-weeknd |title=10 Things You Should Know About the Weeknd |last=Wagstaff |first=Keith |last2=Swanson |first2=David |website=GQ |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye attended [[West Hill Collegiate Institute]] and [[Birchmount Park Collegiate Institute]] in Scarborough, from which he did not graduate, leaving altogether in 2007,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/6163335-scarborough-native-the-weeknd-scores-seven-grammy-nominations/ |title=Scarborough native The Weeknd scores seven Grammy nominations |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe and Mail: Mistry\">{{Cite news |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/why-the-weeknd-is-truly-torontos-very-own/article27053702/ |title=Why The Weeknd is truly Toronto's very own |date=October 30, 2015 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=December 26, 2016}}</ref> after which he also left home. Tesfaye moved to the [[Parkdale, Toronto|Parkdale]] neighborhood of Toronto. Tesfaye has credited his stage name as being inspired by his high school dropout status, claiming \"after [he] left one weekend and never came home\", though producer Jeremy Rose claims the name was his idea.<ref name=\"McGuire\">{{Cite journal |last=McGuire |first=Patrick |date=April 2012 |title=How the Producer of The Weeknd's Breakout Tracks Got Majorly Screwed |url=https://www.vice.com/read/how-the-producer-of-the-weeknds-breakout-tracks-got-majorly-screwed |journal=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |location=New York |access-date=March 3, 2013}}</ref> The spelling was modified in order to avoid trademark issues with the Canadian band [[The Weekend (Canadian band)|The Weekend]].<ref name=\"jcaramanica\" /><ref name=\"where the e went\" />\n\n==Career==\n===2010\u20132011: Career beginnings===\n{{main|House of Balloons|Thursday (album)|Echoes of Silence}}\nTesfaye met Jeremy Rose in 2010, a producer who had an idea for a dark [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] musical project<!-- not a typo; cited in the source -->. After initially trying to pitch the idea to musician [[Curtis Santiago]], Rose played one of his instrumentals for Tesfaye, who [[freestyle rap]]ped over it. This led to the two collaborating on an album. Rose produced three songs \u2013 \"What You Need\", \"Loft Music\", and \"The Morning\" \u2013 and others that Tesfaye had rapped on, which were ultimately scrapped. Rose let Tesfaye keep the tracks he had produced under the condition that he would ultimately be credited for them.<ref name=\"McGuire\" /> In December 2010, Tesfaye uploaded \"What You Need\", \"Loft Music\" and \"The Morning\" to [[YouTube]] under his stage name,<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite news |last=Caramanica A-Train |first=Jon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/02/arts/music/02playlist.html?_r=4&ref=music |title=Screams That Charmed, and Other Overlooked Highlights |date=December 26, 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref> although his identity was initially unknown.<ref name=\"pforkwynreview\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/12131-what-you-need/ |title=The Playlist \u2013 The Weeknd \u2013 ''What You Need'' |last=Fitzmaurice |first=Larry |date=March 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326174005/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/12131-what-you-need |archive-date=March 26, 2011 |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"washpost\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/03/14/AR2011031403984.html |title=Singles File: Da Phuture, The Weeknd, Fever Ray |last=Stewart |first=Allison |date=March 14, 2011 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref> The songs drew some attention online, and were later included in a blog post from [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]].<ref name=\"McGuire\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thirteen.org/riffcity/music/love-and-other-drugs-the-weeknds-altered-state-rb/ |title=Love and Other Drugs: The Weeknd's Altered-State R&B |last=Shepherd |first=Julianne Escobedo |date=March 23, 2011 |publisher=[[WNET]] |access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The songs subsequently received coverage from various media outlets, including [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] and ''[[The New York Times]]''. Before adopting the stage name \"The Weeknd\", he worked under the aliases of \"The Noise\" and \"Kin Kane\".<ref name=\"RStone\" />\n\nTesfaye took to his Twitter to mention that his extended play, ''Noise,'' were \"a bunch of songs leaked by salty producers and found AFTER HOB dropped.\" He says that they were demos that he had written as a teenager to try and get recognition. The EP consists of 10 tracks, some of which influenced his debut mixtape, [[House of Balloons|''House of Balloon''s]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/263753618484760577?lang=en |title=@theweeknd Twitter |last=Tesfaye |first=Abel |date=October 31, 2012 |website=Twitter |access-date=May 7, 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2011, Tesfaye [[self-released]] his debut mixtape ''[[House of Balloons]]''.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{Cite web |url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/03/21/say-hello-to-the-weeknd-drake-co-signs/ |title=Say Hello to The Weeknd, Drake Co-Signs |last=Ramirez |first=Erika |date=March 21, 2011 |publisher=MTV |access-date=March 29, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbcmusic.ca/posts/17548/cohen-gould-buffy-25-best-canadian-debut-albums \"25 best Canadian debut albums ever\"]. ''CBC Music'', June 16, 2017.</ref> The mixtape included production from Canadian producers [[Illangelo]] and [[Doc McKinney]], and included the tracks produced by Rose, although, he did not receive production credits.<ref name=\"McGuire\" /> ''House of Balloons'' was met with critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/house-of-balloons/the-weeknd |title=House of Balloons Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 3, 2013}}</ref> It was named as one of ten shortlisted nominees for the [[2011 Polaris Music Prize]].<ref name=\"shortlist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.polarismusicprize.ca/2011/ |title=Polaris Music Prize |website=Polaris Music Prize |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409053023/http://www.polarismusicprize.ca/2011/ |archive-date=April 9, 2014 |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye began a tour of [[Toronto]], with his first live performance at the city's [[Mod Club]] venue. Drake was in attendance to view the performance, which ran for a total of ninety minutes.<ref>Ritchie, Kevin (July 25, 2011). [http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/music/story.cfm?content=181922 The Weeknd's perfect premiere].''[[NOW Toronto]]''. Retrieved March 28, 2012</ref> Drake approached Tesfaye and described a potential musical collaboration between the pair. Tesfaye accompanied Drake at his various shows, often performing as the opening act for shows scheduled at the [[Molson Canadian Amphitheatre]], as well as appearing at the second annual [[OVO Fest]] in July.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/42716-the-weeknd-to-play-drakes-ovo-festival/ |title=The Weeknd to Play Drake's OVO Festival |last=Fitzmaurice |first=Larry |date=July 3, 2011 |access-date=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Over the summer of 2011, Tesfaye contributed to four songs on Drake's ''[[Take Care (album)|Take Care]]'', both as a writer and a featured artist.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Berry |first=Peter A. |url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/drake-the-weeknd-wrote-take-care/ |title=Drake Sets The Record Straight On How Much The Weeknd Wroteon Take Care Album |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=April 15, 2019 |publisher=XXL Mag}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye refrained from participating in interviews, choosing to communicate via [[Twitter]], after the album was released.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lau |first=Melody |date=July 25, 2011 |title=Mysterious R&B singer sells out first show |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/drake-protege-the-weeknd-proves-hes-no-fluke-in-live-debut-20110725 |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> This was credited{{By whom|date=June 2019}} as an advertising tactic for Tesfayes second mixtape ''[[Thursday (album)|Thursday]]'', which was released on August 18, 2011.<ref name=\"npost\">Dunlevy, T'Cha (March 23, 2012). [http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/20/365-days-of-weeknd-we-chart-abel-tesfayes-rise-to-fame-a-year-after-house-of-balloons/ \"365 days of Weeknd: We chart Abel Tesfaye's rise to fame a year after House of Balloons\"] {{webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120321220120/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/20/365%2Ddays%2Dof%2Dweeknd%2Dwe%2Dchart%2Dabel%2Dtesfayes%2Drise%2Dto%2Dfame%2Da%2Dyear%2Dafter%2Dhouse%2Dof%2Dballoons/ |date=March 21, 2012 }} .''[[National Post]]''. Retrieved March 27, 2012</ref> Tesfaye's third mixtape ''[[Echoes of Silence]]'' was released on December 21, 2011, a year after his debut singles.<ref name=npost/><ref>The Weeknd's Official site [http://the-weeknd.com/ Official Site]. Retrieved March 28, 2012</ref>\n\nFollowing this release, the three mixtapes were collectively known as the ''Balloons Trilogy'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/echoes-of-silence-the-weeknd-reveals-final-part-of-the-balloons-trilogy-77249 |title=Echoes Of Silence The Weeknd reveals final part of the Balloons Trilogy The Line Of Best Fit |date=December 22, 2011 |publisher=theLineofBestFit.com |access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref> and saw Tesfaye receiving offers from various record labels.{{Which|date=June 2019}}<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\n===2012\u20132014: ''Trilogy'' and ''Kiss Land''===\n{{main|Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Kiss Land}}\n[[File:The Weeknd by David Hwang.jpg|thumb|Tesfaye performing at Coachella in 2012.]]\nIn April 2012, Tesfaye began his first tour of the United States, with a performance at the [[Coachella Festival]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/46157-watch-the-weeknds-entire-coachella-set/ |title=Abel Tesfaye makes his U.S. debut |last=Snapes |first=Laura |date=April 16, 2012 |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> The tour culminated in New York with back-to-back sold-out shows, which were positively reviewed by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref name=\"tour\" /><ref name=\"Stones\">{{Cite journal |last=Krishnamurthy |first=Sowmya |date=April 29, 2012 |title=The Weeknd Mesmerizes at Bowery Ballroom |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-weeknd-mesmerizes-at-bowery-ballroom-20120429 |journal=Rolling Stone |location=New York |access-date=May 27, 2012}}</ref> Tesfaye expanded his tour to accompany Europe, performing at various European festivals, including the [[Primavera Sound Festival]]s in Spain and Portugal,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://prettymuchamazing.com/news/the-weeknd-announces-first-ever-tour |title=The Weeknd announces first ever tour |last=Tovar |first=Luis |publisher=prettymuchamazing.com |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> and the [[Wireless Festival]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wirelessfestival.co.uk/line-up/ |title=Wireless line up 2012 |publisher=wirelessfestival.co.uk |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316180853/http://www.wirelessfestival.co.uk/line-up/ |archive-date=March 16, 2012 |access-date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> Covering \"[[Dirty Diana]]\" at his performance in London, he received positive responses from both [[Katy Perry]] and [[Florence Welch]], who noted the singer's ability to successfully undertake a complex song.<ref name=\"June\">{{Cite journal |title=The Weeknd covers Michael Jackson as he plays his debut UK show |url=http://www.nme.com/news/weekend--3/64204 |journal=[[NME]] |location=London |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref> In June, the ''Balloons Trilogy'' was revealed to have been downloaded over 8 million times, which allowed Tesfaye to initiate formal commercial release of the projects later that year.<ref name=\"June\" />\n\nIn September 2012, Tesfaye signed with [[Republic Records]] in a joint venture with his own [[Imprint label|imprint]] [[XO (record label)|XO]].<ref name=\"Hampp\">{{Cite journal |last=Hampp |first=Andrew |date=November 12, 2012 |title=The Weeknd & Reps Talk Clearing Samples, Touring For 'Trilogy' Release |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474219/the-weeknd-reps-talk-clearing-samples-touring-for-trilogy-release |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |location=New York |access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref> The compilation album for the mixtapes entitled ''[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]]'', was released two months later, and consisted of several remastered versions of songs, as well as three additional ones.<ref name=\"pitchfork.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/48066-the-weeknd-shares-rolling-stone-video-trilogy-artwork |title=The Weeknd Shares 'Rolling Stone' Video, Trilogy Artwork |last=Battan |first=Carrie |date=October 2, 2012 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=December 30, 2012}}</ref> It also officially credited Rose as a producer and writer on the three songs from ''House of Balloons'' for which he did not initially receive credit.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=[[Trilogy (The Weeknd album)|Trilogy]] |others=The Weeknd |year=2012 |type=CD liner notes |publisher=[[Republic Records]] |id=3719793}}</ref> ''Trilogy'' charted at number four on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with first-week sales of 86,000 copies. It also debuted at number five on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], with similar sales.<ref name=\"bb\">{{Cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=The weeknd|chart=all}} |title=Trilogy&nbsp;\u2013 The Weeknd |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=November 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Caulfield\">{{Cite journal |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |date=October 10, 2012 |title=One Direction Tops Billboard 200 Chart, 'Twilight' Debuts at No. 3 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474052/one-direction-tops-billboard-200-chart-twilight-debuts-at-no-3 |journal=Billboard |location=Los Angeles |access-date=November 21, 2012}}</ref> ''Trilogy'' was later certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and double-platinum by [[Music Canada]] in May 2013.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22THE%20WEEKND%22 |title=Gold & Platinum Searchable Database |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |access-date=December 19, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Trilogy&sa=The+Weeknd&smt=0 |title=Gold and Platinum Search |publisher=[[Music Canada]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927064324/http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Trilogy&sa=The+Weeknd&smt=0 |archive-date=September 27, 2013 |access-date=December 21, 2012}}</ref> He had also gained a nomination for the [[Sound of...|Sound of 2013]] poll award by the [[BBC]] a week later.<ref name=\"so13\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p010q6bc/profiles/theweeknd |title=Sound of 2013 Profiles: The Weeknd |date=December 9, 2012 |publisher=BBC |access-date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Weeknd at Massey Hall October 17, 2013 amber lighting.jpg|thumb|Tesfaye performing at [[Massey Hall]] in October 2013.]]\nOn May 16, 2013, Tesfaye premiered the [[Kiss Land (song)|title track]] to his debut studio album ''[[Kiss Land]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/05/listen-the-weeknd-kiss-land |title=Listen: The Weeknd \"Kiss Land\" |last=Nostro |first=Lauren |date=May 16, 2013 |access-date=May 17, 2013}}</ref> and announced the album's release date as September 10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://idolator.com/7472491/the-weeknd-kiss-land-release-date-cover-artwork |title=The Weeknd Unveils 'Kiss Land' Release Date & Cover Artwork |last=Williott |first=Carl |date=July 22, 2013 |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |access-date=July 22, 2013}}</ref> The album was later promoted by the singles \"[[Belong to the World]]\" and \"[[Live For]]\" featuring [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], as well as with Tesfaye embarking on The Fall tour a week prior to the album's release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisgoesin.com/2013/07/the-weeknds-kiss-land-arrives-on-august-27th-belong-to-the-world-snippet-news/ |title=The Weeknd's 'Kiss Land' Arrives on August 27th, \"Belong to the World\" Snippet |date=July 13, 2013 |publisher=ThisGoesIn |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723110346/http://www.thisgoesin.com/2013/07/the-weeknds-kiss-land-arrives-on-august-27th-belong-to-the-world-snippet-news/ |archive-date=July 23, 2013 |access-date=July 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Live-For-feat-Drake/dp/B00EP54R5U |title=Amazon.com: Live For [feat. Drake] [Clean]: The Weeknd: MP3 Downloads |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Upon release, ''Kiss Land'' debuted at number two on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 96,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695587/keith-urban-edges-the-weeknd-for-no-1-debut-on-billboard-200 |title=Keith Urban Edges The Weeknd for No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 |date=December 1, 2012 |website=Billboard |access-date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> It was later confirmed to have sold over 273,000 copies in the United States, as well as receiving generally positive reviews from music critics.<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/kiss-land/the-weeknd |title=Kiss Land Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |access-date=September 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye appeared on [[the 20/20 Experience World Tour]], joining headline act [[Justin Timberlake]] for six shows.<ref name=\"jttour\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5778176/the-weeknd-to-open-for-justin-timberlake-on-2020-experience-tour |title=The Weeknd To Open For Justin Timberlake On '20/20 Experience' Tour |last=Payne |first=Chris |date=November 4, 2013 |website=Billboard |access-date=November 27, 2015}}</ref> This was three weeks prior to his contributions to the [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013), contributing \"Devil May Cry\", as well as featuring on [[Sia (singer)|Sia]]'s \"[[Elastic Heart]]\". The latter proved to be the second lead single from the soundtrack.<ref name=\"hunger-cos\">{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/11/album-review-various-artists-the-hunger-games-catching-fire-soundtrack/ |title=Album Review: Various Artists \u2013 The Hunger Games: Catching Fire Soundtrack |last=Hakimian |first=Rob |date=November 19, 2013 |website=Consequence of Sound |access-date=December 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"amazon sia\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Elastic-Heart-From-Hunger-Games/dp/B00FHU3G6I/ |title=Elastic Heart (From \"The Hunger Games: Catching Fire\" Soundtrack) [feat. The Weeknd, Diplo]: Sia |access-date=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Tesfaye remixed \"[[Drunk in Love]]\", a single by [[Beyonc\u00e9]] from her [[Beyonc\u00e9 (album)|eponymous studio album]]. Retaining the theme and concept of the song, he detailed the synopsis through the perspective of a male.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/audio-beyonces-drunk-love-kanye-681039 |title=[Audio] Beyonce's 'Drunk in Love': Kanye West, The Weeknd Release Remixes |last=Lee |first=Ashley |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> The remix was well-received, and came days prior to the announcement of Tesfaye's first headlining tour, entitled the King of the Fall tour. The tour was held across the United States in September and October, and saw [[Schoolboy Q]] and [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] as supporting acts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/archives/2014/06/the_weeknd_tour_1.html |title=The Weeknd touring w/ Schoolboy Q & Jhene Aiko, playing Barclays Center (dates); SBQ played Central Park |access-date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> This oversaw his release of the single \"[[Often]]\", leading to speculation it was the first single from his second studio album.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/entry/view/id/44925 |title=Ida Maria Gets Exclamatory |website=Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on Idolator.com}}</ref> He later collaborated with [[Ariana Grande]] on a duet titled \"[[Love Me Harder]]\", which peaked at number seven on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/10/03/first-look-ariana-grande-the-weeknd-love-me-harder-video/ |title=Ariana Grande and The Weeknd Team Up In 'Love Me Harder' Video |website=Rap-Up |access-date=October 4, 2014}}</ref> Days later, he released \"[[Earned It]]\", a single from ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]'' (2015). This marked his second contribution to a movie, and peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n===2015: ''Beauty Behind the Madness''===\n{{main|Beauty Behind the Madness}}\nAfter Tesfaye won the Centric Award at the [[BET Awards 2015|2015 BET Awards]], he performed \"Earned It\" with [[Alicia Keys]], as well as debuting the song \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60165-janelle-monae-performs-yoga-the-weeknd-performs-earned-it-with-alicia-keys-at-the-bet-awards/ |title=Janelle Mon\u00e1e Performs \"Yoga\", The Weeknd Performs \"Earned It\" with Alicia Keys at the BET Awards |last=Beauchemin |first=Molly |website=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] |access-date=June 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/05/weeknd-debuts-new-song-the-hills.html |title=The Weeknd Returns With 'The Hills,' Which Probably Isn't About Lauren Conrad |last=Lockett |first=Dee |website=Vulture |access-date=May 27, 2015 |ref=vulture-hills}}</ref> \"The Hills\" was later released for digital download, and debuted at number twenty on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The single later went on to top the chart, marking Tesfaye's first number-one single.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.billboard.com/entry/view/id/139265 |title=The Weeknd |website=Billboard |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> The single was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\nOn June 8, \"[[Can't Feel My Face]]\", a previously leaked track, was released as the album's third single, following its performance at the [[Apple Inc.|Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]].<ref name=\"RS1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-the-weeknds-funky-new-song-cant-feel-my-face-20150608 |title=Hear The Weeknd's Funky New Song 'Can't Feel My Face' |last=Kreps |first=Daniel |date=June 8, 2015 |website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |access-date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> The song debuted at number twenty-four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and reached number-one on the Hot 100, making it his third top 10 hit, and his second number-one hit in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6613247/wiz-khalifa-no-1-hot-100-selena-gomez-debuts |title=Wiz Khalifa No. 1 on Hot 100 'Again,' Selena Gomez Debuts at No. 9 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 1, 2015 |website=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6656820/the-weeknd-no-1-hot-100-cant-feel-my-face-one-direction-drag-me-down |title=The Weeknd Tops Hot 100 With 'Can't Feel My Face,' One Direction Debuts at No. 3 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> He occupied all three slots on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]]'' [[Hot R&B Songs]] chart simultaneously with the aforementioned singles, becoming the first artist in history to accomplish this.<ref name=\"alone\">[http://music.cbc.ca/#!/blogs/2015/7/Alone-on-the-podium-The-Weeknd-becomes-first-artist-to-take-over-Billboard-RB-chart \"Alone on the podium: The Weeknd becomes first artist to take over Billboard R&B chart\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301002442/http://music.cbc.ca/#!/blogs/2013/6/Rear-view-Mirror-Who-was-Suzanne-and-why-did-Leonard-Cohen-make-her-famous |date= March 1, 2016 }}. [[CBC Music]], July 17, 2015.</ref> He headlined FVDED in the Park, a festival in [[Surrey, British Columbia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thisisblueprint.com/news/tickets/fvded-in-the-park-2015-announced |title=FVDED in the Park 2015 Announced |publisher=thisisblueprint.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926222507/http://thisisblueprint.com/news/tickets/fvded-in-the-park-2015-announced# |archive-date=September 26, 2015 |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> Tesfaye was unveiled as one of the musical faces of the streaming service [[Apple Music]], a position he harbored with frequent collaborator Drake.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-apples-new-musical-faces---drake-and-the-weeknd-2015-6 |title=Apple's new musical faces - Drake and The Weeknd |access-date=June 8, 2015}}</ref> During the [[2015 MTV Video Music Awards]], Apple debuted a two-part promotional commercial featuring Tesfaye, which had a guest appearance from [[John Travolta]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/15/08/31/latest-apple-music-ads-debut-during-mtv-vmas-feature-the-weeknd-playlists |title=Latest Apple Music ads debut during MTV VMAs, feature The Weeknd & playlists |access-date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> It was revealed that his second studio album would be titled ''Beauty Behind the Madness''.\n\n''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' was released on August 28, 2015, and debuted atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], earning 412,000 album equivalent units in its first week.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6685947/the-weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-debuts-at-no-1-billboard-200-charts |title=The Weeknd's 'Beauty Behind the Madness' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart |website=Billboard |access-date=September 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6700714/the-weeknd-billboard-200-third-week-no-1 |title=The Weeknd spends third week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 |website=Billboard |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> It reached the top 10 in over ten countries, as well as reaching number one in Canada, Australia, Norway, and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-the-weeknd-takes-top-spot-on-australian-chart-20150905 |title=ARIA Albums : The Weeknd Takes Top Spot On Australian Chart |publisher=Noise11 |access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musiccanada.com/charts/#albums |title=Top 20 Albums |website=USA Today |access-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> The album was promoted by Tesfaye headlining various summer music festivals, including [[Lollapalooza]], the Hard Summer Music Festival, and the [[Bumbershoot]] Festival.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/07/10/weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-august-28-release/29961285/ |title=The Weeknd's new album is coming Aug. 28 |website=USA Today |access-date=July 15, 2015}}</ref> He announced [[The Madness Fall Tour|his first large-scale tour]] across the United States, which began in November, and concluded in December.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60875-the-weeknd-announces-the-madness-fall-tour/ |title=The Weeknd announces The Madness Fall Tour |website=Pitchfork |access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6671102/the-weeknd-the-madness-fall-tour-dates |title=The Weeknd Announces The Madness Fall Tour With Travi$ Scott, Halsey & Banks |website=Billboard |access-date=August 21, 2015}}</ref> The album went double platinum in the US, and sold 1.5&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"IFPI2016\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2016.pdf |title=Global Music Report |date=April 12, 2016 |publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] |access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> It was reported to be the most-streamed album throughout 2015, with over 60 million,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6778065/spotify-year-music-lists-2015-drake-rihanna-major-lazer-ed-sheeran |title=Spotify's Year in Music: Drake Most Streamed Artist, Major Lazer & DJ Snake Had Top Song |website=Billboard}}</ref> as well as being ranked on multiple lists concerned with detailing albums of the year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2015-20151201/the-weeknd-beauty-behind-the-madness-20151130 |title=The Weeknd, 'Beauty Behind the Madness' |website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8, Tesfaye became the first male artist to have simultaneously held the top three spots on the Billboard Hot R&B Songs chart, with the three singles that preceded the release of his album. They all went platinum in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6685989/the-weeknd-hot-100-top-three |title=The Weeknd Doubles Up in Hot 100's Top Three |website=Billboard |access-date=August 8, 2015}}</ref> After engaging in multiple musical collaborations with [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/Music/article/belly-might_not_ft_weeknd |title=Belly 'Might Not' (ft. The Weeknd) |website=Exclaim! |access-date=May 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Meek Mill]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.34353/title.meek-mill-reveals-dreams-worth-more-than-money-features |title=Meek Mill Reveals 'Dreams Worth More Than Money' Features |publisher=hiphopdx |access-date=June 22, 2015}}</ref> and [[Travis Scott (musician)|Travis Scott]],<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7606572/demi-lovato-the-weeknd-perform-saturday-night-live-season-41 |title=Demi Lovato & The Weeknd To Perform On 'Saturday Night Live' This Season |publisher=Idolator |access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2352303/justin-bieber-kanye-west-the-weeknd-more-featuring-on-travis-scott-s-rodeo-album/ |title=Justin Bieber, Kanye West, The Weeknd, & more featuring on Travi$ Scott's 'Rodeo\" album |publisher=Inquisitr |access-date=August 20, 2015}}</ref> Tesfaye was featured on \"[[Low Life (song)|Low Life]]\", the triple platinum single from [[Future (rapper)|Future's]] [[EVOL (Future album)|fourth studio album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kiss925.com/2015/12/27/listen-the-weeknd-surprises-fans-by-dropping-two-new-songs/ |title=Listen: The Weeknd Surprises Fans By Dropping Two New Songs! |date=December 27, 2015 |website=Kiss 92.5 |access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye appeared on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' alongside actress [[Amy Schumer]], performing as the show's musical guest on October 10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6685066/weeknd-demi-lovato-snl-musical-guests |title=The Weeknd & Demi Lovato Announced as 'SNL' Musical Guests |website=Billboard |access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref> This was his first performance on the show as a solo artist, after appearing with [[Ariana Grande]] to perform \"Love Me Harder\".<ref name=\"Idolator\" />\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Starboy'' and ''My Dear Melancholy''===\n{{main|Starboy (album)|My Dear Melancholy}}\n\nTesfaye was featured on \"FML\", a track on [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[The Life of Pablo]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kanyewest.com/credits/ |title=Archived copy |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fMFARK1V?url=http://www.kanyewest.com/credits/ |archive-date=February 17, 2016 |access-date=February 17, 2016}}</ref> It marked the second collaboration between the pair, with West providing production and writing on \"[[Tell Your Friends (song)|Tell Your Friends]]\" from ''Beauty Behind the Madness''. Tesfaye appeared on \"[[6 Inch]]\", the fifth song on [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]''. He was announced by [[Spotify]] as being among the top five most streamed artists in their first year partnering with [[Sony]] to provide the streaming service on the [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.spotify.com/us/2016/04/15/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstationmusic/ |title=Spotify and PlayStation Celebrate One Year Together and Hit More Than Five Billion Streams on PlayStation Music |website=Spotify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423181523/https://news.spotify.com/us/2016/04/15/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstationmusic/ |archive-date=April 23, 2016 |access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.scoop.it/topic/music-news-for-orange/p/4062765549/2016/04/19/spotify-and-playstation-celebrate-one-year-together-and-hit-more-than-five-billion-streams-on-playstation-music |title=Spotify and PlayStation\u00ae Celebrate One Year Together and Hit More Than Five Billion Streams on PlayStation\u2122Music &#124; Music News |website=Scoop.it}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, in preparation for his third studio album, [[Republic Records]] executive vice-president Wendy Goldstein confirmed Tesfaye began collaborations with French electronic music duo [[Daft Punk]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/the-weeknd-working-with-daft-punk |title=The Weeknd Is Reportedly Working with Daft Punk |date=August 23, 2016 |access-date=August 23, 2016}}</ref> On the same day, Tesfaye also announced a collaboration with Norwegian record producer [[Cashmere Cat]], titled \"[[Wild Love (Cashmere Cat song)|Wild Love]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Morris |first=Jesse |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/08/the-weeknd-previews-cashmere-cat-collaboration |title=It Sounds Like a Weeknd and Cashmere Cat Collab Is on the Way |date=August 24, 2016 |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> A month later, the previously mentioned album's title was announced as ''Starboy'', and had a release date of November 25.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/67755-the-weeknd-announces-new-album-starboy/ |title=The Weeknd Announces New Album Starboy |last=Pearce |first=Sheldon |date=September 21, 2016 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> He released the album's [[Starboy (song)|title track]], which features Daft Punk on September 21. The song received platinum certification and went to number one in the United States, as well as in various other countries.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/sep/22/hear-the-weeknds-new-track-with-daft-punk-starboy |title=Hear the Weeknd's new track with Daft Punk, Starboy |date=September 22, 2016 |work=The Guardian |access-date=September 22, 2016 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> A second collaboration with Daft Punk, entitled \"[[I Feel It Coming]]\", was released a week proceeding the album's release, alongside the solo efforts \"[[Party Monster (song)|Party Monster]]\" and \"[[False Alarm (The Weeknd song)|False Alarm]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dancingastronaut.com/2016/09/daft-punk-the-weeknd-collaboration-listen/ |title=Listen to Daft Punk's new collaboration with The Weeknd, 'Starboy' |last=Zwilling |first=Eric |date=September 21, 2016 |website=Dancing Astronaut |access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye returned to ''Saturday Night Live'' on October 10, performing \"Starboy\" and \"False Alarm\". He released a 12-minute short film, titled ''M A N I A'', on November 23.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBsycvSU6r8 |title=Watch The Weeknd \u2013 Mania on YouTube |date=November 23, 2016 |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=March 2, 2017}}</ref> Directed by Grant Singer, it featured excerpts from the album, including snippets from \"[[All I Know (The Weeknd song)|All I Know]]\" featuring [[Future (rapper)|Future]], \"[[Sidewalks (song)|Sidewalks]]\" featuring [[Kendrick Lamar]], \"[[Secrets (The Weeknd song)|Secrets]]\" and \"[[Die for You (The Weeknd song)|Die for You]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/69997-watch-the-weeknds-new-short-film-mania/ |title=Watch The Weeknd's New Short Film Mania |date=November 23, 2016 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:The Weeknd with hand in the air performing live in Hong Kong in November 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Tesfaye performing live in Hong Kong in November 2018.]]\nIn 2017, Tesfaye appeared on [[Hndrxx|Future's sixth studio album]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7701959/future-album-hndrxx-the-weeknd-rihanna |title=Future Releases New Album 'HNDRXX' Featuring The Weeknd and Rihanna: Listen |last=Brandle |first=Lars |website=Billboard |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> as well as on the [[Some Way|debut single]] from [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]], who was signed by [[XO (record label)|XO]] in January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-the-weeknds-sultry-some-way-collaboration-with-nav-w467422 |title=Hear the Weeknd's Sultry 'Some Way' Collaboration With Nav |last=Blistein |first=John |website=Rolling Stone |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> He became the first feature utilized by [[Lana Del Rey]], appearing on \"[[Lust for Life (Lana Del Rey song)|Lust for Life]]\", the title track and second single from [[Lust for Life (Lana Del Rey album)|her fifth studio album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.much.com/lana-del-rey-lust-for-life-the-weeknd/ |title=Lana Del Rey Releases 'Lust For Life' Single with the Weeknd |last=Bowsher |first=Allison |website=Much.com |access-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> He was featured on [[French Montana]]'s \"[[A Lie]]\", the third single from his second album ''[[Jungle Rules]]'' and on [[Cashmere Cat]]'s debut single \"Wild Love\" from his album ''[[9 (Cashmere Cat album)|9]]''. He appeared on the [[Virgil Abloh]]-directed music video for [[Lil Uzi Vert]]'s \"[[XO Tour Llif3]]\" alongside XO signee [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]]. He was later featured on [[Luv Is Rage 2|Lil Uzi Vert's debut album]] and [[Gucci Mane]]'s eleventh studio album ''[[Mr. Davis]].'' He gained a Grammy nomination for [[Best Urban Contemporary Album]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards]] for ''Starboy'' and ended up winning the award.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/entertainment-pmn/newsalert-starboy-wins-best-urban-contemporary-album-for-the-weeknd |title=NewsAlert: Starboy winds best urban contemporary album for the Weeknd |date=January 28, 2018 |work=National Post |access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2018, [[Top Dawg Entertainment]] revealed the full tracklist of the [[Kendrick Lamar]]-curated [[Black Panther (soundtrack)|''Black Panther'' soundtrack album]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/1/tde-black-panther-soundtrack-cover-tracklist |title=TDE Reveals Loaded Tracklist for 'Black Panther' Soundtrack |last=Boykins |first=Austin |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> with Tesfaye featured on one of the tracks, [[Pray for Me (The Weeknd and Kendrick Lamar song)|\"Pray for Me\"]]. On February 2, 2018, it was released as the soundtrack's third single. This marks the second collaboration between Tesfaye and Lamar, after the song [[Sidewalks (song)|\"Sidewalks\"]] on the [[Starboy (album)|''Starboy'']] album.\n\nOn March 27, 2018, Tesfaye began publicity for a new official release in an Instagram post.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8263214/the-weeknd-new-album-instagram |title=Is The Weeknd Dropping a New Album on Friday? |work=Billboard |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vibe.com/2018/03/the-weeknd-dropping-album-rumor-report/ |title=Is The Weeknd Dropping A New Album This Week? |date=March 27, 2018 |work=Vibe |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/music/international/the-weeknd-teases-new-song-release-14133016 |title=The Weeknd teases new song release {{!}} IOL Entertainment |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> On March 29, 2018, a billboard appeared in [[London|London, England]] promoting a possible album titled ''My Dear Melancholy,''<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://clashmusic.com/news/has-someone-accidentally-leaked-news-of-the-weeknds-new-album |title=Has Someone Accidentally Leaked News of the Weeknd's New Album? |work=Clash Magazine |access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> and on the same day the project was officially announced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2018/03/the-weeknd-new-album-my-dear-melancholy-announcement/ |title=The Weekend Announces New Album 'My Dear Melancholy,' |last=Sargent |first=Jordan |date=March 29, 2018 |website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2018, the extended play ''[[My Dear Melancholy,]]'' was released.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/stream-the-weeknds-my-dear-melancholy-ep-news.46817.html |title=Stream The Weeknd's \"My Dear Melancholy\" EP |work=HotNewHipHop |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> On June 6, 2018, The Weeknd announced his new [[Beats 1]] radio show ''Memento Mori'', which's first episode was released two days later.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459680/the-weeknd-memento-mori-beats-one-radio-show |title=The Weeknd Announces New Beats 1 Radio Show Memento Mori |website=Billboard |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Later in the year, on November 21, 2018, the compilation album ''[[The Weeknd in Japan]]'' was released and served as his first [[greatest hits album]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.universal-music.co.jp/the-weeknd/products/uicu-1305/ |title=The Weeknd in Japan (Singles Collection) |publisher=[[Universal Music Group]] |language=Japanese |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8491268/the-weeknd-first-japan-concert-kenshi-yonezu |title=The Weeknd Performs First Japan Show With Special Guest Kenshi Yonezu |website=Billboard |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''After Hours''===\n{{Main|After Hours (The Weeknd album)}}\nIn January 2019, [[Gesaffelstein]] (who previously worked with Tesfaye on ''My Dear Melancholy,'') began teasing a new collaboration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=malQ597Kgq8 |title=Gesaffelstein on Youtube |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> On January 11, 2019, Tesfaye and Gesaffelstein released \"[[Lost in the Fire]]\", the second single off the latter's second studio album, ''[[Hyperion (Gesaffelstein album)|Hyperion]].''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-gesaffelstein-and-the-weeknds-new-song-lost-in-fire/ |title=Listen to Gesaffelstein and the Weeknd's New Song \"Lost in the Fire\" |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> On April 18, 2019, Tesfaye released \"[[Power Is Power]]\" alongside [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] and [[Travis Scott]], a song part of [[For the Throne: Music Inspired by the HBO Series Game of Thrones|a series of music]] inspired by the television show ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', of which Tesfaye himself is a fan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/sza-the-weeknd-travis-scott-power-is-power/ |title=SZAThe WeekndTravis Scott 'Power Is Power' |access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> On May 5, Tesfaye, [[SZA (singer)|SZA]] and [[Travis Scott]] released the music video for their ''[[Game of Thrones (season 8)|Game of Thrones]]''-inspired track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bbnews050619sza-8510131 |title=SZA, The Weeknd and Travis Scott Share Video For 'Game of Thrones' Inspired Track |date=May 5, 2019 |website=Billboard |access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref> On August 30, 2019, during the [[Telluride Film Festival]], Tesfaye made his debut cinematic appearance on the world premiere of the film ''[[Uncut Gems]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/film/weeknd-recorded-music-oneohtrix-point-never-intended-uncut-gems-2546398 |title=The Weeknd recorded music with Oneohtrix Point Never intended for 'Uncut Gems' |date=September 10, 2019 |access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 24, 2019, \"[[Blinding Lights]]\", the expected lead single of his fourth album, was announced via a [[Mercedes-Benz]] commercial on German television.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/24/the-weeknd-new-single-blinding-lights/ |title=The Weeknd to Release New Single 'Blinding Lights' on Black Friday |website=Rap-Up |access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref> The next day, footage of its music video being shot in [[Fremont Street]], [[Las Vegas]] surfaced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/11/25/the-weeknd-shooting-new-music-video-las-vegas/ |title=The Weeknd Shooting New Music Video in Las Vegas |website=TMZ |access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref> News outlets then began reporting that Tesfaye would follow up \"Blinding Lights\" with another single titled \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\".<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1199113637912350720 |user=TheAffinityMag |title=\ud83d\udea8 NEW MUSIC FROM @theweeknd \ud83d\udea8 Abel is dropping 'Blinding Lights' TOMORROW and 'Heartless' on Wednesday. Who's excited?! \ud83e\udd29 |date=November 25, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> After having covered the aforementioned singles on November 25, 2019, the following day, news outlets reported that Tesfaye had registered a song titled \"Like Selena\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a29988087/the-weeknd-selena-gomez-like-selena-song-rumor/ |title=Looks Like The Weeknd Is Releasing a Song About Selena Gomez |last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |date=November 26, 2019 |website=ELLE}}</ref> which was reported to have been possibly named after the singer's ex-girlfriend [[Selena Gomez]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2019/11/the-weeknd-releasing-new-single-titled-like-selena-about-gomez/ |title=The Weeknd Releasing New Single Titled 'Like Selena' About Gomez |date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> In promotion of the upcoming album, episode seven of The Weeknd's ''Memento Mori'' Beats 1 radio show was released on November 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://i.redd.it/fcwg6cv283141.jpg |title=Screenshots of Instagram Story on November 26, 2019 |publisher=YouTube Music |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126214534/https://i.redd.it/fcwg6cv283141.jpg |archive-date=November 26, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The single \"Heartless\" went on to debut at number 32 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and later became his fourth number one single on the chart, the following week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545288/the-weeknd-heartless-five-burning-questions |title=Five Burning Questions: Billboard Staffers Discuss The Weeknd's Top 40 Debut For 'Heartless' |website=Billboard |access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> With \"Blinding Lights\" debuting at number 11 on the chart when the aforementioned single topped the chart, and then reaching the top ten on the issue dated February 29, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8551757/the-box-tops-hot-100-7th-week |title=Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Tops Hot 100 For Seventh Week; Dua Lipa Hits Top 5; Justin Bieber, The Weeknd Go Top 10 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=February 24, 2020 |website=Billboard |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545778/the-weeknd-heartless-no-1-hot-100 |title=The Weeknd's 'Heartless' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100, Mariah Carey's 'All I Want for Christmas Is You' Returns to No. 3 High |website=Billboard |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Tesfaye revealed the album's title, ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'', and release date, March 20, 2020, on February 19, 2020, and released the album's [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] as a promotional single simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8551359/the-weeknd-after-hours-release-date-title-track-release |title=The Weeknd Sets 'After Hours' Release Date, Shares Dark Title Track: Listen |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=February 19, 2020 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the album was released on March 20, 2020, containing the singles \"Heartless\", \"Blinding Lights\" and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours/|title=Listen to the Weeknd\u2019s New Album After Hours|last=Strauss|first=Matthew|date=March 20, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the album release, on March 29, 2020, Tesfaye announced the release of three more previously unreleased songs: \"Nothing Compares\", \"Missed You\" and \"Final Lullaby\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/1244332030508199936|title=nothing compares, missed you, final lullaby...|via=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesfayes album ''After Hours'' had a second consecutive week at No. 1 on the Hot 100 Songwriters chart (April 2020), due to five entries on the latest ''Billboard'' Hot 100 (singles), all of which he co-wrote and co-produced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9353926/the-weeknd-songwriters-chart-30roc-producers |title=The Weeknd also repeats at No. 1 on the Billboard 200, Hot 100 & Artist 100 |date=April 8, 2020 |website=billboard.com |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\n\nTesfaye cites [[Michael Jackson]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and [[R. Kelly]] as his main musical inspirations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ca.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |title=The Weeknd: Kiss And Tell (2013 Cover Story) |last=Scott |first=Damien |date=July 15, 2013 |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |access-date=June 9, 2015}}</ref> He has attributed Jackson's music as key in spurring him to be a singer, referencing the lyrics to \"[[Dirty Diana]]\" as an example.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He also said his high-flying vocal style was influenced by [[habesha]] singers like [[Aster Aweke]].<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He grew up listening to a variety of music genres, including [[Soul music|soul]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[funk]], [[indie rock]], and [[post-punk]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberts |first=Randall |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/17/entertainment/la-et-ms-weeknd-review-20121217 |title=Review: Abel Tesfaye, a.k.a. The Weeknd, has hall smoldering |date=December 17, 2012 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Tesfaye has said: \"I've always had an admiration for the era before I was born. You can hear it as far back as my first mixtape that the '80s -- [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Cocteau Twins]] -- play such a huge role in my sound.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Weeknd Worried Album Release was Insensitive|publisher=[[Sioux City Journal]] |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402133801/https://siouxcityjournal.com/people/the-weeknd-worried-album-release-was-insensitive/article_2d374595-cb75-5d45-8fc5-bef91ab613ef.html|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye's songs are \"built around a fogged, [[crepuscular]] production\",<ref name=\"Hoby\">{{Cite news |last=Hoby |first=Hermione |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |title=The Weeknd: Sounds and sensibility |date=November 8, 2012 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=January 6, 2013 |location=London |at=section G2, p. 12}}</ref> and feature slow [[tempo]]s,<ref name=\"Cohen\" /> rumbling bass, and forlorn echoes.<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Tesfaye often sings in a [[falsetto]] register,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/12/rookie-of-the-year-2011/ |title=Rookie of the Year: The Weeknd |last=Robbins |first=Winston |date=December 7, 2011 |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> exhibiting an enticing tone. [[J. D. Considine]] finds his singing's \"[[Tremolo|tremulous]] quality\" similar to Michael Jackson, but writes that he eschews Jackson's \"strong basis in the [[blues]]\" for a more [[Arabic music|Arabic]]-influenced [[melisma]].<ref name=\"Considine\" /> Tesfaye possesses a wide light-lyric [[tenor]] vocal range, which spans over three octaves. His vocal range reaches its extreme low at the bass F (F2), and its peak high at the tenor G\u266f (G\u266f5), with a natural [[tessitura]] within the upper fourth octave.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://therangeplace.boards.net/thread/2513/weeknd |title=The Weeknd {{!}} The Range Place |website=therangeplace.boards.net |access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> Tesfaye often makes use of his [[head voice]] in order to build resonance to belt out strong high notes within the fifth octave.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/singing/comments/4a5h7t/how_is_the_weeknd_abel_testaye_singing/ |title=r/singing - How is The Weeknd (Abel Testaye) singing? |website=reddit |access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> His music incorporates [[Sampling (music)|samples]] that are unconventional in R&B production, including [[Punk rock|punk]] and [[alternative rock]].<ref name=\"Considine\">{{Cite news |last=Considine |first=J. D. |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/how-the-weeknd-became-rbs-next-big-thing/article5370329/ |title=How The Weeknd became R&B's next big thing |date=November 17, 2012 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=January 19, 2013 |location=Toronto |author-link=J. D. Considine}}</ref> Marc Hogan of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' says that Tesfaye's samples tend \"to draw from [[rockism|rock critic-approved]] sources, though generally ones that already share elements of his sexual menace\", with samples of artists such as [[Beach House]], Siouxsie and the Banshees and [[Aaliyah]].<ref name=\"Hogan\">{{Cite journal |last=Hogan |first=Marc |date=October 26, 2012 |title=The Weeknd Imbues 'Enemy' With the Smiths' Seductive Power |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/10/the-weeknd-enemy-the-smiths/ |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |location=New York |access-date=January 19, 2013}}</ref> Tesfaye worked mostly with producers [[Illangelo]] and [[Doc McKinney]], whom ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''{{'}}s Ian Cohen credits with developing \"a state-of-the-art [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] template\" with the artist.<ref name=\"Cohen\">{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17280-the-trilogy/ |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy |last=Cohen |first=Ian |date=November 13, 2012 |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> In concert, Tesfaye reappropriates his digitized productions with a [[Suite (music)|suite]]-like [[arena rock]] aesthetic.<ref name=\"Mistry\" />\n\nHis emotional, plaintive lyrics often express feelings of hurt and deal with subject matter such as sex,<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> drugs, and partying.<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Hermione Hoby of ''[[The Guardian]]'' characterizes Tesfaye's songs as \"narcotised-[[slow jam]]s\" and delineates their message as \"partying is an existential experience, sex is fraught with alienation, and everything registers as unreal and unsettling\".<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> ''The Guardian''{{'}}s Paul MacInnes has stated that he views Tesfaye's three [[mixtapes]] as \"a rough trajectory of party, after-party and [[hangover]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/15/the-weeknd-trilogy-review |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy \u2013 review |date=November 15, 2012 |work=The Guardian |access-date=January 6, 2013 |location=London |at=section G2, p. 23}}</ref> Anupa Mistry of the ''[[Toronto Standard]]'' observes throughout his mixtapes a \"cast of supine, stoned zombie-women ... whose legs willingly part after being plied with substances and who morph into threats only when [he is] [[Comedown (drugs)|coming down]] and feeling vulnerable\".<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> Tesfaye has viewed that, by singing vulgar, ignorant lyrics in an elegant, sexy way, he is paying homage to R. Kelly and Prince.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/07/15/the-weeknds-kiss-land-album-captures-first-experiences-outside-of-toronto/ |title=The Weeknd's Kiss Land Album Captures First Experiences Outside Of Toronto |last=Morgan |first=Nakiya |date=July 15, 2013 |publisher=MTV News |access-date=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye has helped broaden R&B's musical palette to incorporate [[Indie music|indie]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] styles; his work has been categorized with the [[alternative R&B]] tag.<ref name=\":2\">Billboard Staff. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6813596/grammys-2016-preview-best-r-and-b-song-best-urban-contemporary-album-nominees-the-weeknd-dangelo-more \"Grammys 2016 Preview: The Weeknd, D'Angelo and More Soulful Singers Nominated for Best R&B Song and Best Urban Contemporary Album\"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard ]]''. February 13, 2016.</ref> Mistry writes that he \"will be obsequiously praised as the future of R&B music\u2014because [he] is a black singer, not because he's making quantifiable, canonical R&B\".<ref name=\"Mistry\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Andy Kellman categorizes him as an \"alternative R&B act\".<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162 |title=The Weeknd \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |last=Kellman |first=Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> While promoting his third album ''Starboy'', Tesfaye also revealed [[Lana Del Rey]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interview/9711-the-dark-knight-returns-a-conversation-with-the-weeknd/1 |title=The Dark Knight Returns: A Conversation With the Weeknd |last=Mistry |first=Anupa |date=August 31, 2015 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> [[David Bowie]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-weeknd-talks-david-bowie-prince-influences-on-new-album-w448191 |title=The Weeknd Talks David Bowie, Prince Influences on New Album |last=Reed |first=Ryan |date=November 2, 2016 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> [[The Smiths]], [[Bad Brains]], [[Talking Heads]], [[DeBarge]],<ref name=\"bruce\">{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknds_new_album_is_inspired_by_bad_brains_talking_heads_and_the_smiths |title=The Weeknd's New Album Is Inspired by Bad Brains, Talking Heads and the Smiths |last=Slingerland |first=Calum |date=February 6, 2016 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |access-date=September 6, 2016}}</ref> [[50 Cent]], the [[Wu-Tang Clan]],<ref>Sources:\n\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/50-cent-wu-tang-influenced-the-weeknds-starboy-album/ |title=50 Cent and Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album Read More: 50 Cent, Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album |last=Schwadron |first=Eli |website=Xxl |access-date=May 9, 2017}}\n*{{cite web|title=12 Great Songs That Wouldn't Exist Without the Weeknd|authors=Suzy Exposito, Keith Harris, Anupa Mistry, Nick Murray, Brittany Spanos|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 21, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/12-great-songs-that-wouldnt-exist-without-the-weeknd-20151021/drake-hold-on-were-going-home-2013-20151021|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> and [[Eminem]] as influences.<ref>Sources:\n\n*{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W0b6RGdLqTM |title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Crashed Jay Z on 'Renegade,' Talks \"The Hills\" Remix (Nov 24, 2016)}}\n*{{cite web|title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Destroyed 'The Hills' Remix and Jay Z on 'Renegade'|url=http://www.southpawer.com/2016/11/25/the-weeknd-eminem-jay-z-renegade-the-hills-interview/|website=Southpawer|accessdate=November 26, 2016|date=November 25, 2016}}\n*{{cite web|title=The Weeknd on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/653673994240004100?lang=en|website=Twitter|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Business ventures==\nDuring the American leg of his Fall tour promoting ''[[Kiss Land]]'', Tesfaye collaborated with condom-producing company ONE to give away limited-edition condoms at his shows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/52443-the-weeknd-giving-away-kiss-land-condoms/ |title=The Weeknd Giving Away Kiss Land Condoms |last=Battan |first=Carrie |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> They featured the visual identity of the new album with Oxcy \u2013 the album's mascot \u2013 printed on one side.\n\nIn November 2015, to further promote ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'', Tesfaye collaborated with [[Pax Labs]] to release a limited edition version of the PAX 2 vaporizer, an [[electronic cigarette]] that could be used in shows during [[The Madness Fall Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/103135/20151104/weeknd-launches-vape-plays-hit-single-hills-smoke.htm |title=The Weeknd Launches A Vape That Plays His Hit Single 'The Hills' As You Smoke |last=Keating |first=Lauren |date=November 4, 2015 |website=Tech Times |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> The e-cigarette featured the \"xo\" branding on the front, as well as having the ability to play \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\" when turned on.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://porhomme.com/2015/11/the-weeknd-gets-limited-version-of-pax-2-vaporizer/ |title=The Weeknd Gets Limited Version of Pax 2 Vaporizer |date=November 13, 2015 |website=Por Homme |publisher=Pausr Media LLC |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> With the original PAX 2 priced at $279.99, the limited edition e-cigarette cost $324.99.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.joesdaily.com/gear/pax-2-is-a-refined-and-durable-vaporizer-unlike-any-other/ |title=PAX 2 is a Refined and Durable Vaporizer Unlike Any Other |last=Miragliotta |first=Joe |date=February 4, 2016 |website=GQ |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> PAX also acted as an official sponsor for the tour, presenting special backstage VIP activations for fans who bought packages that included the e-cigarette.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sidewalkhustle.com/pax-labs-x-the-weeknd-presents-the-madness-tour-limited-edition-pax-2/ |title=Pax Labs X The Weeknd Presents The Madness Tour Limited Edition Pax 2 |last=Banning |first=Tristan |website=Sidewalk Hustle |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"theverge.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/11/4/9663712/the-weekend-pax-labs-vaporizer-limited-edition |title=The Weeknd is teaming up with Pax Labs to create the ultimate fashion vape |last=Cox |first=Jamieson |date=November 4, 2015 |website=The Verge |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> PAX Labs chief marketing officer Richard Mumby stated \"Music and fashion have always been a natural fit for Pax...This was the perfect opportunity to bring together The Weeknd's style with our technology.\"<ref name=\"theverge.com\" />\n\nIn 2016, Tesfaye announced a partnership with [[Puma SE|Puma]], as a Global Brand ambassador, for the company's \"Run the Streets\" campaign. It was launched in early November, with the final collection made available to coincide with the release of his album ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/style/2016/09/the-weeknd-partners-puma-creative-collaborator-ambassador |title=The Weeknd Partners With Puma as New Creative Collaborator and Ambassador |last=Mench |first=Chris |website=Complex |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> He also hosted several [[pop-up retail]] stores for the \"Starboy: Limited Capsule\" collection,<ref name=\"bustle.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-are-the-weeknds-pop-up-shops-if-you-live-in-one-of-these-eight-cities-youre-in-luck-55779 |title=Where Are The Weeknd's Pop-Up Shops? If You Live in One Of These Eight Cities, You're in Luck |last=Tucker |first=Alexa |website=Bustle |access-date=May 6, 2017}}</ref> which were available across [[North America]], including [[New York City]], [[Los Angeles]], and [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/style/2017/05/the-weeknd-starboy-2-5-united-states-canada-pop-up-shops-lookbook |title=Here's Your First Look at the Weeknd's Starboy 2017 Pop-Up Shop Collection |last=Espinoza |first=Joshua |website=Complex |access-date=May 6, 2017}}</ref> With this partnership, Tesfaye also released three capsule collections named PUMA X XO including T-shirts, caps, sweatpants, bomber jackets and a pair of shoes called the Parallels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/8/the-weeknd-puma-parallel-sneaker-collection |title=The Weeknd and PUMA Officially Unveil Their \"Parallel\" Sneaker |website=Hypebeast |publisher=Hypebeast}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/11/he-weeknd-x-puma-xo-collection-nyc |title=A Closer Look at The Weeknd x PUMA XO Collection Launch in NYC |website=Hypebeast |publisher=Hypebeast}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye has also begun his own XO branded merchandise, which was furthered by a collaboration with [[H&M]] to present its Spring 2017 campaign. The campaign would feature new collaborative pieces developed with the singer's brand, and was released on March 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.hm.com/en_cn/life/culture/inside-h-m/the-weeknd-teams-with-h-m-on-curated-mens-collection.html |title=The Weeknd Teams With H&M on Curated Men's Collection |website=H&M |publisher=Hennes & Mauritz}}</ref> Tesfaye collaborated with H&M again for a fall collection, however, after an incident which he described as \"deeply offensive\" in 2018, he cut ties with the company.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-cuts-ties-with-hm-over-deeply-offensive-photo/ |title=The Weeknd Cuts Ties With H&M Over \"Deeply Offensive\" Photo |last=Yoo |first=Noah |website=Pitchfork |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Tesfaye had a limited edition [[Pop-up retail|pop up]] sale for the \"Starboy 2017 Limited Capsule Collection\".<ref name=\"bustle.com\" /> The collections were available in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Miami Beach, Houston, Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nTesfaye has collaborated with artists and designers such as Kidult, [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/11/wangxo-apparel |title=HYPEBEAST Exclusive: WANGXO Apparel Collection |last=Hasse |first=Lemola |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> and [[Futura (graffiti artist)|Futura]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/4/the-weeknd-futura-xo-capsule-better-look |title=A Better Look at The Weeknd and Futura's Limited-Edition XO Capsule Collection |last=Sajonas |first=Felson |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> for small-lived and sometimes exclusive capsule collections.\n\nIn October 2017, Tesfaye began marketing and promotion on a partnership with [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] on [[Instagram]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/10/the-weeknd-cryptic-image-marvel-collaboration |title=The Weeknd Teases a Cryptic Image Hinting Towards a Collaborative Project With Marvel |last=Patos |first=Robert |website=Hypebeast |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> A week later, he attended [[New York Comic-Con]] and it was revealed that a [[Starboy (song)|Starboy]] comic book would be released on June 13, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/10/the-weeknd-marvel-to-release-starboy-comic-book/ |title=THE WEEKND TEAMS UP WITH MARVEL TO RELEASE 'STARBOY' COMIC BOOK |last=Coleman II |first=C. Vernon |website=XXL |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> with the title character being a superhero modelled after himself.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8257745/marvel-the-weeknd-starboy-comic-book-release-date |title=Marvel Unveils 'The Weeknd Presents: Starboy' Comic Book Release Date |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[XO (record label)|XO]] released a collection of apparel in collaboration with [[A Bathing Ape]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/bape-x-xo |title=BAPE\u00ae x XO |website=us.bape.com |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/the-weeknd-bape-summer-2018-capsule/ |title=The Weeknd x BAPE Summer Capsule Collection Dropping August 4 |date=July 30, 2018 |website=Highsnobiety  |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> They released another collection in January 2020. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-xo-bape-collection/ |title=The Weeknd Reveals Latest XO And BAPE Capsule Collection {{!}} uDiscover |last=Stavropoulos |first=Laura |date=January 8, 2020 |website=uDiscover Music |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Tesfaye bought ownership in [[esports]] company OverActive Media Group, the owners of [[Splyce]] and [[Overwatch League]] team [[Toronto Defiant]], and will serve as the company's [[Brand ambassador|global ambassador]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/weeknd-overactive-overwatch-1.5091861 |title=The Weeknd signs on as part owner, global ambassador of esports firm |date=April 10, 2019 |access-date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTesfaye began dating model [[Bella Hadid]] at the beginning of 2015; the couple were first seen together in May at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style-blog/wp/2015/09/11/kylie-jenner-and-bella-hadid-are-18-their-boyfriends-are-25-why-do-their-relationships-elicit-such-different-reactions/ |title=Kylie Jenner and Bella Hadid are 18. Their boyfriends are 25. Why do their relationships elicit such different reactions |last=McDonald |first=Soraya Nadia |date=September 11, 2015 |website=The Washington Post |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a31091/bella-hadid-19th-birthday/ |title=Bella Hadid Spends Her Birthday Weekend with the Weeknd |last=Lindig |first=Sarah |date=October 10, 2015 |website=Elle |access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref> Hadid later starred in his music video \"[[In the Night (The Weeknd song)|In the Night]]\" in December. They also made a [[red carpet]] appearance as a couple at the [[2016 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.popsugar.com/celebrity/Weeknd-Bella-Hadid-Grammys-2016-40199219#photo-40199219 |title=The Weeknd and Bella Hadid Made Their Red Carpet Debut at the Grammys |last=Sisavat |first=Monica |website=Popsugar Celebrity |access-date=June 6, 2016}}</ref> On November 11, 2016, it was reported that the couple had split; citing their conflicting schedules as the rationale for the relationship's termination.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.com/music/the-weeknd-bella-hadid-split/ |title=The Weeknd and Bella Hadid Have Split: 'They Still Have a Great Deal of Love for One Another' |last=Tracy |first=Brianne |website=People |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye reportedly started dating [[Selena Gomez]] in January 2017 and they moved in together temporarily in September 2017 in [[Greenwich Village, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://people.com/music/everything-we-know-selena-gomez-weeknd/ |title=Everything We Know About Selena Gomez and The Weeknd's Whirlwind Romance |last=Yagoda |first=Maria |date=May 25, 2017 |website=People |access-date=September 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/exclusive-selena-gomez-and-weeknd-temporarily-move-apartment-together-new-york-city-86975 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Selena Gomez and The Weeknd Temporarily Move Into an Apartment Together in New York City |last=Murphy |first=Desiree |date=September 11, 2017 |website=Entertainment Tonight |access-date=September 12, 2017}}</ref> They broke up in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chiu |first=Melody |url=http://people.com/music/selena-gomez-the-weeknd-breakup/ |title=Selena Gomez and The Weeknd Split After 10 Months Together |date=October 30, 2017 |work=People |access-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref> By May 2018, Tesfaye and Hadid began dating again,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/music/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-second-outing-cannes-film-festival/ |title=Bella Hadid and The Weeknd Let Loose at Cannes Film Festival 1 Day After Kissing |last=Paasquini |first=Maria |date=May 12, 2018 |website=People |access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> before splitting again in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a28625896/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-breakup-2019-reason/ |title=Why Bella Hadid and The Weeknd Reportedly Broke Up for the Second Time |date=August 6, 2019 |website=Elle}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye often used drugs to help get over [[writer's block]] on earlier albums and also abused illegal substances such as \"... Ketamine, cocaine, MDMA, mushrooms and cough syrup\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/weeknd-opens-dark-past/story?id=43987671 |title=The Weeknd Opens Up About His 'Dark' Past |last=Fisher |first=Luchina |date=December 5, 2016 |publisher=ABC News |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Speaking in December 2013, Tesfaye said that drugs were a \"crutch\" for him when it came to writing music.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/weeknd-opens-drug-use-1888046 |title=The Weeknd opens up about 'heavy' drug use - NME |date=December 3, 2016 |work=NME |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> On [[social media]] he typically suffixed his first name with \"xo\".<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> According to writer Hermione Hoby, it is meant as an [[emoticon]] for \"[[hugs and kisses|a kiss and a hug]]\",<ref name=\"Hoby\" /> while [[VH1]]'s Zara Golden's stated that it is a reference to his recreational use of [[ecstasy (drug)|ecstasy]] and [[oxycodone]].<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-11-16/who-is-the-weeknd-5-things-you-should-know |title=Who Is The Weeknd? 5 Things You Should Know |last=Golden |first=Zara |date=November 16, 2012 |publisher=[[VH1]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127024250/http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-11-16/who-is-the-weeknd-5-things-you-should-know |archive-date=January 27, 2013 |access-date=August 16, 2013}}</ref> He later altered the handles on his social media to reflect his stage name in preparation for the release of ''Starboy''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.torchonline.com/entertainment/arts-culture/2012/02/21/the-weeknd-is-ready-for-take-off/ |title=The Weeknd is ready for take-off |last=Dow |first=Gabriele |website=the Torch |publisher=St. John's University |access-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTesfaye's hairstyle has been claimed to be partly inspired by [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]] and has been described as his most recognizable trait.<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> In an interview, he detailed that he began growing it out in 2011, and remarked at the easiness in maintaining it, with \"a hard shampoo every once in a while\".<ref name=\"RSinterview\" /> He eventually cut his hair in 2016 prior to the release of [[Starboy (album)|''Starboy'']].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7518696/80s-90s-artists-inspired-the-weeknd-new-haircut |title=5 '80s & '90s Artists Who May Have Inspired The Weeknd's New Haircut |website=Billboard |access-date=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his leisure time, he enjoys watching television<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama/ |title=The Weeknd Reveals How He Got His Name... And Where the 'E' Went |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |publisher=MTV |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> and is an avid video game fan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/15/madness-tour-the-weeknd-travis-scott-visonelie-photos |title=What It's Really Like To Be On Tour with the Weeknd And Travis Scott |last=Sowunmi |first=Jordan |website=Fader |access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitalxtra.com/features/pictures/best-instagram/27th-january/the-weeknd-playing-mario-kart/ |title=The Weeknd spent some time off playing Mario Kart. |website=CapitalXtra |access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref> In the context of media outlets reporting cases of police brutality, in 2016, he expressed disdain, tweeting \"blue lives murder\".<ref name=\"The Weeknd on Twitter\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/751143768833732608?lang=en |title=The Weeknd on Twitter |website=Twitter |access-date=May 5, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/theweeknd/status/751143486590623744?lang=en |title=The Weeknd on Twitter |website=Twitter |access-date=May 5, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-6-1194305 |title=The Weeknd has donated $250,000 to Black Lives Matter |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=August 14, 2016 |website=Time |access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref> In May 2016, Tesfaye and [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] cancelled an appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' due to [[Donald Trump]] being present.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/culture/2016/05/27/3782672/weeknd-400-prominent-writers-protest-donald-trump/ |title=Trump Inspires The Weeknd To Cancel Jimmy Kimmel Performance |last=Goldstein |first=Jessica |website=Thinkprogress |publisher=CENTER FOR AMERICAN PROGRESS ACTION FUND |access-date=May 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legal issues===\nIn January 2015, Tesfaye was arrested for punching a [[Las Vegas Police Department|Las Vegas]] police officer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6436581/the-weeknd-arrested-for-punching-las-vegas-police-officer |title=The Weeknd Arrested For Punching Las Vegas Police Officer |last=Stutz |first=Colin |website=Billboard |access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> Tesfaye pleaded [[no contest]], and was sentenced to 50 hours of [[community service]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/10/22/the-weeknd-no-contest-punching-cop/ |title=The Weeknd Pleads No Contest To Punching a Cop |website=TMZ |access-date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2015, Tesfaye was sued by Cutting Edge Music, who alleged that the [[bass line]] for \"[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]\" had been taken from a composition featured in the score for ''[[The Machine (film)|The Machine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tmz.com/2015/12/09/the-weeknd-the-hills-lawsuit/ |title=THE WEEKND SUED OVER 'THE HILLS' |website=Tmz |access-date=May 12, 2017}}</ref> In September 2018, Tesfaye and [[Daft Punk]] were sued for allegedly stealing the rhythm from a self-described poet, singer and songwriter named Yasminah.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/09/18/the-weeknd-daft-punk-lawsuit-starboy-stolen/ |title=The Weeknd and Daft Punk Sued for Stealing 'Starboy' |website=TMZ}}</ref> Tesfaye has denied these allegations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-denies-stealing-starboy-beat-from-somali-american-singer-news.80542.html |title=The Weeknd Denies Stealing \"Starboy\" Beat From Somali-American Singer |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nPrior to being presented a Bikila Award for Professional Excellence in 2014, Tesfaye donated $50,000 towards a class at the [[University of Toronto]] on [[Ge'ez]], the classic language of Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carissimo |first=Justin |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-the-university-of-toronto-to-help-start-an-ethiopic-studies-program-a7177606.html |title=The Weeknd donates $50,000 to language class at the University of Toronto |date=August 7, 2016 |access-date=August 7, 2016 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In August 2016 he continued donations to the University of Toronto, in the creation of a new [[Ethiopian Studies|Ethiopic Studies]] program.<ref name=\"Time\" />\n\nIn May 2016 Tesfaye has also donated $50,000 for the St. Mary Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church in Toronto, Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ethiosports.com/2016/05/02/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-st-mary-ethiopian-orthodox-church-in-toronto/ |title=The Weeknd Donates $50,000 To St. Mary Ethiopian Orthodox Church in Toronto |last=Lockett |first=Dee |date=May 2, 2016 |website=Ethiosports |publisher=Samuel Yeshiwas}}</ref> In August 2016, Tesfaye also donated $250,000 to [[Black Lives Matter]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/11/the-weeknd-black-lives-matter-beyonce-jay-z-drake |title=The Weeknd gives $250,000 to Black Lives Matter |date=August 11, 2016 |website=The Guardian |access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Time\" /> In December 2015, he worked with [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s foundation to visit [[Children's Healthcare of Atlanta|Children's Hospital in Atlanta]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theybf.com/2015/12/17/the-weeknd-does-charity-work-amidst-cheating-rumors-do-gooder-2-chainz-donates-minivan-to |title=The Weeknd Does Charity Work Amidst Cheating Rumors + Do-Gooder 2 Chainz Donates Minivan To Family With Brain Damaged Son |last=Natasha |website=Young, Black & Fabulous |access-date=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Tesfaye donated $100,000 to the Suubi Health Center, a maternity and children's medical facility in Budondo, Uganda. Tesfaye was inspired to support the center after learning of his friend [[French Montana]]'s work with Global Citizen and Mama Hope to help raise awareness for Suubi and the people of Uganda.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/858296/the-weeknd-donates-100-000-to-health-center-in-uganda |title=The Weeknd Donates $100,000 to Health Center in Uganda |access-date=January 9, 2018 |publisher=E!}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd}}\nTesfaye has won three [[Grammy Award]]s, eight [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], two [[American Music Award]]s, nine [[Juno Award]]s,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |last=Bell |first=David |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/junos-sunday-night-1.3517082 |title=The Weeknd really cleaned up this Juno Awards weekend |date=April 3, 2016 |access-date=March 2, 2017 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> and has been nominated for one [[Academy Award]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|The Weeknd discography}}\n<!-- Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works\". Studio albums only. -->\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Kiss Land]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' (2020)\n<!-- STUDIO ALBUMS ONLY! Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works\". -->\n\n== Tours ==\n* King of the Fall Tour (2014)\n* [[The Madness Fall Tour]] (2015)\n* [[Starboy: Legend of the Fall Tour]] (2017)\n* [[The Weeknd Asia Tour]] (2018)\n* [[The After Hours Tour]] (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikimedia|collapsible=true|c=Category:The Weeknd|d=Q2121062|voy=no|v=no|species=no|wikt=no|b=no|s=no|n=no}}\n* {{official website|http://www.theweeknd.com}}\n\n{{The Weeknd}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Weeknd|Awards for The Weeknd]]\n|list =\n{{Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporany Album}}\n{{Juno Award for Artist of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Canada|Music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weeknd}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Amharic-language singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ethiopian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian record producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Canadian tenors]]\n[[Category:Singers with a three-octave vocal range]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Single of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Republic Records artists]]\n[[Category:XO (record label)]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Artist of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for R&B/Soul Recording of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Songwriter of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:People involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:The Weeknd| ]]\n", "name_user": "ToxiBoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Update author of story", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Weeknd"}
{"title_page": "Jon Macken", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jon Macken\n|          image = JonMacken02.jpg\n|     image_size = 200\n|        caption = Macken in 2007\n|       fullname = Jonathan Paul Macken\n|         height = \n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|9|7|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Blackley]], England\n|       position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n|    youthyears1 = 1995\u20131996 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1996\u20131997 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]    |caps1 = 0   |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 1997\u20132002 |clubs2 = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]    |caps2 = 189 |goals2 = 63\n|         years3 = 2002\u20132005 |clubs3 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]        |caps3 = 51  |goals3 = 7\n|         years4 = 2005\u20132007 |clubs4 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]          |caps4 = 25  |goals4 = 2\n|         years5 = 2006\u20132007 |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] (loan)     |caps5 = 14  |goals5 = 3\n|         years6 = 2007\u20132008 |clubs6 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]              |caps6 = 11  |goals6 = 0\n|         years7 = 2007      |clubs7 = \u2192 [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (loan)             |caps7 = 11  |goals7 = 3\n|         years8 = 2008\u20132010 |clubs8 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]                      |caps8 = 94  |goals8 = 18\n|         years9 = 2010\u20132012 |clubs9 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]                        |caps9 = 76  |goals9 = 21\n|        years10 = 2012\u20132013 |clubs10 = [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] |caps10= 7   |goals10= 2\n|        years11 = 2013      |clubs11 = [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]     |caps11= 13  |goals11= 1\n|        years12 = 2015      |clubs12 = [[Bamber Bridge F.C.|Bamber Bridge]]           |caps12= 1   |goals12= 0\n|  manageryears1 = 2017\u20132020 |managerclubs1 = [[Radcliffe Borough F.C.|Radcliffe Borough]]\n|      totalcaps = 491 | totalgoals = 120\n| nationalyears1 = 1997 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]            |nationalcaps1 = 1 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2004 |nationalteam2 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] |nationalcaps2 = 1 |nationalgoals2 = 0\n|    club-update = 15:06, 14 April 2013 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Jonathan Paul Macken''' (born 7 September 1977 in [[Blackley]], Manchester) is an English [[association football|football]] manager and former player who played as a [[forward (association football)|striker]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 1995 but was released two years later after failing to make a first-team appearance. He joined [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] for \u00a3250,000 and managed to notch up 63 goals in 189 league matches until his departure to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2002. Macken eventually made his first Premier League appearance for City. He only managed to score seven goals in 51 appearances during his three years with City but notably scored against United in the [[Manchester derby]] in 2004. He signed for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in 2005 and while there, moved to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on loan. In 2007, he moved again to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] but was loaned out to [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] after failing to make an impact at [[Pride Park]] where he failed to score in 11 league appearances. He joined Barnsley permanently in 2008 and moved again to [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] two years later. He was released by The Saddlers at the end of the 2011\u201312 season and joined [[Northern Premier League]] side [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]], before joining [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] briefly in 2013.\n\nHe has one international cap for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] which he earned in 2004 whilst a Manchester City player.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Preston North End===\nMacken began his career at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and signed professional in 1996, but never played a first-team game for them and left on 22 July 1997 in a \u00a3250,000<ref name=LEP>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lep.co.uk/sport/football/the-big-interview-ex-pne-striker-jon-macken-1-5917688|title=THE BIG INTERVIEW: Ex-PNE striker Jon Macken|website=www.lep.co.uk}}</ref> move to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in 1997.\n\nHe scored over 70 goals at Preston, twice winning the [[Preston North End Player of the Year Award Winners|Player of the Year]] award. In 1999-2000, under [[David Moyes]], 25 goals from Macken saw Preston win the Second Division title.<ref name=LEP/>\n\n===Manchester City===\nFollowing this success, Macken moved into the [[Premier League]] with a transfer to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in February 2002, for a fee of \u00a35&nbsp;million.<ref name=LEP/> He is most remembered at City for scoring the winner in the 4-3 comeback win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in the [[2003\u201304 FA Cup]] on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3447235.stm|title=Tottenham 3\u20134 Man City|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=4 February 2004 |accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> However, he was severely hampered by a succession of injuries, and only made 27 league starts in over three years. This downturn in his career brought about a move away from Manchester and Macken joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in the summer of 2005 for \u00a31.1&nbsp;million.\n\n===Crystal Palace===\nInitially, Macken did not get into the Palace team, and was behind England international [[Andrew Johnson (English footballer)|Andrew Johnson]] and Republic of Ireland international [[Clinton Morrison]]. An injury to Johnson gave him a chance, initially, but then he himself got injured. His own replacement, [[Dougie Freedman]] showed good form, and despite a recovery from injury, Macken did not get back in the team.\n\nHowever, things turned upwards from there. Poor form by Morrison in the run-up to the Christmas period gave Macken his chance, and he scored his first competitive goal for Palace in the game at [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], on 14 October 2005 (he had previously scored in a pre-season friendly), and scored again on 26 December, at [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], although he was later sent off.\n\nMore injuries then continued to limit his chances, and the partnership with Johnson continued to alternate between Morrison and Dougie Freedman, with many fans voicing their discontent that Macken was not living up to his price-tag. Johnson was sold to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], prompting the return of [[S\u00e1ndor Torghelle]] to the club from his loan at [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], creating speculation that Macken may be leaving the club, but the appointment of [[Peter John Taylor|Peter Taylor]] as manager appeared to silence this. Taylor, a known fan of Macken, had reportedly tried to sign him for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull]], while he was in charge there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fansfc.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225920/http://www.fansfc.com/frontpage/frontpagenews.asp?newsid=151339|url-status=dead|title=fansfc.com domain name is for sale. Inquire now.|archivedate=26 September 2007|website=www.fansfc.com}}</ref>\n\nTorghelle left permanently for Greece, but again his playing opportunities were limited. On deadline-day of the Summer 2006 transfer window, he made a further move to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in [[Football League Championship|The Championship]], this time on loan, being handed the number 27 shirt. The loan was finally agreed when Ipswich agreed to pay an increased proportion of his wages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipswichtown.rivals.net/default.asp?sid%3D911%26p%3D2%26stid%3D8421531 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060714021011/http://ipswichtown.rivals.net/default.asp?sid=911 |archivedate=14 July 2006 }}</ref> Macken scored three goals for the Tractor Boys before returning to [[Selhurst Park]].\n\n===Derby County===\n\nOn 31 January 2007 Macken joined [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on a free transfer. Derby were promoted to the Premier League at the end of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season, but he failed to win a regular place, or even score for The Rams, and was loaned out to [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] for two months in November 2007. Although he was recalled on 27 December 2007<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnsley/7072907.stm|title=Barnsley bag Rams striker Macken|date=1 November 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> he eventually signed a permanent deal with the Tykes on 28 January 2008 for an undisclosed six-figure fee.\n\n===Barnsley===\n\nMacken initially joined Barnsley on 1 November 2007, on loan from [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]. He made his debut against the club that made his name, [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]. He remained goalless for his first nine games, despite having produced a string of fine performances. On 22 December, he scored his first Barnsley goal against promotion chasing [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] after a fine run and shot.\n\nThe goals were flowing for Macken and he notched a brace against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 26 December. First a header from a [[Martin Devaney]] corner. His second goal came courtesy of a [[Kayode Odejayi]] knock-down from another Devaney cross. He then returned to Derby after [[Paul Jewell]] took over.\n\nHe made a couple of substitute appearances for the Rams but his inevitable return to Barnsley was secured on 28 January 2008 for \u00a3200,000.\n\nThe next day, he marked his return with a fine finish in the home game with [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]]. He bagged the second goal in a 2\u20131 win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 9 February and he was again on the scoresheet as the Reds thrashed [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 11 March.\n\nHe was released by Barnsley after the 2009\u201310 season and left when his contract expired in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnsley/8658308.stm|title=Hugo Colace offered new contract|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=3 May 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Walsall===\n\nOn 19 August 2010, League One club Walsall signed Macken on a one-year deal with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_6323775,00.html |title=Saddlers seal double deal |publisher=Sky Sports |date=19 August 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010 }}</ref> On 9 May 2012 it was announced that Macken had been released by Walsall.\n\n===Northwich Victoria===\n\nOn 9 October 2012 it was reported that Macken had signed for [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.northwichvics.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=796:mutch-signs-experienced-striker-jon-macken&catid=35:club-announcements&Itemid=107]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]], as an 80th-minute substitute, that evening.<ref>[http://www.northwichvics.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=798:newcastle-town-1-1-northwich-victoria&catid=51:match-reports-2012-2013]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Stockport County===\nOn 31 January 2013, it was announced by Stockport County that Jon Macken had signed until the end of the 2012\u201313 season on a free transfer. Along with [[Mark Cullen (English footballer)|Mark Cullen]] and [[Jake Fowler]], he was the first signing by new manager [[Darije Kalezi\u0107]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21285332|title=Jon Macken, Mark Cullen & Jake Fowler join Stockport County|date=31 January 2013|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nMacken made his Stockport debut as a second-half substitute in County's 3\u20132 home win over [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Town]] on 2 February. He scored his first goal for the club against rivals [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 30 March. Following their relegation from the [[Conference National]], he was released.\n\n===Bamber Bridge===\nOn 24 February 2015, Macken came out of retirement to sign for Bamber Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Macken joins Brig |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/sport/non-league/macken-joins-brig-1-7124203 |work=Lancashire Evening Post |publisher=Johnston Publishing |date=24 February 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2015 }}</ref> He made his debut in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Darlington 1883]] on 28 February.<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Stoddart |title=Darlington take three much-needed points |url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/11825659.Darlington_take_three_much_needed_points/ |work=The Northern Echo |publisher=Newsquest (North East) |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== International==\n\nMacken represented the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20 team]] at the [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship]], earning one cap.\n\nHe then went on to represent the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] at full international level, playing once on 18 August 2004 in a friendly 1-1 home draw with [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], coming on for [[Clinton Morrison]] after 63 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/republic_of_ireland/3578028.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128022326/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/republic_of_ireland/3578028.stm |archivedate=28 January 2018 |title=Rep of Ireland 1-1 Bulgaria |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 August 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=11|title=Rep. of Ireland v Bulgaria football match, 18 August 2004|website=eu-football.info}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn September 2017 he was appointed as manager of non-league club [[Radcliffe Borough F.C.|Radcliffe Borough]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Stoddart |title=Macken Coup For Radcliffe Borough |url=http://nonleague.pitchero.com/headlines/macken-coup-radcliffe-borough/|work=Non League Pitchero |publisher= |date=17 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017 }}</ref>  He left the club in January 2020 citing differences over the future direction of the club.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lord |first1=Adam |title=\"The club and I were no longer aligned\": Jon Macken departs Radcliffe |url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/18169306.ex-manchester-city-man-jon-macken-departs-radcliffe-boss/ |publisher=Bury Times |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Preston North End'''\n*[[Football League Second Division]] (1): [[1999\u20132000 Football League#Second Division|1999\u20132000]] \n'''Derby County'''\n*[[Football League Championship play-offs]] (1): [[2007 Football League Championship play-off Final|2007]]\n\n'''Awards'''\n*Preston North End Player of the Year (1): [[2000\u201301 Preston North End F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n*Football League Second Division Team of the Year (1): [[1999\u20132000 Football League#Second Division|1999\u20132000]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Republic of Ireland international footballers born outside the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080517022314/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10309~8823,00.html Jon Macken profile] at barnsleyfc.co.uk\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{1999\u20132000 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Preston North End F.C. Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macken, Jon}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Blackley]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northwich Victoria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bamber Bridge F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland international footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Jon Macken\n|          image = JonMacken02.jpg\n|     image_size = 200\n|        caption = Macken in 2007\n|       fullname = Jonathan Paul Macken\n|         height = \n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|9|7|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Blackley]], England\n|       position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n|    youthyears1 = 1995\u20131996 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1996\u20131997 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]    |caps1 = 0   |goals1 = 0\n|         years2 = 1997\u20132002 |clubs2 = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]    |caps2 = 189 |goals2 = 63\n|         years3 = 2002\u20132005 |clubs3 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]        |caps3 = 51  |goals3 = 7\n|         years4 = 2005\u20132007 |clubs4 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]          |caps4 = 25  |goals4 = 2\n|         years5 = 2006\u20132007 |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] (loan)     |caps5 = 14  |goals5 = 3\n|         years6 = 2007\u20132008 |clubs6 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]              |caps6 = 11  |goals6 = 0\n|         years7 = 2007      |clubs7 = \u2192 [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (loan)             |caps7 = 11  |goals7 = 3\n|         years8 = 2008\u20132010 |clubs8 = [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]                      |caps8 = 94  |goals8 = 18\n|         years9 = 2010\u20132012 |clubs9 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]                        |caps9 = 76  |goals9 = 21\n|        years10 = 2012\u20132013 |clubs10 = [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] |caps10= 7   |goals10= 2\n|        years11 = 2013      |clubs11 = [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]     |caps11= 13  |goals11= 1\n|        years12 = 2015      |clubs12 = [[Bamber Bridge F.C.|Bamber Bridge]]           |caps12= 1   |goals12= 0\n|  manageryears1 = 2017\u20132020 |managerclubs1 = [[Radcliffe Borough F.C.|Radcliffe Borough]]\n|      totalcaps = 491 | totalgoals = 120\n| nationalyears1 = 1997 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]            |nationalcaps1 = 1 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2004 |nationalteam2 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] |nationalcaps2 = 1 |nationalgoals2 = 0\n|    club-update = 15:06, 14 April 2013 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Jonathan Paul Macken''' (born 7 September 1977 in [[Blackley]], Manchester) is an English [[association football|football]] manager and former player who played as a [[forward (association football)|striker]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 1995 but was released two years later after failing to make a first-team appearance. He joined [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] for \u00a3250,000 and managed to notch up 63 goals in 189 league matches until his departure to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2002. Macken eventually made his first Premier League appearance for City. He only managed to score seven goals in 51 appearances during his three years with City but notably scored against United in the [[Manchester derby]] in 2004. He signed for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in 2005 and while there, moved to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on loan. In 2007, he moved again to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] but was loaned out to [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] after failing to make an impact at [[Pride Park]] where he failed to score in 11 league appearances. He joined Barnsley permanently in 2008 and moved again to [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] two years later. He was released by The Saddlers at the end of the 2011\u201312 season and joined [[Northern Premier League]] side [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]], before joining [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] briefly in 2013.\n\nHe has one international cap for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] which he earned in 2004 whilst a Manchester City player.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Preston North End===\nMacken began his career at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and signed professional in 1996, but never played a first-team game for them and left on 22 July 1997 in a \u00a3250,000<ref name=LEP>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lep.co.uk/sport/football/the-big-interview-ex-pne-striker-jon-macken-1-5917688|title=THE BIG INTERVIEW: Ex-PNE striker Jon Macken|website=www.lep.co.uk}}</ref> move to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in 1997.\n\nHe scored over 70 goals at Preston, twice winning the [[Preston North End Player of the Year Award Winners|Player of the Year]] award. In 1999-2000, under [[David Moyes]], 25 goals from Macken saw Preston win the Second Division title.<ref name=LEP/>\n\n===Manchester City===\nFollowing this success, Macken moved into the [[Premier League]] with a transfer to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in February 2002, for a fee of \u00a35&nbsp;million.<ref name=LEP/> He is most remembered at City for scoring the winner in the 4-3 comeback win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in the [[2003\u201304 FA Cup]] on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3447235.stm|title=Tottenham 3\u20134 Man City|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=4 February 2004 |accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> However, he was severely hampered by a succession of injuries, and only made 27 league starts in over three years. This downturn in his career brought about a move away from Manchester and Macken joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in the summer of 2005 for \u00a31.1&nbsp;million.\n\n===Crystal Palace===\nInitially, Macken did not get into the Palace team, and was behind England international [[Andrew Johnson (English footballer)|Andrew Johnson]] and Republic of Ireland international [[Clinton Morrison]]. An injury to Johnson gave him a chance, initially, but then he himself got injured. His own replacement, [[Dougie Freedman]] showed good form, and despite a recovery from injury, Macken did not get back in the team.\n\nHowever, things turned upwards from there. Poor form by Morrison in the run-up to the Christmas period gave Macken his chance, and he scored his first competitive goal for Palace in the game at [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], on 14 October 2005 (he had previously scored in a pre-season friendly), and scored again on 26 December, at [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], although he was later sent off.\n\nMore injuries then continued to limit his chances, and the partnership with Johnson continued to alternate between Morrison and Dougie Freedman, with many fans voicing their discontent that Macken was not living up to his price-tag. Johnson was sold to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], prompting the return of [[S\u00e1ndor Torghelle]] to the club from his loan at [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], creating speculation that Macken may be leaving the club, but the appointment of [[Peter John Taylor|Peter Taylor]] as manager appeared to silence this. Taylor, a known fan of Macken, had reportedly tried to sign him for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull]], while he was in charge there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fansfc.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225920/http://www.fansfc.com/frontpage/frontpagenews.asp?newsid=151339|url-status=dead|title=fansfc.com domain name is for sale. Inquire now.|archivedate=26 September 2007|website=www.fansfc.com}}</ref>\n\nTorghelle left permanently for Greece, but again his playing opportunities were limited. On deadline-day of the Summer 2006 transfer window, he made a further move to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in [[Football League Championship|The Championship]], this time on loan, being handed the number 27 shirt. The loan was finally agreed when Ipswich agreed to pay an increased proportion of his wages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipswichtown.rivals.net/default.asp?sid%3D911%26p%3D2%26stid%3D8421531 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060714021011/http://ipswichtown.rivals.net/default.asp?sid=911 |archivedate=14 July 2006 }}</ref> Macken scored three goals for the Tractor Boys before returning to [[Selhurst Park]].\n\n===Derby County===\n\nOn 31 January 2007 Macken joined [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on a free transfer. Derby were promoted to the Premier League at the end of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season, but he failed to win a regular place, or even score for The Rams, and was loaned out to [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] for two months in November 2007. Although he was recalled on 27 December 2007<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnsley/7072907.stm|title=Barnsley bag Rams striker Macken|date=1 November 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> he eventually signed a permanent deal with the Tykes on 28 January 2008 for an undisclosed six-figure fee.\n\n===Barnsley===\n\nMacken initially joined Barnsley on 1 November 2007, on loan from [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]. He made his debut against the club that made his name, [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]. He remained goalless for his first nine games, despite having produced a string of fine performances. On 22 December, he scored his first Barnsley goal against promotion chasing [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] after a fine run and shot.\n\nThe goals were flowing for Macken and he notched a brace against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 26 December. First a header from a [[Martin Devaney]] corner. His second goal came courtesy of a [[Kayode Odejayi]] knock-down from another Devaney cross. He then returned to Derby after [[Paul Jewell]] took over.\n\nHe made a couple of substitute appearances for the Rams but his inevitable return to Barnsley was secured on 28 January 2008 for \u00a3200,000.\n\nThe next day, he marked his return with a fine finish in the home game with [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]]. He bagged the second goal in a 2\u20131 win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 9 February and he was again on the scoresheet as the Reds thrashed [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 11 March.\n\nHe was released by Barnsley after the 2009\u201310 season and left when his contract expired in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnsley/8658308.stm|title=Hugo Colace offered new contract|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=3 May 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Walsall===\n\nOn 19 August 2010, League One club Walsall signed Macken on a one-year deal with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_6323775,00.html |title=Saddlers seal double deal |publisher=Sky Sports |date=19 August 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010 }}</ref> On 9 May 2012 it was announced that Macken had been released by Walsall.\n\n===Northwich Victoria===\n\nOn 9 October 2012 it was reported that Macken had signed for [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.northwichvics.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=796:mutch-signs-experienced-striker-jon-macken&catid=35:club-announcements&Itemid=107]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Newcastle Town F.C.|Newcastle Town]], as an 80th-minute substitute, that evening.<ref>[http://www.northwichvics.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=798:newcastle-town-1-1-northwich-victoria&catid=51:match-reports-2012-2013]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Stockport County===\nOn 31 January 2013, it was announced by Stockport County that Jon Macken had signed until the end of the 2012\u201313 season on a free transfer. Along with [[Mark Cullen (English footballer)|Mark Cullen]] and [[Jake Fowler]], he was the first signing by new manager [[Darije Kalezi\u0107]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21285332|title=Jon Macken, Mark Cullen & Jake Fowler join Stockport County|date=31 January 2013|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nMacken made his Stockport debut as a second-half substitute in County's 3\u20132 home win over [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Town]] on 2 February. He scored his first goal for the club against rivals [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 30 March. Following their relegation from the [[Conference National]], he was released.\n\n===Bamber Bridge===\nOn 24 February 2015, Macken came out of retirement to sign for Bamber Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Macken joins Brig |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/sport/non-league/macken-joins-brig-1-7124203 |work=Lancashire Evening Post |publisher=Johnston Publishing |date=24 February 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2015 }}</ref> He made his debut in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Darlington 1883]] on 28 February.<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Stoddart |title=Darlington take three much-needed points |url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/11825659.Darlington_take_three_much_needed_points/ |work=The Northern Echo |publisher=Newsquest (North East) |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== International==\n\nMacken represented the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20 team]] at the [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship]], earning one cap.\n\nHe then went on to represent the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] at full international level, playing once on 18 August 2004 in a friendly 1-1 home draw with [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], coming on for [[Clinton Morrison]] after 63 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/republic_of_ireland/3578028.stm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128022326/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/republic_of_ireland/3578028.stm |archivedate=28 January 2018 |title=Rep of Ireland 1-1 Bulgaria |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 August 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=11|title=Rep. of Ireland v Bulgaria football match, 18 August 2004|website=eu-football.info}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn September 2017 he was appointed as manager of non-league club [[Radcliffe Borough F.C.|Radcliffe Borough]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=Stoddart |title=Macken Coup For Radcliffe Borough |url=http://nonleague.pitchero.com/headlines/macken-coup-radcliffe-borough/|work=Non League Pitchero |publisher= |date=17 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017 }}</ref>  He left the club in January 2020 citing differences over the future direction of the club.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lord |first1=Adam |title=\"The club and I were no longer aligned\": Jon Macken departs Radcliffe |url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/sport/18169306.ex-manchester-city-man-jon-macken-departs-radcliffe-boss/ |publisher=Bury Times |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Preston North End'''\n*[[Football League Second Division]] (1): [[1999\u20132000 Football League|1999\u20132000]] \n'''Derby County'''\n*[[Football League Championship play-offs]] (1): [[2007 Football League Championship play-off Final|2007]]\n\n'''Awards'''\n*Preston North End Player of the Year (1): [[2000\u201301 Preston North End F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n*Football League Second Division Team of the Year (1): 2000\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Republic of Ireland international footballers born outside the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080517022314/http://www.barnsleyfc.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10309~8823,00.html Jon Macken profile] at barnsleyfc.co.uk\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{1999\u20132000 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Preston North End F.C. Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macken, Jon}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Blackley]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ipswich Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northwich Victoria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bamber Bridge F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland international footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Macken"}
{"title_page": "Thank You (1925 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1925 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thank You\n| image          = Thank You lobby card.jpg\n| caption        = Lobby card\n| director       = [[John Ford]]\n| producer       = [[John Golden]]\n| writer         = [[Frances Marion]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''Thank You''|[[Winchell Smith]] and [[Tom Cushing]]}}\n| starring       = [[Alec B. Francis]]<br>[[Jacqueline Logan]]\n| cinematography = [[George Schneiderman]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox|Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{film date|1925|11|1}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes \n| country        = United States \n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''Thank You''''' is a 1925 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[John Ford]]. The film is considered to be [[lost film|lost]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/T/ThankYou1925.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Thank You'' |accessdate=March 6, 2008|work=silentera.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.silentsaregolden.com/arnefox.html ''Thank You'' at Arne Andersen's Lost Film Files: ''Fox Films Studios'']</ref> This film is based on a 1921 Broadway play, ''Thank You'', by [[Winchell Smith]] and [[Tom Cushing]].<ref>[http://ibdb.com/production.php?id=12649 ''Thank You'' as produced on Broadway at the Longacre Theatre Oct. 3, 1921; IBDb.com]</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alec B. Francis]] as David Lee\n* [[Jacqueline Logan]] as Diane Lee\n* [[George O'Brien (actor)|George O'Brien]] as Kenneth Jamieson\n* [[J. Farrell MacDonald]] as Andy\n* [[George Fawcett]] as Cornelius Jamieson\n* [[Cyril Chadwick]] as Mr. Jones\n* Edith Bostwick as Mrs. Jones\n* Marion Harlan as Milly Jones\n* Vivia Ogden as Miss Blodgett\n* [[James Neill (actor)|James Neill]] as Doctor Cobb\n* Billy Rinaldi as Sweet, Jr.\n* Aileen Manning as Hannah\n* [[Maurice Murphy (actor)|Maurice Murphy]] as Willie Jones\n* Robert Milasch as Sweet, Sr.\n* Ida Moore as Gossiping Woman\n* Frankie Bailey as Gossiping Man\n* [[William Courtright]] (uncredited)\n* [[Richard Henry Cummings|Richard Cummings]] (uncredited)\n* Tommy Hicks as Fat kid (uncredited)\n* [[Francis Powers]] as Gossiping Man (uncredited)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0016417|title=Thank You}}\n*{{allmovie|113065|Thank You}}\n\n{{John Ford |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1925 films]]\n[[Category:1925 comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Ford]]\n[[Category:Fox Film films]]\n[[Category:Lost American films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Frances Marion]]\n[[Category:1920s lost films]]\n[[Category:Lost comedy films]]\n{{1920s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1925 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thank You\n| image          = Thank You lobby card.jpg\n| caption        = Lobby card\n| director       = [[John Ford]]\n| producer       = [[John Golden]]\n| writer         = [[Frances Marion]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''Thank You''|[[Winchell Smith]] and [[Tom Cushing]]}}\n| starring       = [[Alec B. Francis]]<br>[[Jacqueline Logan]]\n| cinematography = [[George Schneiderman]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox|Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{film date|1925|11|1}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes \n| country        = United States \n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''Thank You''''' is a 1925 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[John Ford]]. The film is considered to be [[lost film|lost]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=ht